<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Quebec-Blackout 1stLd-Writethru a0861 04-18 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quebec-Blackout, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0861,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Power Blackout Hits Quebec Province</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New info and changes throughout</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A widespread power failure Monday night blacked
out Quebec and parts of New Brunswick province, affecting millions
of people including some in scattered districts in Maine and
Vermont.
   Hydro Quebec, the provincial power utility, said the power
outage began at 8:09 p.m. EDT.
   Among the blackout victims was television coverage of the Adams
Division final game between the Montreal Canadiens and the Boston
Bruins of the National Hockey League. The game at the Montreal
Forum was interrupted in the first period but then continued with
the use of emergency lights. Montreal won 5-2.
   Hydro Quebec spokesman Jean-Guy Ouimet said the breakdown began
on a power line between Churchill Falls, Labrador, and the Arnaud
generating station near Sept-Iles, Quebec, but the cause was was
not known.
   ``The problem came from the Churchill Falls power house. For
some reason the power stopped coming'' and that caused an overload
on other lines, he said.
   Power was being restored in one area at a time, he added.
   Cities on the New York side of the border were not affected
because the state does not operate on the same system, according to
a spokesman for New York State Electric and Gas.
   In Montreal, street lights and traffic signals blinked out and
passengers were rescued from stalled subway trains. Hospitals used
emergency generating systems and said there were no serious
problems.
   Police reported no looting or other disturbances, but the armed
forces said military police patrols were reinforced at armories.
   Hydro Quebec and Bell Canada officials pleaded with people not
to use the strained telephone system, but many radio stations lost
their transmitting facilities and were unable to broadcast the
appeals.
   Gerry Morris, an official with the Vermont Electric Cooperative,
said about 800 homes in the Canaan and Norton areas were blacked
out for about an hour.
   The sale of Canadian hydropower to New England and New York has
become an important part of Quebec province's economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
