<1ST_LINE>u p AM-NewYorkPolls 2ndLd-Writethru a0807 04-18 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New York Polls, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0807,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Leads In Polls, But Jackson Still In Range</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf with 2 grafs to UPDATE with latest ABC poll;
SUBS penultimate graf with new ABC figure</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polls gave the lead to Gov. Michael Dukakis in
the last campaign day before New York's Democratic presidential
primary, but Jesse Jackson was within striking distance and turnout
was considered critical.
   While Dukakis led by 10 or more points, pollsters said to watch
the turnout Tuesday, particularly among non-Jewish whites, a
potential swing vote. If many stayed home, they said, Jackson could
come from behind.
   ``Nobody can predict for sure what the final combination of
blacks, Jews, Hispanics and white Catholics will be,'' said ABC
News pollster John Brennan. ``We could all be wrong. New York is a
killer.''
   Polling Monday by ABC and the Washington Post found Dukakis
holding the ground he gained Sunday after a dip Friday and
Saturday, while Jackson slid a bit. The combined Sunday-Monday
results gave Dukakis 51 percent and Jackson 34. The Friday-Saturday
totals had been 46-40.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Albert Gore Jr. had 9 percent in the final
ABC-Post poll, down from 11 percent Friday and Saturday.
   A CBS News survey Saturday and Sunday had a slightly narrower
spread, with Dukakis at 43 percent, Jackson at 33 and Gore at 12. A
Gallup poll done Friday through Sunday put the race at Dukakis 45,
Jackson 32 and Gore 10.
   The ABC-Post poll had a 6-point margin of error, CBS's 4,
Gallup's 5.
   Pollsters said Gore, after an upward blip late last week,
settled back to his previous, comparatively low level of support
and did not seem likely to draw enough votes to affect the outcome
greatly. Gore was up slightly in the CBS poll but down a tick in
the ABC-Post and Gallup polls.
   ``Gore does not appear to have gotten into the numbers where he
will close the margin,'' said Lee Miringoff, chief of the Marist
College Institute for Public Opinion. ``That leaves the next level
of analysis: Turnout.''
   Jews, who can make up roughly 25 percent of New York's primary
vote, strongly favored Dukakis; blacks, who can make up about the
same proportion of the vote, backed Jackson overwhelmingly. Jackson
had roughly 20 percent of the non-Jewish white vote, the ABC-Post
poll said.
   ``Jackson is not getting enough whites. He needs a large black
turnout and low white ethnic turnout to close what is a
moderate-size Dukakis lead at this point,'' Miringoff said. ``White
ethnics are solidly behind Dukakis. The question is whether they go
and vote.''
   The ABC-Post and CBS polls said Jackson's supporters were
significantly more committed to their candidate than were Dukakis'
backers. Miringoff said analyses of only the most likely voters
narrowed Dukakis' lead.
   But in New York, even when black voters are committed to a
candidate, ``even in the best of times that doesn't mean as good a
turnout as the Jewish turnout,'' said CBS poll chief Warren
Mitofsky. ``The Jewish vote always turns out.''
   It remained to be seen if Dukakis would retain that vote,
Mitofsky said. Moreover, he noted that a CBS poll late last week
said as many as one-fifth of the voters had not decided _ making
the candidates' final efforts, on the stump and in advertising,
particularly important. Even the CBS poll that was completed Sunday
night said 9 percent remained undecided.
   ``I'd take these last few days very seriously,'' Mitofsky said.
   The ABC-Post poll, which presses respondents to make a choice,
had only 3 percent undecided. ``The biggest group of wafflers right
now'' _ about 10 percent of the electorate _ ``is trying to decide
between Dukakis and Gore,'' said Brennan.
   There were other imponderables, including the new conflict in
the Persian Gulf. Voters could turn to Dukakis as ``a safer vote,''
Brennan conjectured, or to Jackson as a protest vote, or to Gore
because of his experience in military matters.
</TEXT>
