<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Refused     04-18 0768</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Refused,0788</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Refusenik Follows Wife's Surgery Long Distance</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vladimir Tufeld's thoughts revolve around a very
sick woman in an American hospital thousands of miles away. But his
crippled body is stuck in a two-room apartment with a 12th-floor
view of a city he no longer wants to see.
   In late December, Tufeld's wife of 35 years, Izolda, was given
permission to leave the Soviet Union to undergo brain tumor surgery
at Johns Hopkins University hospital in Baltimore, Md.
   But according to Soviet government officials, the knowledge
Tufeld gained working in an electronics factory 15 years ago still
could threaten Soviet security. Despite appeals from members of the
U.S. Congress and governments from Britain to Australia, the
distinguished-looking 60-year-old electronics engineer had to stay
behind.
   A growing number of Soviet Jews, including the best-known
refuseniks, have been allowed to emigrate under more liberal
policies implemented by Mikhail S. Gorbachev. But many others, like
Tufeld, remain in the web of bureaucracy and indifference that has
held them for years.
   ``We have been married for 35 years, and we've never been
separated from the moment of our wedding,'' Tufeld said in a recent
interview.
   Even under more liberal travel and emigration policies, Soviets
are not often allowed to travel abroad as entire families. Tufeld
said he feels like a hostage.
   On Wednesday, Tufeld received yet another rejection of his
appeal to leave the Soviet Union and eventually settle in Israel.
That makes more than 20 of them since the couple first applied to
emigrate on July 4, 1977 _ ``the day of independence in the United
States,'' Tufeld noted.
   Mrs. Tufeld, 57, underwent surgery for a brain tumor for the
first time in 1981, in the Soviet Union. But Soviet doctors did not
remove all of the tumor and it grew back even larger.
   Doctors at Johns Hopkins removed the new tumor im mid-January,
and have conducted several operations since then. Tufeld said
doctors believe the operation went well, but Izolda remains
hospitalized and on a respirator. Tufeld hasn't talked to her since
before the first American operation.
   He gets weekly reports from his son Igor, who was allowed to
emigrate to Israel in 1977 and saw his mother for the first time
since then when he traveled to the United States to be with her.
   The KGB secret police, the Ministry of Internal Affairs and the
Moscow visa office have no objection to Tufeld leaving the Soviet
Union, Tufeld said. The hang-up is the Ministry of General
Machine-Building.
   A ministry official, Nikolai Gavrilenko, told him the objection
is in force until 1992, Tufeld said. ``That doesn't mean you can
leave in 1992,'' Tufeld quoted Gavrilenko as telling him. ``It
means we'll review your case in 1992 and decide how much longer you
have to wait.''
   Refuseniks have long said that rejection because of alleged
access to state secrets is widely abused by officials.
   Jewish emigration from the Soviet Union increased in early 1988,
but the annual figures for recent years are far below the peak of
more than 51,000 in 1979.
   ``There is a certain amount of progress, but already the West
has changed its opinion to think that there is no longer a
problem,'' Tufeld said.
   But Tufeld continues to struggle, both with his own infirmities
and the Soviet bureaucracy.
   Tufeld and his wife, a former teacher, both were declared by the
Soviet government to be invalids in need of constant care. He has
not worked for 10 years and receives a $190 pension because of a
back problem that an American doctor has diagnosed as either a
herniated disc or a tumor.
   Tufeld said Soviet doctors cannot do the tests necessary to
decide which it is. Tufeld also suffers from severe gallstones.
   He gets around slowly with the help of a cane between the
telephone, a wall plastered with pictures of foreign notables and a
windowsill piled high with letters of support and futile
communications with Soviet officials. The window looks down on an
ancient church surrounded by drab east Mosocw apartments and
factories.
   Tufeld charges that officials who refuse to let him leave are
undermining the authority of Gorbachev, who has told the West that
everyone refused permission to emigrate because of access to state
secrets is given a definite date when he will be allowed to leave.
   ``I think there's a game going on,'' Tufeld said. ``They reject
you and wait for the reaction from the West. If it's quiet there
then _ `Let him die.'''
</TEXT>
