<DOCNO> AP880418-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0020EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BlackTeachers     04-18 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Black Teachers,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minority Teaching Program Guarantees Jobs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Black Protests</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STATESBORO, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A college and five school systems
troubled by a growing shortage of minority teachers have teamed up
in an effort to lure more blacks into the classroom with offers of
scholarships and assurances of jobs back home.
   Until about 10 years ago teaching was an especially attractive
profession for college-educated blacks, offering opportunity and
job security that was sometimes hard to find in other fields.
   But by 1981, fewer than 10 percent of the nation's public school
teachers were black; that total is expected to drop to fewer than 5
percent by the early 1990s, according to Jack Miller, dean of
Georgia Southern College's School of Education.
   In Georgia, blacks account for 10 percent of public school
teachers, but their numbers will shrink to fewer than 6 percent in
just two years. At the same time, the black student population will
increase from 40 percent this year to 55 percent in 1990.
   ``There is a critical need for role models for black kids,''
said Johnny Tremble, a co-director of Georgia Southern's minority
teaching program. ``Boys and girls need to see themselves being
successful, contributing to society, and need to hear about values
from black people.''
   Black teachers also can help white students avoid racist
attitudes by showing it is better to ``judge a person on what he or
she has to offer,'' said Tremble.
   Tremble, principal of the collge's laboratory school where
future teachers get classroom experience, said he has received
numerous phone calls since the school announced its minority
teaching program in March.
   Three students already are in the program, and college officials
hope to sign up 25 to 30 more promising black students by
September, said Tremble.
   Five school systems _ from Bibb, Chatham, Emanuel and Barrow
counties in Georgia and Beaufort, S.C._ are participating.
   The school systems identify promising black students and provide
scholarships for those willing to major in education. The school
systems also guarantee the students a job after graduation. Teacher
salaries in Georgia range from $16,352 to $33,462, depending on
experience and level of training.
   Georgia Southern provides counseling and puts together a
financial package that could include additional scholarships,
grants, low-interest loans and loans that are considered repaid if
the student teaches for a specified period.
   ``There has been a great deal of national talk about the issue,
but this is the most complete plan to actually do something about
it,'' said Beaufort School Superintendent Terry Terril.
   Miller said the program is unique because the school systems
handle the recruitment.
   ``We're getting capable people because ... the school districts
decide who they want to come back and teach in their communities,''
said Miller, a co-director of the program. ``Thus far, I've been
impressed with the kind of kids we have been talking to.''
   All of the students taking part in the GSC program will have
above-average SAT scores, Miller said.
   Georgia Southern received a $50,000 grant from the U.S.
Department of Education to help run the program for two years.
   Tremble believes fewer blacks are going into teaching these days
because they can choose from a wider range of careers.
   But the nationwide teacher decline is not a problem that is
confined just to minorities. Tremble noted that Georgia has a
shortage of 10,000 certified teachers. In recent years, an
increasing number of students of all races have shunned teaching to
pursue careers that appear to be more rewarding.
   Tremble said educators and guidance counselors have focused on
the negative aspects of teaching, without pointing out the rewards.
   ``We're not giving education a fair shake,'' he said. ``I don't
mind you talking about the bad, but talk about the good, too. And
if you're going to talk bad of education, talk about the bad of
other careers.''
</TEXT>
