<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Naples-LittleAmerica     04-18 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Naples-Little America,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Naples' Big American Community Lying Low</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAPLES, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``Little America'' colony was shaken by
the bloody terrorist attack on the USO club here, but the U.S. Navy
says its 10,000-strong community in Naples won't be driven away.
   The car bombing that killed four Italians and one American
servicewoman was the first known terrorist act against the U.S.
Navy in this southern port city that serves as center for 6th Fleet
operations in the Mediterranean.
   The Thursday night blast also injured 17 people, including four
American sailors. Two Islamic groups claimed responsibility.
   Italian investigators say the attack was carried out by Junzo
Okudaira, a notorious terrorist of the Japanese Red Army, which is
tied to Arab terrorist groups in Lebanon. Police say he had at
least two accomplices, Fusako Shigenobu, the woman leader of the
Japanese gang, and a Middle Eastern or North African man.
   Chief investigator Romano Argenio on Sunday said he had no new
leads in the case.
   Security measures have been tightened at the extensive American
Navy facilities here, but officials and dependents say their lives
and activities haven't changed much.
   ``The first couple of days there is apprehension but it wears
off real fast,'' said Lt. David Morris, a Navy spokesman. ``You
have to get on with life.''
   ``We are all devastated, but you can't live in a shell of
fear,'' added his wife, Deirdre, mother of an 11-month-old child.
   The car bomb exploded as dozens of sailors from the visiting
frigates USS Paul and USS Capodanno were at a party inside the USO
club. The frigates have since left Naples, but five ships from the
6th Fleet's amphibious task force are due to arrive here Wednesday
on a routine port call.
   In addition to welcoming visiting servicemen from 6th fleet
ships, Naples is home to about 10,000 Navy personnel and dependents.
   Some are stationed at NATO's Southern Europe Command, but most
serve at the Naval Support Activity Base in the Naples' suburb of
Agnano. The 55-acre complex has been the administrative
headquarters for the 6th Fleet since 1963.
   The 6th Fleet flagship, the USS Belknap, is based in Gaeta, 60
miles to the north.
   The Agnano complex could pass for a small American town. It is
equipped with a supermarket, bar, restaurant, club, movie theater,
bank, hospital, church, post office, school and gymnasium. The base
also has a weekly newspaper, a local English-language radio station
and a TV station which receives American programs by satellite.
   But the Americans are not completely isolated. Since only a
limited number of enlisted personnel is provided housing, most
people rent apartments in the local community.
   Most live in the western part of the city in an area known as
Little America.
   The American presence has been an economic boom for Naples,
pouring some $250 million a year into the local economy.
   The newspaper La Repubblica summed up the feeling of Naples'
residents following the USO attack as: ``Italians, Americans what's
the difference? For us it is a tragedy in the family.''
   Still, many Neopolitans say they have little direct contact with
the resident Americans.
   The U.S. community ``is almost an invisible army, a community
that lives like a colony, closed in its own world,'' commented the
newspaper Il Messaggero. ``The women rarely venture out into the
city. They hate the traffic, they are not able to adjust, they are
afraid of muggers.''
   Morris said there are some Americans who can't adjust to
Neopolitan ways and rarely leave the Navy complex.
   ``But most people serve here for two years and that mentality
wears off after a while,'' he said. ``I don't think there is a
fortress attitude.''
   However, he said, Navy personnel are constantly aware of the
possiblity of terrorist attacks and take sufficient precautions.
   While Americans in Naples had never been terrorist targets
before, U.S. military figures have been attacked elsewhere in
Italy. Brig. Gen. James L. Dozier was kidnapped by the Red Brigade
in Verona in 1981 and rescued 42 days later. Leamon Hunt, the
Rome-based head of the U.N. observer force in the Sinai, was
assassinated in 1984. The Red Brigades, an Italian terrorist group,
claimed responsibility for his killing.
   ``We try not to draw a lot of attention to ourselves,'' said Lt.
Cmdr. John Marchi, another Navy spokesman. ``Naples is a very big
city and we kind of melt in.''
</TEXT>
