<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Girl'sDeath     04-18 1215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Girl's Death,1255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Girl's Death Splits Country, Fuels Jewish-Arab Mistrust</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The April 6 confrontation in the occupied West
Bank that led to the death of an Israeli and two Arabs heightened
tension between Palestinians and Jews, inflamed Jewish settlers and
embroiled the army in a controversy over who killed the Israeli
teen-ager. Here is a report:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELON MOREH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The conflict between Arabs
and Jews came into stark focus on a recent spring day when a group
of young Israelis hiked into an area where Arabs were tending
fields of wheat and barley in these contested hills.
   On that day, profound mistrust between reluctant neighbors
turned into terror and bloodshed. Yet it's likely neither group
wanted or expected trouble.
   Indeed, the whole affair may have resulted from a chain of
misunderstandings.
   Before the day ended, two Arab youths were killed, and
15-year-old Tirza Porat became the first Israeli civilian to die in
unrest that has swept the Israeli-occupied territories in the past
four months. Two other Arabs were wounded by gunfire in the April 6
confrontation, and 15 Israeli settlers were injured by stones.
   The Arabs said the Israeli settlers marched toward Beita and one
of their guards shot to death a Palestinian. They said they feared
an attack and rushed to defend their village with stones and axes.
   For the 16 teen-agers and two adult guards from the Jewish
settlement of Elon Moreh 35 miles north of Jerusalem, the day
became a nightmare. They said hundreds of Arabs encircled them,
shouting ``Slaughter the Jews!''
   Two very different accounts emerged inside Israel about how the
Israeli teen-ager died that day.
   After an initial report that she had been shot by Arabs, the
Israeli army said the girl had been stoned to death. But an
examination of the body showed she died of a bullet wound to the
head. The army finally said Romam Aldubi, a right-wing extremist
accompanying the teen-agers as a guard, accidentally shot her.
   However, the Israeli settlers insisted she was stoned to death
by the Palestinians.
   They accused the Israeli army, usually immune from political
attack, of backing the Arabs' version of the day's events. The
settlers, who number about 65,000 among 850,000 West Bank
Palestinians, turned the dark-haired Israeli teen-ager into a cause
celebre.
   Israeli hard-liners, who think Israel should foster settlements
on the land their army seized from Jordan in the 1967 Middle East
War, rallied behind the settlers.
   The settlers lashed out in a personal attack on Lt. Gen. Dan
Shomron, the Israeli army's chief of staff, for saying most
villagers tried to help the Israelis.
   ``Shomron is wrong. The Arabs were vultures. I didn't realize
how hostile and primitive the population was,'' Menachem Ilan, the
other adult on the hike, said.
   He said before the Israeli teen-ager was shot, some Arabs
shouted in Hebrew, ``You took two of ours, now give us two of
yours.''
   Shomron, for his part, grew angry when the teen-agers held a
news conference four days later to dispute the military's version
of events. He said the children and their parents were trying to
undermine Israel's army and even hinted about subjecting the
teen-age hikers to lie-detector tests.
   Left-wing Israelis, meanwhile, attacked the army from the rear.
They said the military wrongly punished the village.
   The army had placed Beita under curfew for five days, detained
hundreds of men and destroyed 14 homes.
   ``Why didn't the army wait until it knew the facts?'' said
Felicia Langer, an Israeli attorney who represents Palestinians.
   For the settlers, however, the army had not struck back hard
enough. The mourners at the teen-ager's funeral demanded revenge
and marched through an Arab village.
   Cabinet Minister Avraham Sharir called for razing Beita,
shocking Israeli moderates.
   ``Our problem at this stage isn't the Arabs, it's the Jews,''
Yaacov Hasdai, an Israeli educator, told the Jerusalem Post. ``If
we don't restore our basic values and send the extremists back to
their corners, we don't have much time left to us.''
   The final version of the army's report on that day has not yet
been released. However, it is likely to contain implicit criticism
of the settlers, who failed to follow military rules requiring
Israelis hiking through the West Bank to notify the army in advance.
   The report, according to published accounts, indicates Aldubi
himself may have caused the trouble by being too quick to fire his
M-16 rifle in the field near Beita, killing the first Palestinian.
   ``The farmers thought the settlers were coming to hurt us,''
villager Nitham Muthgar, 27, said afterward. ``One Palestinian
approached to ask what they were doing. A settler shot and wounded
him, and then all the villagers were afraid.''
   The subsequent chain of events is not completely clear. Arabs
apparently led the settlers into the village, where news of the
death had been broadcast over a mosque loudspeaker.
   ``More and more youths gathered on the hilltops,'' Rachel
Savitch, 16, said at the hiker's news conference. ``They got closer
and closer,'' she said. ``They descended and completely surrounded
us.''
   The settlers said they followed the Arabs into Beita because
they were afraid. A mob of Arabs, said Rami Hoffman, 17, were led
by ``women and girls with their faces painted, shouting, wailing,
whipping up the atmosphere to a fever pitch.''
   In Beita, the Israeli hiker and another Palestinian were shot to
death, and villagers attacked the settlers.
   Aldubi, who has not regained consciousness after being stoned by
Arabs, is believed to have killed the second Arab.
   Arab villagers wrested Aldubi's gun away from him but apparently
did not fire it, according to the army. Instead, the Palestinians
dismantled it and eventually returned it to the army with eight
bullets inside.
   The villagers say the only weapons they used were stones and
farm tools. Their version is supported by the army, which said no
firearms were found in house-to-house searches.
   But the settlers contend the hiker was shot by a Palestinian
with a Soviet-made Kalashnikov.
   Ariel Aviva, 17, said he saw an Arab firing the gun he believes
killed his fellow hiker.
   ``I looked up and saw an Arab man with a masked face shooting a
Kalashnikov rifle from a rooftop,'' he said. ``I was in front of
Tirza. When I looked down, she was lying there bleeding from the
head.''
   However, the army says an autopsy showed the bullet went through
her jaw and came out the top of her head, indicating that no one
firing from a rooftop could have killed her.
   But a police inquiry was expected to conclude it is impossible
to tell which version is correct, since no bullet was found.
   Some Israelis asked why, in a dangerous period of Arab-Israeli
tensions, the group was hiking in the Arab-populated hills.
   ``This was clearly a political act. The settlers viewed the hike
as patriotic, staking their claims to the land,'' Meron Benvenisti,
a former deputy mayor of Jerusalem who publishes annual reports on
the occupied territories, said.
   Ilan, 55, said denied that. But he added: ``This land is ours.
If an Arab has the right to walk around Tel Aviv, we certainly have
the right to hike around our homes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
