<DOCNO> AP880418-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0015EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0833 04-18 1141</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0833,1100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Race Said Tightening In New York As Candidates Make Final Appeals</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 8th graf pvs bgng, `Meanwhile, a,' with 4 grafs to
UPDATE with Washington Post-ABC News poll; PICKS UP 9th graf pvs
bgng, `The poll'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson on Sunday accused his Democratic
presidential opponents of inconsistent policies toward South Africa
as the New York primary contest moved into its final hours with a
flurry of ethnic campaigning.
   With new polls indicating the race for New York's 255 Democratic
convention delegates is tightening, Jackson, Michael Dukakis and
Albert Gore Jr. aired differences over policy toward South Africa
and the Middle East, as well funding for combating drugs.
   The candidates also vowed to work for party unity, regardless of
which of them wins the Democratic presidential nomination.
   ``It's Too Close To Call,'' proclaimed the New York Daily News
in a front-page headline Sunday as it released the findings of its
latest poll.
   The overall poll numbers, based on responses from Democrats
questioned Monday through Thursday, had Dukakis in front of
Jackson, 51 percent to 37 percent, with Gore trailing at 10 percent.
   However, the Daily News reported that in the final two days of
polling, Gore had begun to pick up support among likely Democratic
voters, at the expense of Dukakis.
   The survey questioned 502 likely Democratic voters and had a
margin of error of 4.5 percentage points.
   Meanwhile, polls by The Washington Post-ABC News and USA
Today-Cable News Network indicated the race was even tighter.
   The Washington Post-ABC poll, based on interviews Friday and
Saturday nights and pubished Monday, showed Dukakis with 46 percent
support, Jackson with 40 percent and Gore with 11 percent. It also
showed that Dukakis and Jackson each got about 40 percent support
in New York City.
   The survey, with a margin of error of 8 percentage points, was
based on telephone interviews with 183 registered Democrats who
said they planned to vote in the primary.
   The USA Today-CNN survey taken Friday, Saturday and Sunday found
Dukakis with 46 percent support, Jackson 34 percent and Gore still
far behind at 9 percent.
   The poll picked up some movement toward Jackson on Sunday,
handing him a slight lead over Dukakis in New York City, but
Dukakis had twice as much support as Jackson in the city's suburbs
and in upstate New York, according to poll results published in
Monday's edition of USA Today.
   The survey questioned 846 registered Democrats who said they
were certain to vote Tuesday and had a margin of error of 3.5
percentage points.
   Just how many voters go to the polls on Tuesday may be the
crucial factor, some observers said.
   ``The race is getting closer and turnout is the key,'' New York
pollster Lee Miringoff, head of Marist College's Institute for
Public Opinion, said Sunday.
   A low turnout will favor Jackson, said Miringoff, because of the
candidate's near unanimous and highly committed support among New
York's black voters who generally make up about 25 percent of the
vote in New York's Democratic primaries.
   In a telephone interview with The Associated Press, New York
Gov. Mario Cuomo said he thought there could be a low turnout for
the primary. He also said he ``wouldn't be surprised'' by a Jackson
victory.
   Meanwhile, Dukakis defeated Jackson by a 3-2 margin in Arizona's
Democratic presidential caucuses Saturday night.
   When vote totals were completed early Sunday, Dukakis had 54
percent to 38 percent for Jackson and 5 percent for Gore. That
meant Dukakis picked up 22 national delegates; Jackson received 14
delegates, and Gore got none.
   After their televised debate on WNBC, Dukakis and Gore marched
in a ``Salute to Israel'' parade on Fifth Avenue. Jackson passed up
the parade and met with community leaders, a session set up by one
of his most prominent Jewish supporters, R. Peter Straus, president
of the New York chapter of the American Jewish Committee.
   After the meeting, Jackson was asked why he had passed up the
parade. He said, ``We had to make a judgment about our time today
...my day is full and my outreach continues.''
   Jackson refused to comment on New York City Mayor Edward Koch
calling him a liar.
   Interviewed on the ABC television show, ``This Week with David
Brinkley,'' the mayor said Jackson had lied when he said he was the
last person to speak with Martin Luther King Jr. before he died. He
also contended Jackson had initially denied he had ever called New
York ``Hymietown,'' a term widely viewed as anti-Semitic. Jackson
later apologized for the remark.
   ``I'm faulting him for lying ... do you want a president who
under stress, is not capable of telling the truth?'' said Koch.
   After marching in the parade, Gore was touring Hispanic, Italian
and Jewish neighborhoods, while Dukakis was attending a Gaelic
football game and then a reception with Gov. Rafael Hernandez-Colon
of Puerto Rico.
   Jackson's contribution to the ethnic mix was a fund-raising
event with Chinese-American businessmen.
   The discussion of South Africa began with the three candidates
agreeing that they would oppose severing relations with the
government of South Africa even if it does not move to end
apartheid.
   ``That's not the approach,'' said Jackson. ``I believe you have
to talk with the enemy.''
   The differences between the candidates emerged when Gore said he
opposed sending arms to countries bordering South Africa _ the
so-called frontline states of Tanzania, Zambia, Zimbabwe and
Mozambique.
   ``I think that would be inviting a lot more bloodshed,'' said
the Tennswee senator.
   Jackson said those countries ``ought to be able to defend
themselves from South Africa's bombarding of their infrastructure
and our investment.''
   Dukakis agreed with Gore, saying, ``I think the superpowers are
supplying arms to too many countries as it is.''
   Gore also quoted Dukakis as saying he thought current funding
was sufficient to deal with drugs.
   The Massachusetts governor replied that Congress _ ``you and
your colleagues'' _ had appropriated ``enough funds to get
started'' on educational programs to combat drugs, but said the
Reagan administration had not used it properly.
   ``But wait, but wait a minute,'' said Gore. ``This is a major
crisis. The drug crisis deserves more attention.''
   Jackson said that if he arrived at the Democratic convention
with the second-largest bloc of delegates ``I certainly would have
earned serious consideration'' for a spot on the ticket. But he
refused later to say whether he would accept the vice presidential
nomination if it were offered.
   Asked if he would choose Jackson as his running mate, Dukakis
said, ``I would not rule anybody out or in at this point.''
   All the candidates called for party unity. Jackson said, ``We
should not have the notion, the attitude that if I don't win, I'm
going to take my marbles and go home.''
</TEXT>
