<DOCNO> AP880418-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0036EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Anniversary     04-18 1210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Anniversary,1247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Israel _ 40th Birthday In A Time Of Trouble</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in report for AMs of Sunday, April 17.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel turns 40 this week, beset by a rebellion
among Palestinians who have spent more than half that time under
occupation and a wrenching debate on the young nation's future.
   The Arab uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip has
drained much of the joy from a year-long birthday celebration that
climaxes April 21, which coincides on the Hebrew calendar this year
with May 14, 1948, the date Israel was founded.
   A poetry festival and a $10 million rock music extravaganza in
the Negev Desert are going ahead but plans to bring singer Barbra
Streisand, tennis star Chris Evert and the rock group Pink Floyd
collapsed.
   Officials had hoped to demonstrate Israel's achievements and
acceptance during the anniversary year. Instead, canceled plans and
the absence of foreign heads of state underline its vulnerability.
   Much of Israel's success has been in developing military power,
the result of five wars with neighboring Arab states. For example,
it ranks sixth in the world in arms exports, which bring in about
$1 billion a year.
   There also is a flourishing cultural life, especially in a range
of music from Hebrew punk-rock to that great national cultural
achievement, the Israeli Philharmonic.
   Since Dec. 8, when the violence began, Israel has been consumed
by the question of what to do with the territories captured from
Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war. For the first time
the issue is likely to be the focus of elections, now scheduled for
November.
   Liberal politicians say 20 years of occupation has had a
corrosive effect on morality and does not square with being a
``light unto nations'' the goal declared by Israel's first prime
minister, the late David Ben-Gurion.
   Abba Eban, elder statesman of the Labor Party, said growth of
character has not matched the country's growth in material wealth
and military power.
   ``We anticipated that within a period of 40 years we would have
outlived the rhetoric of struggle and resistance and would be
moving into some kind of drama and romance in social creativity,''
the former foreign minister said.
   ``Modern Israel does not owe the same allegiance, debt or
devotion to its traditional Jewish character, and it very rarely
compares its actions to criteria that come from the Jewish ethical
tradition.''
   He said democracy was being undermined by the emergency measures
of occupation, and the cooperative spirit of pioneer days was being
supplanted by materialism.
   Such misgivings are not shared by the rising star of the
conservative Likud bloc, Benyamin Netanyahu, who recently resigned
as ambassador to the United Nations. He said Israel's success
``borders on the miraculous.''
   Half a century ago, Netanyahu said, the Jewish people had
crawled from the Holocaust and the possibility of building a
national life seemed hopelessly remote.
   ``Yet in a few years the Jews recovered their homeland, fought
off armies that assaulted them, liberated their ancient capital,
built a modern economy, theaters, universities and concert halls,
and revived an ancient tongue,'' he declared.
   Netanyahu, whose brother Yonathan was killed leading the daring
1976 rescue of hijacked airline hostages at Entebbe, Uganda, said
the Arab threat is undiminished.
   ``The grim truth remains that the majority of the Arab world
still refuses to accept Israel's right to exist, and still seeks to
wage war against it, war by different means, including the present
means of mass violence and media stampede,'' Netanyahu said.
   In the former ambassador's view, withdrawal from the occupied
lands would shrink Israel's waist to a 10-mile-wide strip against
the sea, with thousands of young Palestinians holding rockets
instead of stones.
   The left believes Israel is strong and secure enough to risk
trading land for peace and that greater danger lies in keeping the
occupied territories and trying to rule the hostile and rapidly
growing popuatlion of 1.5 million Arabs.
   Palestinian intellectuals attribute the sudden explosion of
anger and violence Dec. 8 to three factors:
   _The Palestinian question was ignored by the U.S.-Soviet summit
last December and given secondary priority to the Iran-Iraq war at
the Arab summit in November
   _Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir expressed satisfaction with the
status quo and a desire to make the occupied land a permanent part
of ``Greater Israel.''
   _Daily frustrations about army rule radicalized younger Arabs.
   A generation of Palestinians has been born and grown to
adulthood since 1967, resentful of occupation and less intimidated
by the might of the Israeli military. Many also have been attracted
to the Moslem fundamentalism spreading through the Arab world
   One result of these forces has been a young, underground
leadership of the Palestine Liberation Organization that has taken
charge of the rebellion and is directing it.
   Saeb Erakat, a political science professor at An Najah
University in the West Bank, said: ``The uprising is a message to
the Israelis, the Americans and the Arabs: We don't want to become
Israeli. We are not a minority, but a people, and therefore we
demand our right to self-determination,''
   Many Israelis say the Arabs fail to comprehend or accept the
historical connection Jews feel to the land.
   Yehuda Avni immigrated from Chicago in 1949 and built the Vered
Hagalil ranch near the Sea of Galilee with his wife Yona. Across
the road from his stable of pure-bred Arabian horses is the ruin of
the home of an Israelite who lived about 200 B.C.
   ``We both picked this site with its beautiful view for our
farms,'' said Avni, 60. ``I feel a kind of kinship with him. I feel
I am part of a chain. The sense of continuity is something vivid,
and it gives depth to my life.''
   In Efrat, a Jewish settlement eight miles south of Jerusalem,
Rabbi Shlomo Riskin showed a reporter the rocky hills on which he
has founded a community of 300, mostly religious Jews.
   Seeking to dispel the image of settler as fanatic, Riskin
stresses his desire for coexistence with Arabs.
   The difficulty of achieving it is illustrated by his experience
with Majid, a Palestinian handyman who taught Riskin Arabic.
   ``I studied with him a few times a week,'' the rabbi said. ``He
had gefilte fish at my home on Friday evening a number of times. We
had what I thought were very good relations.''
   Then one day a bomb was planted just outside Efrat and one of
the prime suspects was Majid, who disappeared.
   ``I teach my children and myself to respect every human being as
innocent until proven guilty,'' Riskin said. ``At the same time, I
have to make sure that I protect myself.''
   The Arab-Israeli conflict touches almost every aspect of life,
even the 110-piece Israel Philharmonic.
   Ely Eban, 38, a clarinetist and son of Abba Eban, said the
unseen impact was brought home to him when he returned from
studying in the United States. In Israel, the tempo of life was
rapid.
   ``Whenever I would hear myself playing something here, it always
seemed a little fast, a little strident, a little more nervous,''
he said. ``When you live here, there is this rhythm that you take
on, and it does affect the music making.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
