<1ST_LINE>u i AM-France-Canada     04-18 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Canada,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>France Recalls Ambassador After 21 Anglers Arrested In Canada</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. JOHN'S, Newfoundland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France recalled its ambassador
to Canada on Sunday after 21 French nationals were arrested for
illegally fishing in Canadian waters.
   The French citizens, who had been protesting a fishing ban on
French trawlers when they were arrested on Thursday, were released
from jail on Sunday following a bail hearing.
   The French foreign ministry said the decision to recall
Ambassador Philippe Husson to Paris was taken because of a
``worsening of the French-Canadian dispute over fishing.''
   The trawler the fishermen were on was based in St.
Pierre-Miquelon, a group of small French-held islands south of
Newfoundland.
   The islanders have been banned from their traditional fishing
grounds in the Gulf of St. Lawrence because of a dispute between
Canada and France over the size of the fishing boundaries around
the islands. The men are scheduled to appear in St. John's for a
preliminary hearing on Oct. 3.
   ``Canada has a lot of progress to make as a civilized country,''
said Albert Pen, a senator from the islands and one of the 21
people who took part in the fishing protest.
   Also among the group was Gerard Grignon, a member of the French
chamber of deputies on the islands, and Victor Reux and Marc
Plantegenest, two members of the islands' territorial government.
   In Edmonton, External Affairs Minister Joe Clark defended the
arrests.
   ``This is a matter which is essentially a fishery dispute, a
very important one. It is capable of being resolved by
negotiation,'' said Clark. ``In the meantime, if Canadian law is
breached Canadian law will be enforced.''
   During the weekend, President Francois Mitterrand of France said
it was ``intolerable'' that the islanders were not able to fish
normally ``in waters they have for a long time been accustomed to
use for that work.''
</TEXT>
