<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--France-Prison     04-18 0142</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--France-Prison,0146</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prison Riot Ends Peacefully In France</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENSISHEIM, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 250 prisoners who rioted and
took two hostages at Ensisheim Prison surrendered and freed their
captives unharmed.
   The prisoners, who were protesting what they called inhumane
conditions at the prison, gave up Sunday afternoon and freed a nun
who worked as a volunteer at the prison, Sister Francoise, and a
guard who was not identified.
   Nearly all 260 inmates at the prison in eastern France were
involved in the riot that began Saturday. Ten of the prisoners were
injured.
   Five leaders of the riot talked for several hours Sunday morning
with negotiators. French authorities said they made no concessions,
but would take into consideration the convicts' complaints.
   The authorities did not say how the riot started, whether the
prisoners were armed or whether the prison was damaged.
</TEXT>
