<HEAD>Two Ethiopian Military Officers Request Asylum In Sudan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Ethiopian air force plane flew into
southeastern Sudan and two of its nine crew members requested
asylum.
   A government official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
on Sunday the aircraft landed in Suki, 240 miles from the capital
of Khartoum. After the landing Saturday, the crew members were
questioned in Khartoum, he said.
   The official declined to say if asylum would be granted to the
two crew members who requested it or what would happen to the other
seven men.
   Relations have been strained between Ethiopia and Sudan over the
past few years. Both countries are fighting insurgencies and accuse
each other of allowing rebels to flee across their border to escape
capture.
