<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HonestyPays     04-18 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Honesty Pays,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honest Worker Reports $1,000 Find</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Alice Lisquez opened a letter
and found a $100 bill, the thought of keeping the money never
entered her mind.
   ``It never occurred to me to take it,'' Lisquez said.
   A Georgia woman, planning to use the cash on her vacation,
mistakenly sent 10 $100 bills along with an order for some plants.
   Lisquez, 47, usually spends her days opening about 1,000 orders
for Michigan Bulb Co. In one she opened about three weeks ago was a
$21.84 order from Mary Duval of Dahlonega, Ga., for creeping phlox
and peonies.
   The big bills also were there.
   Lisquez told her supervisor, Sue Barnstable, who tracked down
Duval. Barnstable sent Duval a $1,000 check to her to replace the
cash.
   On Thursday, Lisquez received a $100 bill and a silk scarf from
Duval as a reward.
   ``Lord, it's the least I could do,'' Duval said.
   The package also contained two letters from Duval, one to
Lisquez and one to Barnstable.
   ``Dear Alice,'' Duval wrote. ``I called your office to obtain
your name and to thank you. I, like you, am a working girl and I
had saved most of (the money) haphazardly and converted it to the
$100 bills, as a twenty gets easily spent.
   ``It was for a badly needed vacation, and thanks to you my plans
do not have to be changed.''
   The note to Barnstable praised Lisquez for her honesty.
   ``I still have difficulty accepting the fact that there is basic
honesty practiced,'' Duval wrote. ``I would never have known what
happened to the money.''
   Duval, 63, said the return of the money has saved a month-long
trip to England she has planned for later this year.
   ``I've never been there before,'' said the head nurse at the
infirmary at North Georgia College.
   Office Manager Lyle Hansen said he has seen a few mistaken
mailings during the company's 43-year history, but never more than
a phone bill or house payment that got switched around in the
shuffle, and never before in cash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
