<DOCNO> AP880418-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ArizonaDemocrats     04-18 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arizona Democrats,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Notches Arizona Victory Just Before New York Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis'
backers are hoping his victory over Jesse Jackson in Arizona's
Democratic presidential caucuses will give him a boost heading into
the crucial New York primary.
   Dukakis, who took 54 percent of the vote to 38 percent for
Jackson, picked up 22 delegates and six alternates in Saturday's
vote. Jackson got 14 delegates and four alternates.
   Gore, who got only 5 percent of the vote, was shut out because
he failed to reach the 15 percent minimum in any one of Arizona's
five voting regions.
   Arizona's other five delegates to the Democratic National
Convention in Atlanta July 18-21 are top party and government
officials who thus far are uncommitted.
   Jose Villarreal, the Dukakis state campaign director, contended
that the Arizona win established Dukakis as the ``undisputed
front-runner'' going into New York.
   ``This sends two messages,'' Villarreal said. ``One to New York,
that Governor Dukakis has established a momentum throughout the
Western states that is going to carry him to victory in New York.''
   The other message, Villarreal said, is that ``Al Gore is no
more.'' Gore has been winless since Super Tuesday.
   Richard Ybarra, the Western states coordinator for Dukakis,
said, ``He's being called `El Nuevo Kennedy' in the barrios around
Phoenix.''
   Other supporters, however, said the Arizona victory was welcome,
but not overly significant.
   ``I think it's got zip effect in New York,'' said Dukakis
campaign coordinator Renz Jennings. ``New Yorkers are as
independent as you find.'' However, he said a loss to Jackson in
Arizona would have hurt the Massachusetts governor.
   ``We did just what we needed to do,'' he said. ``We picked up
delegates. We beat Gore to the point that he didn't even make the
threshold'' to win delegates.
   Jackson's campaign said the Arizona race had not been crucial.
   ``I don't think the Arizona primary is going to break someone
into front-runner status,'' Jackson's state director John Norris
said. ``Basically it's still a horse race going into New York.''
   He also said Jackson's showing was relatively good.
   ``It's pretty fair to say that we ran a strong second in
Arizona,'' Norris said. ``It definitely beat expectations based on
the polls'' which had given Dukakis a stronger lead.
   Illinois Sen. Paul Simon, who has put his campaign on hold, got
1.2 percent of the Arizona vote while political extremist Lyndon
LaRouche had well under 1 percent and 1.7 percent expressed no
preference.
   Gore spokeswoman Sue Laybe acknowledged, ``We tried a grassroots
campaign; it didn't work very well. With all the money going to New
York there wasn't much we could do.''
   Dukakis ran well ahead in four of Arizona's voting regions,
while he and Jackson were tied at 47 percent in western Maricopa
County, which included south Phoenix and its high minority
population.
   Jackson also scored well in parts of Pima County, which includes
Tucson. He won the rural counties of Apache and Coconino, while
Dukakis took the other 11 rural counties.
   Party officials said 38,464 of Arizona's 680,000 Democrats
voted, for a slightly higher turnout than was predicted on a day
that saw stormy weather across much of the state.
   Dukakis received 20,814 votes to 14,538 for Jackson, 1,972 for
Gore, 465 for Simon, 35 for LaRouche and 639 expressing no
preference.
   Democrats on Saturday also began the process of choosing the
delegates who will actually go to the national convention.
Thirty-six are being allocated in proportion to the caucus vote,
while the other five top party and elected officials are
uncommitted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
