<DOCNO> AP880418-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0048EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-GetKoch     04-18 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Get Koch,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Backers May Unite Against Koch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the black, Hispanic and liberal white
forces backing Jesse Jackson in New York's Democratic presidential
primary say they will turn their fire after Tuesday on Jackson's
most vocal local critic: Mayor Edward I. Koch.
   But while a strong enough voting bloc has emerged to give
Jackson a shot at carrying the city in the three-way primary, it is
uncertain whether his coalition can survive without him and settle
on a Koch challenger.
   ``It's not going to be the same campaign,'' said Rep. Charles
Rangel, D-N.Y., a Jackson supporter who said he would consider a
mayoral race. ``But it is true that we are bringing people together
that we didn't have before.''
   Jackson voters ``would be a hell of a base for someone'' in the
mayoral race, said pollster Sergio Bendixen. ``You couldn't win the
leadership of New York with just those groups. But it would be a
hell of a base.''
   For minority activists, the problem in past elections has been
agreeing on a challenger to Koch, who has held office since 1978.
Blacks have favored a black candidate, Rangel noted, while
Hispanics sought one of their own.
   Still, Koch's critics said the mayor himself has aided their
cause by attacking Jackson and saying Jews would ``have to be
crazy'' to vote for him. Koch last week endorsed underdog Sen.
Albert Gore Jr., a Jackson critic.
   ``The one fellow who comes out the loser in this primary fight
is Ed Koch,'' said former U.S. Rep. Herman Badillo, an Hispanic
leader who also said he would consider running for mayor in 1989.
   ``Most everyone agrees that Koch's behavior has been especially
outrageous,'' Badillo said. ``He's gone beyond the bounds of
decency. ... It's really an anti-Jackson campaign of the most
vicious kind.''
   Badillo supports Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, pointing up
that not all blacks and Hispanics are in accord on Jackson. In any
case, Badillo said Friday, an anti-Koch coalition is not limited to
Jackson's camp.
   ``The fact that some of us are supporting Dukakis and some are
supporting Jackson has nothing to do with Koch,'' he said.
``There's a total basis here for us being able to work together
after next Tuesday.''
   Thus far, though, Hispanics remain supportive of Koch. In a
survey of Hispanic Democrats by Bendixen last week, 55 percent gave
Koch a favorable rating, to 19 percent unfavorable.
   ``His numbers are not weak enough that you could see that the
Hispanic community as base against him,'' Bendixen said.
   But Jackson should do well enough with New York Hispanics to
bring a sizable number to the Democratic National Convention with
him. As they work with Jackson's other delegates, ``They'll have
some interesting experiences. And that usually breeds cooperation
and long-term type coalitions,'' Bendixen said.
   Koch opponents had hopes for such a coalitin surviving from the
Jackson campaign in 1984. It did not, but Rangel _ a Walter Mondale
backer then _ noted that minority voters are far more strongly for
Jackson now.
   ``In the city of New York he has brought together a lot of
people, some of whom have problems with the existing leadership in
the city, who have never worked together before,'' said Rangel, who
is black.
   As for himself, ``I would consider running for mayor if I had a
group of people that really convinced me that I could do better
serving the city of New York than I could do in the U.S.
Congress,'' said Rangel.
   Badillo noted that he was ready to run in 1985 when black
leaders opted instead for Herman Farrell, the black Democratic
leader of Manhattan, who did poorly. Asked if he would run in 1989,
Badillo said: ``I can't tell what the black leaders are going to
do. If we can form a coalition, I sure would.''
</TEXT>
