<DOCNO> AP880418-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0049EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PorkPresident     04-18 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pork President,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmer With PhD Heads Hogs Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRBURY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who leads 100,000 of the nation's
hog farmers says his doctorate degree and university teaching
experience are valuable _ on the farm and on the road promoting
pork.
   ``Those skills, coupled with a lot of practice, have been very
useful,'' said pig farmer Ray Hankes. ``I haven't regretted the
direction my career has taken _ not one little bit.''
   Hankes, 41, recently was elected president of the National Pork
Producers Council. The 25-year-old group says it has helped change
consumers' attitudes about pork and the way hogs are raised,
leading to the production of a more popular and leaner meat.
   ``I guess our programs are working,'' said Hankes, who earned
his doctorate at the University of Illinois in meat science and
ruminant nutrition.
   His main goal as president is to win nationwide approval for a
mandatory levy on pork producers. Farmers will vote in September on
the plan, which would collect 25 cents for every $100 in hog sales
to pay for market development and research.
   Hankes' second goal is make pork even leaner, perhaps by
offering a cash bonus for hogs with less fat or by paying less
money for those that are not as lean.
   ``We've taken a lot of the fat off, but there's still a lot of
work to be done in this area,'' said Hankes.
</TEXT>
