<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diane Olrick and Tony Jestis had a nice
traditional church wedding, then celebrated by climbing into
separate airplanes and flying off into the wild blue yonder.
   At Saturday's ceremony at St. Peter's Cathedral in Belleville,
the couple exchanged medals of Our Lady of Loreto, the patron of
air travelers. Then, the newlywed pilots headed to St. Louis for an
airborne wedding procession.
   At St. Louis Downtown-Parks Airport, the bride flew off in a
restored 1940 Waco UPF-7 while the groom followed in a Cessna 152.
Pilot friends and several wedding guests completed the unusual
procession in seven other small planes.
   ``The idea for the flyby just sort of evolved,'' said Ms.
Olrick, 31, an air traffic controller and part-time flight
instructor.
   Jestis, 26, a senior at Parks Air College, proposed last year to
Ms. Olrick on the campus. She received her engagement ring after a
romantic 2 a.m. flight.
   If riverfront passers-by were startled by the flyby, the
couple's friends and relatives were unfazed.
   ``I wasn't one bit shocked,'' the groom's mother, Dottie Jestis
of Decatur. ``They're both kind of buggy when it comes to flying. I
think it's unique. It's great. But I don't understand it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROYAL OAK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The debate over whether William
Shakespeare actually wrote the great literature and plays
attributed to him may make for good drama itself.
   The Bard will go back to court Sunday for a tongue-in-cheek
trial in which a prosecutor will argue that the William Shakespeare
who wrote plays, poems and sonnets wasn't the man who lived and
worked in Stratford-Upon-Avon under various spellings of
``Shakspere.''
   The prosecutor is Mark McPherson, director of the Daedalus
Agency, a Michigan-based investigative agency that has looked into
such matters as the Loch Ness monster, whether King Arthur really
existed and who put the bop in the bop she bop she bop?
   ``The Case Against Will Shakspere'' will be heard at Oakland
Community College's Royal Oak campus, where a collection of legal
and literary experts will argue the merits of the case.
   ``A lot of people think I'm doing this for the sheer pleasure of
being an iconoclast,'' McPherson said. ``This is not true. I've had
moments when I wished I was presenting the defense. It would be so
much easier.''
   Of the 36 plays, two long narrative poems and 154 sonnets
written between 1593 and 1623 and attributed to Shakespeare, many
were published anonymously, while others were published by an
author named William Shakespeare, McPherson said.
   In 1623, the works became identified with a man baptized April
26, 1564, in Stratford-on-Avon as Gulielmus Shaksper or Shakspere.
   But, McPherson claims, Shakspere was busy suing debtors for
pennies, developing Stratford and getting married while some
struggling writer with a similar name penned the plays.
   ``I believe that Shakespeare wrote Shakespeare,'' McPherson
said. ``I just don't know who `Shakespeare' was. The bridge from
Mr. Shakspere of Stratford to the Shakespeare of legend is shaky at
best.
   Michigan Court of Appeals Judge Myron Wahls will preside over
the mock trial. Leading the defense will be Detroit attorney and
former judge Peter B. Spivak. There will be a celebrity jury, plus
an audience who will vote on the case.
</TEXT>
