<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SmithsonianFolklife     04-18 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Smithsonian Folklife,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New England Culture Featured At Outdoor Smithsonian Festival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For two weeks this summer, the National Mall
will look like a slice of traditional New England life.
   A giant clambake will be surrounded by boat makers, cranberry
growers and stonewall builders as the Smithsonian Institution
spotlights Massachusetts at its annual American Folklife Festival.
   ``The festival is really kind of an innovative museum
exhibition,'' said festival director Diana Parker. ``An indoor
exhibition could show people folk pottery or folk instruments,
(but) to really get behind the genius of what those things are, you
have to see the thought process that creates it.''
   For the 22nd year, the Smithsonian will bring to Washington
people who have struggled to keep American folklife alive, a
program that Folklife Office Director Peter Seitel calls an extra
Smithsonian museum for two weeks of the year.
   Organizers once again expect about 1 million people to visit the
festival for 10 days ending Independence Day.
   Officials at the Smithsonian's Office of Folklife Programs
stress the interaction between the folk artists and the exhibit
goers.
   ``The people speak more eloquently for themselves than we could
speak for them, so we'd rather have them telling what the pot is
and why it's important and why it's made and how it's made than
having a museum label put on it that interprets through us why we
think it's important,'' Parker said.
   The theme this year will focus on how traditional Yankees such
as farmers, fishermen and craftsmen, along with urban ethnic
groups, have adapted to modern life while holding on to their
traditions.
   Exhibits will include an area featuring Massachusetts industry
from old-fashioned clock-making to computer assembly, plus displays
of urban gardens with Italians, Poles, blacks and Portuguese.
   ``That shows how people who were raised in the country ... moved
to the city and wanted to keep up that idea of a countryside
feeling, so they took a spare lot or their backyard and made it
into a hidden countryside,'' said Betty Belanus, curator of the
Massachusetts section of the program.
   The other end of the Mall will feature a clambake, ethnic crafts
including an Irish needleworker and Cambodian kite maker, an
agricultural fair with maple syrup, cranberries and tobacco, stone
wall builders, a maritime exhibit featuring boat builders and sail
makers, an oxen-pulling contest, ethnic and holiday cooking and a
half dozen bands.
   Smaller sections at this year's festival will feature how four
ethnic groups _ blacks, Chinese, Ethiopians and Salvadorans _
migrated to the Washington, D.C., area and how their cultures have
survived.
   Another section will feature Soviet musicians in the United
States as part of a cultural exchange.
   Parker remembered a recent festival that featured both Eskimo
culture and teen-age break-dancers from inner-city neighborhoods of
Philadelphia.
   ``Some of these people still write each other. Very close ties
are created. Walls are broken down,'' she said.
   The festival will run from June 23 to June 27 and June 30 to
July 4.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
