<DOCNO> AP880418-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0113EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PhoneRates     04-18 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Phone Rates,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Northern States Face Long-Distance Rate Discrimination</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Madelon in 7th graf is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A policy aimed at equalizing interstate
long-distance telephone rates is not being phased out quickly
enough to end discrimination against northern industrial states, a
research organization says.
   The rate policy adopted after the breakup of American Telephone
& Telegraph Co. requires long-distance carriers to bear _ and share
_ some of the equipment and distribution costs of local telephone
companies.
   But the Northeast-Midwest Institute, a research and lobbying
group serving 18 states, says pooling rates to spread out the
non-traffic costs favors the South and West at the expense of the
``Rust Belt.''
   ``The Federal Communications Commission requires the average
telephone subscriber in the Northeast-Midwest to pay more for
access than it actually costs to provide,'' it said in a recent
report on telecommunications policy.
   ``The additional payments are then used to subsidize
long-distance access for subscribers in states such as Florida,
California and Colorado.''
   Although the FCC has begun eliminating pooling gradually, the
institute said it should have followed the lead of Illinois and
started the phaseout years ago.
   Illinois has been shifting an increasing share of non-traffic
costs from long-distance carriers to local-calling companies since
1984, Madelon Kuchera of the Illinois Commerce Commission said
Friday.
   ``Every year that we transition more to the end-user, the
long-distance carriers are forced to pass those savings along in
lower rates,'' she said. ``So within Illinois, long-distance rates
have decreased almost 30 percent.''
   For example, C&P Telephone Co. in the nation's capital said it
costs 71 cents for a three-minute, direct-dial call from
Springfield to Belleville in Illinois during weekday business hours.
   In comparison, it said a similar call covering about the same
distance in Texas, from Austin to San Antonio, costs 99 cents _ 39
percent more than the Illinois call.
   Similar savings could be achieved on calls outside the state's
borders if the rate structure was not inflated to help other
regions, Ms. Kuchera said.
   ``We've always argued that we don't like subsidizing Florida and
California,'' she said. ``If we could have the rates reflect our
true costs, they would be much less.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880418-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ReservoirExpansion Bjt   04-18 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reservoir Expansion, Bjt,0694</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Bit Of Heaven' Fights Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GOOSE PRAIRIE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Goose Prairie has been described as
``a bit of heaven,'' but residents fear a plan to enlarge a nearby
reservoir may sink the outskirts of their pristine haven in a
watery grave.
   Life in the Cascade Mountain village would be altered forever if
the Bumping Lake reservoir is expanded to more than 13 times its
present capacity in an effort to help drought-stricken Northwest
farmers, residents say.
   But after three decades of debate, Rep. Sid Morrison, R-Wash.,
who represents Bumping Lake and Goose Prairie, says he will sponsor
a bill calling for the expansion. Other area congressmen have
pledged to support the legislation.
   ``It will commercialize the Goose Praire area,'' complained Chet
Clark, who lives in the remote mountain village during the summers.
``You'll have people, construction workers, staying there.
   ``It will have quite an impact on the hiking, the fishing and
the camping.''
   The village, with five permanent residences, 14 summer cabins
and a couple of businesses, is at the end of a narrow blacktop
road, near Mount Rainier National Park.
   Huge evergreens absorb noise and sunlight, giving the area a
cathedral-like stillness. The Bumping River, named by Indians
because of its rocks, races a few feet beyond the edge of the road.
The snow-covered Cascade Range looms overhead.
   ``Goose Praire is a bit of heaven in all seasons,'' Supreme
Court Justice William O. Douglas, a dogged environmentalist, wrote
in his 1974 autobiography, ``Go East, Young Man.''
   Douglas, who grew up in nearby Yakima, first came to Goose
Prairie as a boy and wrote of it in his memoirs after making a home
there away from Washington, D.C.
   ``Goose Prairie is now a part of a technological society which
may in time destroy it,'' wrote Douglas, who died in 1980. ``But
the values of the Prairie are so precious, so unique _ that all who
love the Goose Prairies of this continent will put up a valiant
fight to preserve them.''
   Those words proved prophetic, as environmental groups have lined
up against the U.S. Bureau of Reclamation plans to expand the
reservoir.
   ``Douglas I'm sure would be turning over once again to see this
perennial project has arisen,'' said David Ortman, Northwest
representative for Friends of the Earth and a leading opponent of
the project.
   Ortman said greater water conservation efforts, not bigger
reservoirs, are needed. The dam would inundate 1,600 acres of
never-logged old growth forests, some hundreds of years old, which
provide habitat for creatures not found elsewhere, he said.
   In addition, there would not be enough water to fill the
reservoir for many years, leaving unsightly mud flats, he said.
   Bumping Lake is one of five reservoirs that provide irrigation
to the half-million-acre Yakima Project. Built in 1910, the 60-foot
dam backs up 33,700 acre feet of water that drains from the slopes
of the Cascades, providing water for the fertile but arid Yakima
Valley.
   The $150 million expansion project would include a 240-foot high
dam 4,000 feet downstream from the existing dam, 2 miles from Goose
Prairie. The new dam would create a 458,000 acre foot storage
reservoir.
   A total of 3,000 new acres would be inundated, including some
summer cabins and campgrounds at the lake. The village itself is
below the dam and would not be covered by water, but expansion
opponents fear their lifestyle would be disrupted and resources
like hiking trails would be destroyed.
   The dam is just outside the boundaries of the William O. Douglas
Wilderness area, where such developments would be prohibited.
Douglas opposed just about all development in the area.
   ``I was teaching at Yale when news came that a road would take
the place of the trail'' (to Goose Prairie), he wrote. ``I almost
wept at the thought of pot-bellied, cigar-smoking men roaming
through a sacrosanct valley and polluting it with the noise and
fumes of cars.
   ``I wrote, I protested, complained, but progress won out, as it
usually does.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880418-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WorldProsperity     04-18 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-World Prosperity,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bermudans, Swiss Reported Most Prosperous; US Third</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bermuda residents were the world's most
prosperous in 1986 with an average income of $20,420 a year, the
World Bank reports.
   The Swiss came next with an average of $17,840. Americans were
third with $17,500.
   The U.S. rank was due at least in part to the drop in the price
of the dollar, compared with the Swiss franc and other major
currencies, a descent that began in 1985.
   The rankings are contained in an updated atlas released in
conjunction with last week's semiannual meetings of the bank and
its sister organization, the International Monetary Fund.
   The average income figure for Japan was $12,850, for West
Germany $12,080, for France $10,740 and Britain $8,920. The incomes
do not necessarily represent living standards, since prices and
lifestyles differ so much from country to country.
   Citizens of Brunei, whose average income surpassed those of the
United States in 1985, were down to $15,400 because of the drop in
the price of oil. Brunei is a small country on the southeast Asian
island of Borneo, ruled by an independent sultan.
   At the low end of the scale the bank leaves out many countries
like war-torn Afghanistan and Angola where it does not try to
estimate incomes. The lowest figure _ $120 a year per citizen _
comes from Ethiopia, where two armed revolts have been going on for
many years.
   In Burkina Faso, formerly Upper Volta in southern Africa, the
average is $150. Burkina Faso has had several coups, but no
large-scale fighting.
   There is no estimate for the Soviet Union, which does not belong
to the bank. The average for 1,054,000,718 Chinese is put at $300,
down from $320 in 1985 despite official Chinese claims of rapidly
increasing prosperity.
   In many Third World countries, and not only those that depend on
oil production, average incomes have been going down instead of up.
Especially in Africa and Central America, some have seen a steady
drop since at least 1973. They include Bolivia, the Central African
Republic, Gabon, Guyana, Guinea-Bissau. Gambia, Guatemala,
Honduras, Madagascar, Nicaragua, Nigeria, South Africa, Tanzania
and Zambia.
   The report provides some consolations for lower incomes. An
Australian baby born in 1985, for example, could expect to live for
78 years though his or her share of the national income was only
$12,370. The U.S. baby could count only 76 years though prospects
for income were better.
   French babies also had a 78-year life expectancy. Spanish,
Swiss, Dutch, Norwegian, Swedish and Icelandic babies could all
expect 77 years.
   In the United States 99 percent of all children between the
standard ages of six and 17 were reported in school in 1984.
Because some prosperous countries start primary schooling at five,
the bank put their rates at 100 percent plus. They include Brunei,
Denmark, Iceland, and the French island of New Caledonia in the
south Pacific.
   Japan, despite its tradition of intensive education, rates 97
percent.
   But in Ethiopia and Chad, only one child in four gets to attend
school.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880418-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0126EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NuclearCurriculum     04-18 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Curriculum,0704</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Nuclear Age' Curriculum Stirs Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRAD CAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``nuclear age'' curriculum aimed at
teaching students to peacefully resolve conflicts should be ready
for Oregon classrooms this fall despite concerns that it might
traumatize school children.
   The program was approved by the Legislature after backers said
students aren't being offered the information they need to cope
with a world bristling with the weapons of mass destruction.
   ``We can't let kids grow up with no knowledge and no ability to
handle what is probably the most important subject today, and that
is the threat of nuclear war,'' said Democratic state Rep. Wayne
Fawbush, chief sponsor of the curriculum legislation.
   Critics, however, said the curriculum will frighten and depress
children.
   ``To start pumping this type of stuff into them just seems to be
forcing them to deal with things they're not equipped to deal
with,'' said Lon Mabon, executive director of the conservative
Oregon Citizens Alliance.
   Mabon also said his group suspects the real objective of the
curriculum's backers is to promote nuclear disarmament. But
supporters say that's not true.
   Under the law passed last year, school districts will be
encouraged but not required to use the materials in their
classrooms.
   Chris Dudley, executive director of the Oregon School Boards
Association, said he can't predict how many districts will use the
curriculum once it's drawn up.
   ``It will vary around the state,'' Dudley said. ``I think the
Portland School District expressed interest in it. ... But I think
there will be other districts where the community won't want to
have that kind of curriculum.''
   The state Department of Education is creating the program, for
students in kindergarten through 12th grade. It should be available
to districts after Sept. 1.
   Among other things, the law calls for the curriculum to:
   _improve students' conflict resolution skills and encourage
creative problem solving;
   _provide students with an understanding of other cultures and of
the roots and nature of conflict between cultures;
   _present a discussion of the history of the arms race, the
potential effects and dangers of using modern weapons, and
strategies for preventing war in the nuclear age.
   Fawbush said he recognized the need for such a curriculum after
the 1983 broadcast of ``The Day After,'' the television drama
depicting a nuclear war.
   ``That prompted a lot of national debate,'' he said. ``Some
schools handled it well. But in other districts, including Hood
River, teachers were told not to talk about the issue'' with
students.
   Don Skinner of Salem, a statewide coordinator for Oregon
PeaceWorks, a group that promotes peace issues, said students want
to become involved in the nuclear arms issue.
   ``It's very important for our kids to feel they have a role in
this, because it's their future,'' Skinner said.
   But state Rep. Walter Schroeder called the bill a ``scare
tactic'' that could make students believe that the only way to make
the world safe is to get rid of all nuclear weapons.
   ``I'm one of those who believes in peace through strength, not
peace though weakness,'' the Republican legislator said.
   Fawbush denies there's any intent to promote a particular point
of view.
   ``All we're seeking is a balanced approach to the subject,'' he
said. ``Some people will conclude that we must have clearly drawn
lines and the means to defend those lines. Others will conclude
that what we need to do is erase the lines if possible and reduce
the points of conflict.''
   The Citizens Defense Education Committee, a group that supports
a strong national defense, is monitoring the drafting of the
curriculum to make sure it presents a balanced view.
   Bill Moshofsky, an attorney who is working with the group, says
the organization hopes the curriculum will mention the fact that
nuclear arms so far have acted as a deterrent to another world war.
   ``Having a national defense capability is no different than a
community having a police force,'' said Moshofsky, a former state
Republican Party chairman. ``It recognizes that there are people
out there who are a threat to our security.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
