<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Trade     04-18 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats On Trade Decision: No Going Back on Plant Closings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic leaders appear determined to hand
President Reagan sweeping trade legislation on a
take-it-or-leave-it basis despite a chorus of administration veto
threats.
   ``The die is cast and we'll just have to see how the votes
fall,'' Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, said as Congress moved toward
a head-on collision with the Reagan administration on the trade
issue.
   The root of the conflict is a provision that would require
employers to provide advance notice of plant closings and
large-scale layoffs. Labor is pushing it while the administration
is siding with business groups and threatening a veto.
   Following a decision by the leaders Thursday night to retain the
provision, there were calls for reconsideration from lawmakers who
said it was guaranteed to sink the entire trade bill.
   But Bentsen, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, said
Friday morning it was too late to remove the provision. He also
said it would be ``very difficult'' to pass a watered down version
of the trade bill later in the year if Reagan vetoed this one.
   With the plant-closings provision in the bill, Reagan ``may well
veto it and of course that would make our job tougher,'' he said.
He acknowledged that trying to override such a veto could prove
futile.
   ``It'll be close,'' said Bentsen, who had pushed for a bill
likely to gain a presidential signature rather than a veto.
   That effort ended Thursday when House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas, and Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va.,
decided to support the plant-closings plan.
   Among top Democrats, only House Ways and Means Committee Dan
Rostenkowski, D-Ill., was raising storm signals over that decision.
He said it could mean the nation will ``let trade policy drift for
another three years'' and added that would be ``a tragedy.''
   Republicans are proving less reluctant to forecast the result.
   ``It's time to write the obituary,'' said Sen. John C. Danforth,
R-Mo., one of the chief authors of the legislation, which has been
on the drawing board in Congress for three years.
   ``Now is no time to let the trade bill go down the tubes,''
Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., said.
   The plant-closings provision would require companies with at
least 100 employees to give a 60-day warning of impending factory
shutdowns or layoffs involving 150 workers or more if that
represented one-third of the work force.
   Layoffs of 500 or more would have to be accompanied by notice
regardless of whether they involved one-third of the work force.
   Critics say the measure would prove too burdensome for business
and could be the forerunner of more far-reaching moves to strip
corporate management of its powers. Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin
warns against ``the obvious legal battles, confusion and
confrontation between management and labor that will ensue'' if the
provision becomes law.
   Supporters say too many breadwinners arrive for work only to
find the plant gate locked and their jobs gone without warning.
   ``Vetoing the trade bill because of the plant-closing provision
would be a triumph of right-wing ideology over fairness and common
sense,'' says Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass. ``If business really
wants a world-class work force to meet foreign competition, then
workers deserve help in adjusting to sudden business decisions that
can devastate families and whole communities.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
