<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SAfrica-Churches Bjt   04-18 0816</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Churches, Bjt,0843</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Now Leads Anti-Apartheid Movement In South Africa</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Spelling of Adriaan in 14th graf is cq.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With secular anti-apartheid
groups effectively silenced, clergymen have sharpened their attacks
on the white-led government and rekindled a longstanding
church-state conflict.
   Spared in recent government crackdowns, activist church leaders
represent one of the few prominent opposition forces operating
without restrictions.
   In recent weeks, Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu and other
clergymen have organized and led demonstrations, issued harsh
anti-government statements, focused sermons on political themes and
dared authorities to act against them.
   ``The churches have been pushed to the front line of the
struggle,'' said the Rev. Alan Boesak, president of the World
Alliance of Reformed Churches. ``We have always protested against
apartheid. We must now go over to participate in the resistance
against apartheid.''
   Although President P.W. Botha's National Party government has
refrained from clamping down on the clergymen, it has attempted to
undercut the credibility of Tutu, Boesak and other prominent
ministers.
   Botha regularly refers to South Africa as a country guided by
Christian principles, yet pointedly tells anti-apartheid clergymen
they have no business in politics.
   In recent letters to activist church leaders, Botha said the
clergymen ``love and praise'' the outlawed African National
Congress guerrilla movement, ``with its Marxist and atheistic
ideology.''
   ``You embrace and participate in their call for violence,
hatred, sanctions, insurrection and revolution,'' Botha said. ``The
question must be posed whether you are acting on behalf of the
kingdom of God or the kingdom promised by the ANC.''
   ``I work for God's kingdom,'' replied Tutu, winner of the 1984
Nobel Peace Prize. ``For whose kingdom, with your apartheid policy,
do you work for?''
   At one point, the Anglican church threatened to sue Botha,
saying his statements were defamatory.
   ``I would like that,'' responded Botha. ``Then the government
will come forward with all the knowledge and facts it has at its
disposal.''
   Botha did not elaborate.
   The long-simmering, church-state feud began to boil over after
the government on Feb. 24 banned 18 leading anti-apartheid
organizations from participating in politics. Church leaders
marched on Parliament on Feb. 29 to protest the ban, and 25
clergymen, including Tutu, were briefly arrested.
   In early March, church leaders formed the Committee for the
Defense of Democracy in a bid to fill the void created by the
government crackdown. But within days, Law and Order Minister
Adriaan Vlok barred the new organization from ``performing any
activities or acts whatsoever.''
   Boesak reported March 11 that his house had been stoned and that
he had received death threats. He said that if anything happened to
him ``suspicion should fall on the South African government and the
police.''
   Two weeks later, police searched the home of a Catholic bishop,
Edward Adams, and confiscated documents related to local
organizations in the southern Cape Province.
   ``The state is intent on an open confrontation with the
church,'' the Southern African Catholic Bishops Conference said in
a statement condemning the search.
   Anglican bishops, backed by Archbishop of Canterbury Robert
Runcie in Britain, declared the government had ``launched a
carefully planned attack'' on Tutu, Boesak and others, ``aimed at
portraying them as Marxists and isolating them from their churches
as a prelude to state action against them.''
   However, Botha's verbal attacks on activist clergy have won
support from sectors of the white community, including the Dutch
Reformed Church, the largest white denomination.
   In this deeply religious country, the Dutch Reformed Church has
long had close links to the government and maintained until 1986
that apartheid was justified in the Bible.
   Apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the
25.6 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million
whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools
and health services.
   Dutch Reformed leaders said recently that black clergy do not
represent the Christian church when they confront the state. The
leaders called on Tutu and Boesak to ``divorce themselves from this
impious road and to discuss their problems openly'' with Botha and
Vlok, ``who are both avowed Christians.''
   The anti-apartheid clergy are denounced frequently in letters to
the editor in the pro-government newspapers.
   ``These men are doing Satan's work,'' said one recent letter in
The Citizen, a Johannesburg daily. ``It is hoped that these
troublemakers are dealt with, and not to worry about the cloth they
wear.''
   But the criticism appears only to have strengthened the
ministers' resolve to confront the government.
   ``The government of South Africa has signed its own death
warrant,'' Boesak said in a recent sermon in Cape Town. ``No
government can challenge the living God and survive.''
   ``I am not going to allow this government to choose my friends
for me,'' Tutu said at the same service. ``If teaching the gospel
of Jesus Christ is going to lead me into trouble, tough luck.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880418-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0130EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-IrrigationWoes     04-18 0861</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Irrigation Woes,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gas Prices Triple for Farm Irrigators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tony Leddy, a southwest Kansas farmer,
received an unwelcome $75,000 surprise in his mail earlier this
year.
   A letter notified Leddy of a near tripling of the price of
natural gas used to power irrigation pumps supplying water for
2,900 acres of land that he and his father-in-law farm near the
community of Ulysses.
   The increase will raise his yearly bill from about $24,000 to
nearly $75,000, making irrigation fuel the single largest expense
for his farming operation.
   ``I know if the average consumer had a 300 percent jump in their
natural gas bill, Washington would sure hear about it,'' says
Leddy, 34, who has been farming for 14 years.
   ``If their gas bill would go from $45 to $150 a month ... then
something would be done. But we're a small isolated pocket of
individuals out here and don't have the masses to support that kind
of an effort.''
   Legislation has been introduced in Congress to roll back the
prices increases, and similar relief proposals have been offered in
state legislatures in Kansas and Oklahoma. But with a doubtful
outlook for legislation, farmers also are negotiating with gas
companies to try to obtain lower prices.
   Farmers say they could be forced to abandon irrigation in some
cases. And that prospect threatens not only the livelihoods of farm
families but the region's fragile agriculturally dependent economy.
   ``It's very obviously going to eliminate some people from the
business without a doubt,'' says Randal Loder, a Garden City, Kan.
farmer.
   The culprit, according to irrigators, is a 1986 order by the
Federal Energy Regulatory Commission raising the maximum price that
can be charged for natural gas in production before 1978.
   In effect, the government freed gas producers to seek higher
prices from their pipeline purchasers. But that also translated
into bigger bills for irrigators who buy unprocessed gas straight
from the wellhead.
   ``Frankly we were not surprised there was an increase, but the
surprise was that it was so dramatic, so quick,'' says Larry
Kepley, a board member of the Southwest Kansas Irrigators
Association.
   ``The first any of the producers knew was here came a bill that
translated into three times as high as any they had been paying
before.''
   Farmers in southwest Kansas and the Oklahoma panhandle, a dry
region transformed into an agricultural oasis through irrigation,
sit atop the Hugoton gas field, one of the largest in the world.
   According to Kepley, there are about 11,500 gas-powered
irrigation wells in southwest Kansas and more than 3,000 in
Oklahoma.
   Because the Hugoton field has been in production for decades,
its gas has been some of the cheapest in the nation for pipelines
and their utility customers.
   The FERC order was designed to bring down high-priced gas at the
same time allowing cheaper regulated gas to rise to market levels.
   In Leddy's case, the cost jumped from 53 cents to $1.50 for a
thousand cubic feet, or mcf.
   Loder saw his gas costs go from 55 cents to $1.24, and $1.50 an
mcf for some of his 14 wells. Yet he continues to see no drop in
price for one well that costs $4.25 an mcf. ``I've been hit in the
pocketbook extensively,'' he complains.
   Gas producers defend the FERC order.
   ``It's worked pretty well,'' says Mike Waters, a spokesman for
the Natural Gas Supply Association, a producer group.
   John Stow, a spokesman in Washington for Amoco Production Co.,
one of the companies that operates in the Hugoton field, says
irrigators are not treated differently than the company's other gas
customers. He says the company also opposes any legislation to
control gas prices for irrigators.
   But irrigators contend they should be treated differently: most
of their gas purchases come during the spring and summer when
residential use is lowest and they usually buy raw, sometimes
low-quality gas.
   Few alternatives are available. Farmers in southwest Kansas say
diesel fuel and electricity are too expensive to replace natural
gas.
   Compounding the problem is the uncertainty of future prices. The
FERC order allows what, in effect, are floating prices. Some
irrigators were hit with a doubling or tripling of prices early
this year, but then saw them return months later to 50 cents to 60
cents.
   Irrigators say the changing prices make it nearly impossible to
accurately project their production expenses, can leave them short
of cash and ruin their cropping plans.
   ``It makes it real difficult to plan and your banker sure
doesn't understand it,'' says Kansas state Rep. Gene Shore, who has
sponsored legislation in the Legislature to help irrigators.
   Leddy, for example, prepared some irrigated acreage last fall
for growing corn. That was months before he received his January
price increase notice. He intends to stick with his irrigation
plans but ``we are monitoring all our expenses right down to the
penny.''
   ``We just feel like no major business can really truly absorb a
300 percent jump on something that is a major input like natural
gas is for us,'' says Leddy. ``They would try to do everything they
could to alleviate the problem.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
