<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PeaceCorps-Teachers     04-18 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peace Corps-Teachers,200</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release at 9:45 a.m. EDT; time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>Peace Corps, NEA Launching New One-Year Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine Virginia school teachers will become
Peace Corps Volunteers in Ghana for a year as part of an effort to
double the number of volunteers abroad, the Peace Corps announced
today.
   The new one-year program _ volunteers normally serve for two
years _ will help teachers in Ghana develop new courses, said Peace
Corps Director Loret Miller Ruppe.
   She said the Peace Corps, which hopes to increase its volunteers
from about 5,000 to 10,000 by 1992, has requests for more teachers
from many of the 60 countries where volunteers now serve. More U.S.
educators will be enlisted under the new Leadership for Peace
program, Ms. Ruppe said.
   The first assignments in the program resulted from a cooperative
effort involving the Peace Corps, the National Education
Association and the Commonwealth of Virginia. A Peace Corps news
release said Virginia has been taking steps to internationalize its
education, using former Peace Corps volunteers to help make
teachers and students more aware of other peoples and cultures.
   The teachers nominated for the program include elementary,
intermediate and high school teachers from eight different schools.
</TEXT>
