<HEAD>Kennedy Stumps For Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENSBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Edward Kennedy is predicting that
Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis will win the presidential
nomination at the Democratic Convention this summer.
   ``I have never felt it will be a brokered convention. I think
Gov. Dukakis will be a success, and he'll have the votes to win,''
Kennedy told about 1,300 guests on Sunday at the annual spring
dinner of the Westmoreland County Democratic Committee.
   Kennedy, D-Mass., said he believes Dukakis will ``be a success
in New York on Tuesday, the day of its primary.'' He added that
Dukakis does not take the April 26 Pennsylvania primary ``lightly.''
   Asked whether he will ever run for the presidency, Kennedy said,
``I've indicated my concern is not constantly pursuing the
presidency, but working with public policy.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Schroeder Says Candidates Miss Point</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Instead of talking about defense, the
presidential candidates should be focusing on the social problems
that confront Americans, Rep. Patricia Schroeder said.
   The presidential hopefuls focus on economic and international
issues, she told more than 260 people who attended the third annual
Women's Fair at Lakewood Hospital on Saturday.
   ``Obviously we want America to be strong, but what are we going
to do with the family?'' she asked. ``Families are the foundation
of this government. Based on that, our government is in trouble.''
   Schroeder, a Colorado Democrat who considered entering the
presidential race last summer, said the primary concerns of
Americans are ``education, child care and how people will afford
the American dream.''
   Schroeder, a member of the House Armed Services committee and
16-year congresswoman, said women should not feel guilty about
asking for equal rights.
   ``As long as they are going to take taxes from us equally, they
might as well treat us equally,'' she said.
