<DOCNO> AP880418-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0457EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Markets     04-18 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Fall in Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed slightly lower today against the
Japanese yen in Tokyo, while stock prices declined substantially in
slow trading.
   On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange market, the dollar closed at
123.78 yen, down 0.35 yen from Friday's close of 124.13 yen. It
opened at 123.83 yen and fluctuated between 123.68 yen and 123.85
yen.
   Volume totaled $4.34 billion, compared with $6.189 billion last
Friday.
   A Bank of Tokyo dealer, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the market in Tokyo was quiet with nothing to stimulate it.
   The dealer said the Bank of Japan intervened slightly when the
dollar went down to 123.70 yen, but the intervention did not have
any impact on the market.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which fell 217.78 points Friday, lost 222.12
points to finish the day at 26.671.45 points.
   Volume on the market's first section totaled 550 million shares,
compared with 1 billion shares Friday.
   An official of Nomura Securities Co. said, ``the market was dull
as there were no special news to attract investors.''
   He added that investors appeared to be staying on the sidelines,
watching new moves following last Thursday's report that the U.S.
trade deficit widened in February.
   The official, who also demanded anonymity, said steel,
electrical and auto issues were particularly weak.
</TEXT>
