<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HospitalBabyDeath     04-18 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hospital Baby Death,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Infant's Drowning In Toilet Under Investigation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drowning of a newborn girl in a toilet at a
state psychiatric hospital could not have been foreseen, a state
official says.
   But mental health advocates say it points out the problems of
underfunded, understaffed hospitals.
   The girl, born Tuesday night to a patient at the Chicago-Read
Mental Health Center, died by drowning, an autopsy showed. The
infant was found in the toilet about 15 minutes after staff members
had checked the mother in her bed, said David Devane, spoeksman for
the state Department of Mental Health.
   The staff check around 8 p.m. showed the woman, who was nine
months pregnant, was ``resting comfortably with no indication of
rapid breathing or anything to indicate labor,'' Devane said Sunday.
   Staff members found the infant after they saw blood on the lower
part of the mother's body, Devane said.
   ``The trail of blood went back to the bathroom,'' he said.
   Devane said the 34-year-old woman, identified by police as
Patricia Ales, was checked every 15 minutes because of her
pregnancy. He declined to discuss her mental condition.
   Chicago Police Sgt. Thomas Czarnecki said an autopsy determined
that the baby had drowned. He said he did not expect charges to be
filed against the mother.
   Mental health advocates questioned how a woman could give birth
unnoticed in a crowded hospital unit.
   ``I find it incredible that this could happen and nobody knew
she was in labor,'' said Jan Holcomb, former president of the
Mental Health Association in Illinois, a private advocacy group.
   ``Does it take the death of a newborn baby to recognize that our
underfunded and understaffed state mental health facilities can
pose a threat to the health and safety of our most vulnerable
citizens?''
   Devane said the staff did everything possible.
   ``There were four people on the unit, four staff members,''
Devane said. ``She (the mother) was under close observation and
that close observation had been followed.''
   The woman had been examined by her obstetrician at the
University of Illinois' downtown clinic earlier that day, Devane
said. The doctor did not indicate any need for her to go to a
maternity ward, he said.
   The Chicago Tribune reported that fire department paramedics
responded to a call of ``woman in labor'' at 8:14 p.m. When they
arrived, the newspaper said, they were first directed to the
mother, who was hemorrhaging, and then were told by an unidentified
staff member that a baby was in the bathroom toilet, police records
show.
</TEXT>
