<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Continental-Fire     04-18 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Continental-Fire,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smoky Fire Forces Passengers To Evacuate Jet</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Continental-Safety</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A smoky electrical fire in an overhead luggage
compartment of a Continental Airlines jet forced the 103 passengers
to use emergency chutes to evacuate after it landed at Cleveland
Hopkins International Airport.
   Six of the 103 passengers aboard the Boeing 737 were treated at
two hospitals for smoke inhalation.
   Continental Airlines spokesman Bruce Hicks said Flight 159 was
bound for Cleveland from Newark, N.J., when smoke was detected
during the final minutes of Sunday night's flight.
   ``It was a safe landing. We just evacuated the cabin to make
absolutely sure that everyone was safe,'' Hicks said.
   The fire was extinguished by airport firefighters.
   Mort Edelstein, a spokesman for the Federal Aviation
Administration, said the fire was caused by a short in the wires
powering lights above the seats. The wires are located behind a
liner in the overhead storage bins.
   Passenger Peter Munro of Boston said he did not see any flames
but saw a lot of smoke.
   ``The smoke was waist high and higher in the front of the plane.
In the back, it was completely black. It was pretty frantic,'' said
Munro.
