<1ST_LINE>d p PM-BRF-NHGovernor     04-18 0138</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF-NH Governor,0141</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McEachern Launches Third Try For New Hampshire Governor's Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEMBROKE, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Calling Gov. John Sununu contemptuous of
New Hampshire, Democrat Paul McEachern announced his third bid to
become the state's chief executive.
   ``New Hampshire is not a franchise _ to be opened for
development _ but a place to be protected as we pass,'' McEachern,
a Portsmouth lawyer, told several hundred cheering supporters
Sunday at Pembroke Academy.
   McEachern accused the Republican governor of turning his back on
education, giving the state away to developers and relying too much
on the ``nuclear pellet'' with his continued support of the
Seabrook nuclear power plant.
   McEachern, 50, twice mentioned his opposition to finished but
unlicensed Seabrook.
   McEachern, who expects to be unopposed in the September primary,
lost to Sununu by 8 percentage points in 1986.
</TEXT>
