<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PowerboatCrash     04-18 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Powerboat Crash,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Die When Powerboat Flips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A specially designed cockpit
wasn't enough to save two powerboat racers who were killed when
their boat hit the peak of a wave and flipped, authorities and
witnesses said.
   The Spirit of Miss Liberty, racing Saturday in the Sportsman D
class of larger boats, was traveling nearly 100 mph in the Gulf of
Mexico less than 1,000 feet offshore when it crashed, witnesses
said.
   ``It was one of the fastest boats out there,'' said Panama City
Beach resident Jack Woodliff.
   Killed in the accident were the boat's owner and pilot, Thomas
Brandt of Gulf Stream, and the throttleman, Don Wright of Fort
Lauderdale, police said. Their ages were unavailable.
   The boat's enclosed cockpit reportedly was designed to lessen
the impact in case of an accident and was believed to improve the
aerodynamics of the 30-foot Chris Craft.
</TEXT>
