<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0601EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w BC-US-Gulf 4thLd-Writethru a0521 04-18 0761</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-US-Gulf, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0521,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Calls Shelling a ``Measured Response'' to Iran's
Mining</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Fixes typo in 2d graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, retaliating for the mining
of a U.S. Navy frigate, ordered the shelling of Iranian offshore
oil platforms in the Persian Gulf Monday in what the White House
called ``a measured response to Iran's unlawful use of force.''
   The United States had said there was ``substantial evidence''
that Iran had planted a mine that blew a hole in the side of the
USS Samuel B. Roberts in the central Gulf last week and injured 10
crewmen.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said there were no
American casualties in the shelling and the United States did not
know of any on the Iranian side.
   Fitzwater said Reagan decided on the attack Sunday night during
meetings in the residence section of the White House.
   He said Reagan met with Secretary of State George P. Shultz,
National Security Adviser Colin Powell and others at 8:30 p.m. EDT
Sunday, then briefed congressional leaders and met with his
advisers for ``fine tuning'' of the decision.
   The spokesman said he did not know how many people were aboard
the platforms, although they normally have a complement of 20 to 40
men. They are manned by Iranian Revolutionary Guards. He said they
were given several minutes warning to leave, and some were seen
leaving.
   Fitzwater said the frigates Simpson and Bagley and the cruiser
Wainwright took part in the attack on the Sirri platform, which he
said is 18 miles off Sirri island. He said the destroyers Merril
and McCormick and the landing platform ship Trenton, which carries
helicopters, took part in the attack on the Sassan.
   He said there was no indication of resistance. The platforms
were still burning about three hours after the attack.
   Fitzwater said the Sassan platform had been boarded by Marines,
who were setting charges to destroy it.
   Fitzwater said four Iranian F4 fighters took off during the
attack, but returned to their base without firing. He said aircraft
from the U.S. aircraft carrier Enterprise were in the air during
the shelling, but he did not know whether they took any part. He
said he understood all of the firing was from the ships.
   Fitzwater said the attack represented ``a measured response to
Iran's unlawful use of force against the United States and to
Iran's numerous violations of the rights of other non-belligerents.
And they constitute a lawful excerise of the United States'
inherent right of self defense under Article 51 of the United
Nations Charter.''
   Reagan first met with top advisers on Friday to decide upon a
response to the mining of the Roberts, a guided missile frigate
which came close to sinking.
   The incident was the second of its nature since the United
States began escorting oil tankers through the gulf on July 21,
1987 to protect them from attack from the warring parties in the
7{-year Iran-Iraqn war.
   On Oct. 19, a raid was staged in retaliation to a missile attack
on a Kuwaiti ship flying the U.S. flag in which 18 Americans were
injured. Two Iranian oil platforms were destroyed in what Reagan
termed a ``prudent'' response.
   Reporters were summoned to the White House for a 2:30 a.m. EDT
briefing on Monday. By time it was under way, an hour later, news
reports on the shelling had been received from the Persian Gulf.
   In a written statement, Fitzwater said, ``The government of Iran
should understand that we will protect our ships and our
interests'' against such attacks.
   ``These platforms are used as command and control radar stations
for the Iranian military,'' he said of the targets.
   ``The government of Iran has repeatedly been warned about the
consequences of such hostile acts'' as the mining of the Gulf, he
said.
   Fitzwater said the ``friendly governments'' had been informed in
advance.
   ``We have repeatedly told Iran that we do not desire military
confrontation,'' Fitzwater said. ``But the government of Iran
should understand that we will protect our ships and our interests
against unprovoked attacks.''
   ``We urgently seek an end to tensions in the region and to the
Iran-Iraq war,'' he said. ``This would benefit the people of both
nations who have suffered so much from the brutal conflict.''
   Fitzwater said the United States is urging Iran to accept a
United Nations Security Council resolution, passed July 20, calling
for a cease-fire in the seven-year-old Iran-Iraq war.
   ``Iran has nothing to gain from continuation of the war,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
