<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     04-18 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Hampshire Digging Out From Snowy Onslaught</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   New Hampshire dug out from more than a foot of snow today and
Idaho cleaned up debris left by two tornadoes as much of the nation
was hit by scattered showers and heavy thunderstorms.
   A storm turned New Hampshire's north country into a winter
wonderland Sunday, dumping up to 14 inches of snow in the lowlands
and more than 33 inches atop Mount Washington.
   Meteorologist Chris Norcross said Mount Washington's 6,288-foot
peak received 33.5 inches of snow, with light snow likely to
continue for several days. Pittsburg, in northernmost New
Hampshire, reported 14 inches, Dixville Notch 12 inches and
Crawford and Pinkham notches 8 inches.
   Thunderstorms spawned tornadoes in Idaho on Sunday night. One
tornado touched down near in the southeastern town of Ririe,
destroying a shed and carrying a telephone pole across a field. The
second tornado struck south of nearby Roberts.
   Meanwhile, thunderstorms moving slowly across the lower
Mississippi Valley produced 1-inch sized hail and damaging winds in
Louisiana on Sunday. The winds downed numerous trees in Bienville
County.
   But skies were fair over the southern and mid-Atlantic states
early this morning, as well as over the northern Plains and upper
Mississippi Valley.
   The forecast for today called for showers and thunderstorms
across the Southeastern, the Tennessee Valley and the Carolinas
into the central Appalachians and mid-Atlantic states; showers from
the upper Ohio Valley, New England, the Pacific Northwest, and
south into the central inter-mountain region and Arizona; and snow
across Michigan.
   High temperatures will be in the 50s or 60s across much of the
nation; in the 30s across the northern Great Lakes; in the 40s from
the northern Plains into the lower Great Lakes and over northern
Maine; in the 70s from the Southern California valleys and desert
Southwest, and from west-central Texas through the lower
Mississippi Valley into the southern Atlantic coast; in the 80s
across much of Florida and from the Louisiana coast into southern
Texas; and near 90 in parts of the lower Rio Grande Valley.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 19 at
Bismarck, N.D., Fargo, N.D., and Warroad, Minn., to 77 at Laredo,
Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 62 partly cloudy; Boston 48 fair; Buffalo 46
rain; Charleston, S.C., 64 fair; Cincinnati 64 cloudy; Cleveland 48
showers; Detroit 38 windy; Miami 70 fair; New York 49 fair;
Philadelphia 53 fair; Pittsburgh 62 windy; Portland, Maine, cloudy;
Washington 57 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 19 fair; Chicago 42 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 57 fair; Denver 39 cloudy; Des Moines 40 cloudy;
Indianapolis 47 showers; Kansas City 47 windy; Minneapolis-St. Paul
32 fair; Nashville 58 rain; New Orleans 72 cloudy; St. Louis 49
rain.
   _West: Albuquerque 43 partly cloudy; Anchorage 40 cloudy; Las
Vegas 54 fair; Los Angeles 58 cloudy; Phoenix 59 cloudy; Salt Lake
City 56 cloudy; San Diego 60 cloudy; San Francisco 53 cloudy;
Seattle 47 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 52 cloudy; Toronto 43 windy.
</TEXT>
