<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Germany-AirCrash     04-18 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Air Crash,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Air Force F-16 Jet Crashes In West Germany Injuring Pilot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RAMSTEIN AIR BASE, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Air Force F-16
fighter jet crashed today in a field near the West German border
with Luxembourg, slightly injuring the pilot when he ejected, an
Air Force spokeswoman said.
   It was third crash of a fighter plane over the densely populated
country since March 30. A U.S. Army helicopter also crashed earlier
this month.
   ``A U.S. Air Force F-16C crashed near Erzberg at 9:10 a.m. (3:10
a.m. EDT),'' staff Sgt. Linda Brandon said. Erzberg is a small
village located near the West German border with Luxembourg. She
said the aircraft ``was on a low-level training mission at the time
of the crash.''
   The pilot ejected safely from the F-16 before the craft plowed
into an open field. Ms. Brandon said he was taken to the U.S.
Army's Landsthul hospital near Kaiserslautern in southwestern West
Germany.
   ``He suffered no serious injuries but is being kept for
observation,'' Brandon said. The pilot was not immediately
identified.
   Brandon, reading from a statement, said the aircraft was
assigned to the 86th Tactical Fighter Wing, which is based at
Ramstein Air Base, also near Kaiserslautern.
   ``A board of officers will investigate the accident,'' said
Brandon.
   She said additional details would be provided ``as they become
available.'' It was the second crash of a U.S. Air Force fighter
since March 31, when an F-16C went down in the town of Forst, 12
miles north of Karlsruhe.
   That crash killed the pilot, 24-year-old Lt. Thomas Edward Doyle
of Oroville, Calif., and a West German resident on the ground. The
crash also demolished three houses.
   A day earlier, a French Mirage crashed less than one mile from a
nuclear power plant in Bavaria, killing the French air force pilot.
   On April 5, a U.S. Army lieutenant and West German employee of
the Army died when an Army helicopter crashed. The American was
identified as 1st Lt. Glen P. Adams, 28.
   West German anti-nuclear activists have demanded restrictions on
military flights over the nation, as has the Association of German
Aviation, a private pilots' organization.
</TEXT>
