<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Eichmann     04-18 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Eichmann,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel First Tried Nazi War Criminal in 1961</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Demjanjuk, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Demjanjuk is the second man to be tried in
Israel for Nazi war crimes. In 1961, a special court heard the case
of Adolf Eichmann, found him guilty and sentenced him to death.
   A year later, Eichmann was hanged, the only person to have been
executed in Israel's 40-year history.
   Although Demjanjuk could suffer Eichmann's fate, there are many
differences between the two men and their trials.
   Above all, there was no doubt about Eichmann's guilt.
   His Nazi wartime record was well documented. He was considered a
high-ranking leader of the Nazi regime and was the man in charge of
carrying out his government's orders to exterminate European Jewry.
   Unlike Demjanjuk, Eichmann never denied committing the wartime
deeds of which he was accused. Also, Eichmann's trial was held 17
years after the end of the war, when the memory of the Holocaust
was still fresh and many of those who survived it still alive.
   His presence aroused so much anger in Israel that the
authorities built a bulletproof glass booth to protect him during
the open-court proceedings in Jerusalem.
   The Israeli government regarded the trial as an historic
settling of accounts with the Nazi movement. Eichmann was regarded
not only as a man who had committed unspeakable crimes, but also as
a symbol of the entire Nazi regime which was being brought to
justice by the Jewish people.
   The accused contributed to the sense of national outrage in
Israel by his demeanor. He observed his trial in silence, with a
sardonic smile on his face, and never expressed regret for his
deeds.
   The Austrian-born Eichmann became the perfect stereotype of the
cold and ruthless Nazi killing machine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880418-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0715EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     04-18 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed In Nervous Trading, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in early European trading
today amid fears of central bank intervention if the American
currency moves lower. Gold prices were slightly higher.
   Market sentiment remains extremely bearish toward the dollar
because of disappointment over the widened February trade deficit,
dealers said.
   Traders ``are not touching the dollar, afraid that the central
banks might step in,'' said one Rome dealer on condition of
anonymity. ``The dollar is only moving as a result of cross
trading.''
   Traders noted that banks intervened heavily in support of the
U.S. currency after the trade figures were released last week.
   Britain's pound sterling continued strong on high interest rates.
   ``People are wondering whether we'll see another base rate cut
in Britain this week, though I'm not expecting one,'' one dealer at
a U.S. bank in Frankfurt said.
   A cut in the basic interest rate would make the pound less
attractive to buyers and strengthen the dollar.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.35 yen to a closing 123.78. But later, in
London, it rose to 124.40 yen, higher than Friday's close of 124.13
yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's
rates:
   _1.6625 West German marks, up from 1.6605
   _1.3750 Swiss francs, up from 1.3720
   _5.6455 French francs, up from 5.6325
   _1.85885 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8630
   _1,231.00 Italian lire, down from 1,232.50
   _1.2305 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2335
   In London, the British pound rose against the dollar. It cost
$1.8925 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.889 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $456.75 a troy ounce and
at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $457.55. Both were higher than Friday's late
bid of $456.25.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $457, up from $455.50 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.03 to close at a bid $457.98.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.515 a
troy ounce, up from Friday's $6.49.
</TEXT>
