<DOCNO> AP880418-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0719EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Demjanjuk-Highlights     04-18 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Demjanjuk-Highlights,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Highlights of Demjanjuk Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Demjanjuk, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The following is a summary of prosecution and
defense arguments in the Nazi war crimes trial of John Demjanjuk:
   
   THE PROSECUTION:
   The prosecution claims Demjanjuk is ``Ivan the Terrible,'' a
brutal guard who operated gas chambers that killed 850,000 Jews at
the Treblinka death camp in Nazi-occupied Poland in 1942 and 1943.
   Prosecutors presented five Treblinka survivors who identified
Demjanjuk as ``Ivan'' in photo lineups that included a 1952 picture
of the defendant and another taken from his alleged Nazi identity
card.
   Survivor Pinchas Epstein pointed to Demjanjuk in court and said
he recognized the defendant's walk, while survivor Eliyahu
Rosenberg said he remembered Demjanjuk's ``murderous eyes.''
   The prosecution's most pivotal evidence was Demjanjuk's alleged
Nazi identity card. Issued at Trawniki, a training camp for death
camp guards, the document does not mention Treblinka but states
Demjanjuk was posted at the nearby Sobibor death camp.
   Six prosecution experts authenticated the paper, ink, photograph
and signatures on the Trawniki card. One expert produced a video
showing how the photograph of the young guard on the card matched
the present-day Demjanjuk almost exactly. In addition, two
historians vouched for the document's historical authenticity.
   In a grueling week-long cross-examination, prosecutors showed
inconsistencies in Demjanjuk's version of his whereabouts during
World War II and accused him of hiding his true identity.
   
   THE DEFENSE:
   Demjanjuk claims he is an innocent victim of mistaken identity
and says he was a Nazi prisoner-of-war during the years of
Treblinka's operation, 1942-43.
   Demjanjuk admits he lied on his U.S. immigration application,
saying he was a Polish farmer rather than a Ukrainian soldier, but
he insists it was because he feared forced repatriation to the
Soviet Union and not because he was hiding a Nazi past.
   A psychology expert raised doubts about the reliability of the
Treblinka survivors' memories more than 40 years after the
Holocaust. He also contended the photo lineups were biased against
Demjanjuk because his picture was the largest, clearest and the
only one of a bald man.
   Demjanjuk's attorneys presented 12 statements from Treblinka
inmates who failed to identify Demjanjuk's picture as ``Ivan.''
   Demjanjuk claims the Trawniki card was forged by the Soviet
Union, which provided it and three other other similar documents to
Israel. He says the Soviets wanted to frame Demjanjuk because he
served in an anti-Communist unit organized by the Germans at the
end of World War II.
   The defense also called six experts who contended the Trawniki
card was forged. One document expert said the paper could not have
been produced in Nazi Germany because it was made of rags, a
material that was scarce during World War II.
   Defense witnesses also said Demjanjuk's signature on the card
was forged and contended the picture on the document, even if it
portrayed Demjanjuk, was not the original but had been glued on at
a later date.
   Several defense witnesses were discredited, including one who
retracted her testimony and another who tried to commit suicide
after her credentials were called into question.
   Some defense witnesses also offered bizarre arguments, including
one who claimed the Soviet secret service used ``thought power'' to
kill its enemies and inflict disasters on the West.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880418-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0730EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-DemjanjukProfile     04-18 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Demjanjuk Profile,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demjanjuk Describes Himself As Simple Man Who `Can't Think
Properly'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Demjanjuk, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Demjanjuk, the second man to be tried in
Israel for Nazi war crimes, says he is a simple man with a
fourth-grade education who survived near-starvation in the Soviet
Ukraine by eating birds, rats and a pet cat.
   ``My tragic mistake is I can't think properly. I don't know how
to answer,'' the retired Ohio autoworker told an Israeli court in a
revealing moment.
   Demjanjuk has become more human to many Israelis than Adolf
Eichmann, the first man to stand trial for Nazi war crimes, because
he learned some Hebrew and his family attended nearly every session.
   The Israeli prosecution says Demjanjuk is ``Ivan the Terrible,''
who operated gas chambers that killed 850,000 Jews at the Treblinka
death camp in Nazi-occupied Poland in 1942 and 1943.
   During the trial, Demjanjuk chatted with police guards, laughed
good naturedly during sessions and shouted the Hebrew greeting
``Shalom'' to bystanders as he was led handcuffed to and from court.
   He even tried to shake hands with a Treblinka survivor, who
recoiled in horror and called Demjanjuk a murderer.
   Before being yanked into the public eye by charges he was a
brutal Nazi guard, the 68-year-old grandfather lived a quiet life
centered on family and friends in Cleveland's close-knit Ukrainian
community, where Demjanjuk emigrated in 1952.
   When he took the stand in Israel, Demjanjuk endeavored to win
sympathy by describing his own hardships in the Soviet Ukraine and
portraying himself as a mild-mannered man who ``couldn't even kill
a chicken.''
   ``Me and my relatives were forced to eat birds, mice, rats and
even our pet cat,'' Demjanjuk said of his childhood in the Ukraine
in 1932 and 1933.
   The balding defendant tried to explain away inconsistencies in
his version of his whereabouts during World War II by blaming his
lack of education and faulty memory.
   ``What do you expect when I had only four years of schooling?''
he said in helpless frustration during a grueling weeklong
cross-examination last August.
   Demjanjuk's three children describe their father as a patient,
good-natured man who tried to make life more homey in his dreary
Israeli isolation cell by hanging hundreds of cards from
well-wishers and family photographs onto the walls.
   Alone in his prison cell, Demjanjuk lifted his spirits by
reading from a Ukrainian-language Bible and doing sit-ups and
push-ups to relieve tension, his children said in interviews.
   Demjanjuk and his wife, Vera, 62, worked long factory shifts to
attain a measure of the good life. They bought a house in the
middle-class Cleveland suburb of Seven Hills, where Demjanjuk
planted a garden and planned to retire.
   ``My dad enjoyed seeing things grow. He was squeamish about
killing anything, even worms in the garden,'' said Demjanjuk's
daughter, Irene Nishnic, 28.
   On Aug. 25, 1977, the first accusations against Demjanjuk
appeared in the U.S. media.
   After a six-week trial in Feb. 1981 in a U.S. District Court in
Cleveland, when Demjanjuk admitted lying to immigration authorites,
he was stripped of his U.S. citizenship.
   He was extradited to Israel in February 1986 and his
14-month-long trial began one year later.
   Describing her father, Mrs. Nishnic said: ``My dad is a good
man, a loving man. He's never beat on me, he's never hurt me. But
that's not going to make any difference, is it?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880418-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0742EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MILSTAR     04-18 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-MILSTAR,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top-Secret Satellite Costs May be Rocketing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ultra-secret multi-satellite program
intended to help coordinate the nation's nuclear weapons appears to
be facing serious problems, including budget overruns and technical
obstacles, a newspaper reported.
   The San Jose Mercury News said the 5-year-old MILSTAR program at
Lockheed Missiles & Space Co. is supposed to be tough enough to
survive an all-out war, smart enough to run itself for six months
at a time and sophisticated enough to link just about every ship,
plane and battlefield unit with a nuclear weapon.
   But a congressional report prepared in December reported
``pervasive problems'' and cost overruns in MILSTAR, which is short
for military strategic and tactical relay system, the newspaper
said in its Sunday editions.
   The report blamed the problems on ``repeated changes in
acquisition schedules, inadequate funding, poor contracting
procedures and a lack of management attention at the senior levels
of the Department of Defense and Air Force.''
   ``Hundreds of millions of dollars, perhaps as much as a billion
dollars, could be wasted over the next decade,'' it warned.
   The newspaper quoted an unidentified congressional source as
saying contracts weren't written to encourage Lockheed and its
subcontractors enough to save money. Fluctuations in Air Force
financing led to inefficiencies on the production lines, the source
said.
   ``There were an awful lot of problems,'' said the source, who
asked not to be identified. But, the source added, ``that doesn't
mean it's a dog of a program.''
   Congress recently authorized an additional $25 million above
what has been allocated for the project this year. The project's
budget is secret; the newspaper said the budget was ``estimated at
$10 billion or perhaps much more.''
   ``The MILSTAR program, we think, is proceeding well,'' said Lt.
Col. Rick Oborn, a spokesman for the Air Force. ``We do realize
there are some techinical challenges, and there are some minor
setbacks.
   ``But given the technical risks those setbacks are not
insurmountable. It is a program designed as the highest national
priority,'' he said.
   Richard Buenneke, editor of the industry newsletter Military
Space, was more skeptical.
   ``They're obviously using the security around the program to
hide a lot of the problems with it,'' said Buenneke.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
