<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Gulf-Shelling 3rdLd-Writethru a0535 04-18 1012</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Shelling, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0535,1040</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Warships Attack Two Iranian Oil Platforms In Gulf, Iran
Retaliates</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with attack on U.S. vessels and to
tighten. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. warships today attacked two offshore
Iranian oil facilities in the Persian Gulf in retaliation for a
mine explosion that ripped open the hull of an American frigate and
injured 10 crewmen.
   Iran countered by striking oil facilities off Sharjah and at
least two U.S. vessels.
   The White House said three U.S. warships ships attacked each
Iranian platform and that the facilities were on fire. No American
casualties were reported in the U.S. attacks, and the Iranians
reportedly fled prior to the shelling.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency said the U.S. warships
first struck the Sassan platform in the southern gulf at 9 a.m.
(1:30 a.m. EDT). Twenty-three minutes later they blasted the Nasr
platform at nearby Sirri Island, IRNA said.
   Soon afterward, an Iranian warship shelled oil facilities off
Sharjah, an emirate in the southern gulf, shipping executives said.
   Targeted in the Iranian attack were the Scanbay drilling rig,
the 112,744-ton British tanker York Marine and a storage facility.
All three are in the Mubarak oilfield off Sharjah, the gulf-based
executives said.
   The executives, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
York Marine was set afire and that its crew had abandoned the
vessel.
   A Reagan administration official in Washington said an Iranian
guided missile patrol boat had fired on the U.S. cruiser
Wainwright, one of the American ships that took part in the attack
on one of the Iranian platforms.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
Wainwright was not hit. He said the U.S. frigate Simpson returned
fire and scored a direct hit on the patrol boat. Asked if the
Iranian ship was sunk, he said only, ``It scored a direct hit; use
your imagination.''
   The official also said a U.S. supply vessel, the Willy Tide, was
under attack by three Iranian speedboats. He said he had no other
details.
   The London-based Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit also
reported the attack on the Willy Tide, a 283-ton vessel operated by
Tidewater Inc. of New Orleans.
   Iran and Iraq have been at war since 1980, and the war has
produced repeated attacks on neutral shipping. Last July, the
United States stepped up its presence in the gulf, reflagging 11
Kuwaiti tankers and giving them U.S. Navy escorts.
   The U.S. raid on the Iranian oil platforms was confirmed by the
White House early today after it was reported by Iran and the
shipping executives. The White House said the attack was ``a
measured response to Iran's unlawful use of force.''
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said there were no U.S. casualties in
the raid and the United States did not know of any on the Iranian
side.
   ``These actions,'' he said, ``were taken in response to Iran's
recent resumption of mine laying in international waters and its
mine attack (Thursday) on the USS (frigate) Samuel B. Roberts ...
The government of Iran has repeatedly been warned about the
consequences of such hostile acts.''
   Fitzwater said he did not know how many people were aboard the
platforms, although they normally have a complement of 20 to 40
men. They are manned by Iranian Revolutionary Guards. He said they
were given several minutes warning, and some were seen leaving.
   The White House spokesman said the frigates Simpson and Bagley
and the cruiser Wainwright attacked the Sirri platform. He said the
platform is 18 miles off Sirri Island. Iran's statement, monitored
in Cyprus, said the platform was on the island. The two reports
could not be reconciled immediately.
   Fitzwater said the destroyers Merril and McCormick and the
landing platform ship Trenton, which carries helicopters, attacked
the Sassan platform.
   He said there was no indication of Iranian resistance and that
both platforms were burning about three hours after the attacks.
   The shipping executives, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said their monitors picked up a radio message about 30 minutes
before the attack in which a U.S. warship urged platform workers to
evacuate.
   The executives said the warning specified the facilities ``will
be shelled in five minutes.''
   The Iranians radioed back: ``We have no instructions to leave
the place.''
   Eight minutes later, the American warship, which the executives
could not identify, said: ``We will blast the platform in half a
second.''
   One shipping executive noted: ``Circumstances of the attack on
Sassan were very much similar to those that preceded the U.S.
shelling of Rostam last October.'' Rostam is the sister platform to
Sassan.
   The Rostam was wrecked in October 1987 after Iran fired a
Chinese Silkworm missile into a U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti oil tanker,
injuring 18 crewmen. ``After a five-minute warning, the American
guns blazed away at the platform,'' the executive said of the
attack on Rostam.
   The Samuel B. Roberts had sailed into a mine field on Thursday
and was trying to manuever to safety when it was hit by a submerged
mine, U.S. military officials said on Sunday.
   While trying to move ``at minimum speed to maintain a safe
distance'' from three mines it had spotted on the surface, the
3,700-ton warship ``apparently slid into the mine from the side,''
said Maj. Barry Willey of the U.S. Central Command.
   The explosion blew a hole in the port side of the ship's hull
beneath the waterline, causing fire and flooding and injuring the
10 crewmen.
   The frigate to the United Arab Emirates port of Dubai on
Saturday. The four most seriously injured Americans have been flown
to a U.S. military hospital in West Germany.
   U.S. officals also said on Sunday that two more mines had been
found and destroyed in the waters where the Roberts was crippled.
That brought to five the number known to have been seen in the area.
   U.S. officials have said the mines were recently laid and that
they came from the same source as those found on an Iranian
minelayer disabled by U.S. helicopters on Sept. 21, 1987.
</TEXT>
