<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MarineBuried     04-18 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marine Buried,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mourners Call Slain Marine A Peacemaker</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos RA2,3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cpl. Ricardo Villahermosa, killed
accidentally by fellow Marines in Panama last week, had said before
he left for that Central American nation that he ``wasn't coming
back,'' friends said at his funeral.
   The corporal, who was eulogized as a peacemaker for his efforts
on behalf of his country, was saluted with a three-gun volley and
taps during the services Sunday.
   The Rev. John Flood, minister of Whitakers Baptist Church and
the grandfather of Villahermosa's wife, Titina, said the
25-year-old Marine was part of a ``God-ordained force to protect.
``Without that protection, we are loose for the enemy to destroy.''
   After the service, friends of the Camp Lejeune Marine said he
was ``fun to be with'' but that he ``didn't seem right'' and had
said that he didn't expect to come back.
   Villahermosa, a weapons platoon squad leader, was part of a
12-man security patrol guarding a petroleum storage area near a
U.S. military base. He was shot in the abdomen last Tuesday by
fellow Marines who thought they were firing at intruders.
   Villahermosa's 3-year-old daughter Victoria sat on her mother's
lap throughout the memorial service, playing with a strand of beads
around her mother's neck.
   Villahermosa's family flew to North Carolina from Puerto Rico
and California for the service at Johnson Funeral Home in Rocky
Mount. Villahermosa was buried at a family cemetery near Sharpsburg.
   A Marine handed the corporal's folded flag to Victoria. A second
flag went to Villahermosa's father, Augustine, of Puerto Rico, who
flew to North Carolina for the service.
   Villahermosa's brother, Hendrick, of California, was also at the
service. Villahermosa's mother, Juanita, was ill and could not make
the trip from Puerto Rico, friends said.
   After the service, friends of the family remembered Rick as a
happy, friendly man.
   ``He was fun to be with. If you were down, you could go to
him,'' said Diane Lamm of New Bern. ``If you didn't have a brother,
you had one in him. He most surely died a hero.''
   Cynthia Marker, who was a neighbor of Villahermosa at a mobile
home park in Bridgeton, said she saw Villahermosa the night before
he reported to Camp Lejeune. ``He just didn't seem right. He told
me he wasn't coming back. I thought he was kidding,'' she said.
   Flood said he received a similar impression from talking to
family members.
   ``I don't think he was looking to come back,'' Flood said.
</TEXT>
