<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RapeVictim     04-18 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rape Victim,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine Years After Rapist Severs Hands, Mary Vincent Builds New Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mary Vincent says she once considered suicide
after a rapist hacked her forearms off during nine years ago, but
now a young son has given her a reason to live.
   ``There are times when it takes an hour or two to get myself
together in the morning because I get so frustrated that I cannot
stop crying,'' she said in an interview published in this week's
issue of People magazine.
   Ms. Vincent says she still has nightmares about the attack and
struggles to cope without hands.
   Larry Singleton was convicted in 1978 of raping Ms. Vincent,
chopping off her forearms with an ax and leaving her for dead. She
walked three miles and was rescued by motorists.
   Singleton is scheduled to be released from parole on April 25;
because of controversy over his release he has been living on the
grounds of San Quentin Prison near San Francisco.
   Ms. Vincent says she dreads his release out of concern for her
18-month-old son, Luke.
   ``I don't want anything to happen to him,'' she said. ``I
treasure him like life itself. He is my life.''
   Ms. Vincent, 24, outfitted with prostheses with metal pincers,
lives as a single mother on welfare in a small town in the
northwestern United States which People did not to identify.
   As for men, she said, ``I don't think too highly of them any
more. Luke's father, he understood me, and I basically understood
him, but he is like (other) people who want to care about somebody
who went through a bad trauma: They can't cope with the hurt that
goes on inside me or any other victim.''
</TEXT>
