<1ST_LINE>r p PM-LouisianaEelection     04-18 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Louisiana Eelection,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McCrery Hopes To Take Office This Week; Campbell Won't Concede</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Jim McCrery said he expects to
take the oath of office this week to become northwest Louisiana's
first GOP congressman in 114 years, although his opponent has
refused to concede.
   McCrery's thin margin in a special election Saturday over
Democrat Foster Campbell prompted Gov. Buddy Roemer to send state
police and private security personnel to beef up security around
locked voting machines.
   The victory won't be official until Tuesday, when the machines
are opened and the results verified. Complete but unofficial
returns show McCrery with 51 percent or 63,488 votes to 49 percent
or 62,139 votes for Campbell, a state senator.
   If it holds, the victory will even out Louisiana's house
delegation at four Democrats and four Republicans. McCrery will
replace Roemer, a Democrat who vacated the 4th District seat when
he took office as governor March 14.
   McCrery touted himself as a follower of the popular Democratic
governor's conservative principles. He said he will win again when
he is up for re-election to a full term in the fall.
   ``I think this shows that the people here are going to elect me
and re-elect me,'' McCrery, 38, said Sunday. ``I represent the
philosophy of this area'a main stream.''
   His Democratic opponent tried to paint McCrery as a tool of
special interests, noting that McCrery's last job was as a lobbyist.
   Prior to his stint as a lobbyist for Georgia-Pacific Corp.,
McCrery, a former Democrat, was a congressional aide, first serving
Congressman Buddy Leach, then Roemer after Roemer defeated Leach in
a 1980 election.
   Campbell, 41, didn't talk with reporters Sunday. His manager,
Joe Ticheli said Campbell wasn't ready to concede.
   There was confusion about the exact vote in Caddo Parish forcing
officials to check and recheck totals.
   On election night, Secretary of State Fox McKeithen raised
questions about the removal of about 3,000 voters from the Caddo
Parish rolls of registered voters between the March 8 primary
election and Saturday's runoff. McCrery ran well in Caddo Parish.
   McKeithen said on Sunday that the purge broke no state laws, but
he was planning to check that with federal officials.
   McCrery led the March 8 primary with 31 percent of the vote to
Campbell's 19 percent in a field of 10 candidates. Louisiana's open
primary system puts the top two vote-getters in a runoff,
regardless of party affiliation, if no candidate has a clear
majority.
</TEXT>
