<DOCNO> AP880418-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0858EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BeverlyHillsMayor 1stLd-Writethru a0477 04-18 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Beverly Hills Mayor, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0477,0718</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Establishment Attorney-Writer To Take Up Mayor's Gavel</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, ``I don't need...' to restore dropped word
`player'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LISA WOLFSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor-turned-novelist
becomes the mayor of this celebrity mecca Tuesday amid concern that
his abrasive, anti-establishment style will intensify the City
Council's infighting.
   Robert Tanenbaum, 45, who maintains a law practice, devotes most
of his time away from City Hall to his relatively new occupation _
writing. His first endeavor, the autobiographical ``Badge Of The
Assassin,'' which traced his pursuit of police killers, was made
into a 1985 CBS-TV movie.
   With two successful careers under his belt, why does Tanenbaum
sacrifice 20 or so hours a week to the city of Beverly Hills?
   ``He's the most honest guy I know and why he got involved in
politics _ well, that I'll never know,'' said longtime friend and
assistant Don Baezler.
   But while no one questions Tanenbaum's honesty, his method of
governing has caused a stir among the city's establishment, to
which the transplanted New Yorker definitely does not belong.
   Tanenbaum was the top vote-getter in the 1986 election _ his
first run for a council seat _ and he has kept his campaign pledge
to vote consistently against overdevelopment and commercial
encroachment on residential areas of this wealthy Los Angeles-area
community.
   But his courtroom-style cross-examinations, shouting matches and
name-calling during council meetings have raised the ire of many.
   In addition, some find it odd that Baezler, a former detective
with the New York Police Department, lives in Tanenbaum's home and
works alongside him.
   ``I'd be talking to someone at a council meeting and he
(Tanenbaum) would send over his bodyguard, or whatever (Baezler)
is, to listen to what I'm saying,'' said Ed Brown, a former mayor
and real estate investment executive. ``It's a type of
intimidation.''
   But Tanenbaum, who as the former deputy chief of homicide for
the New York District Attorney's Office helped ``put away my share
of mobsters,'' said Baezler is no political spy, merely his
assistant and trusted family friend.
   ``I don't need a bodyguard,'' said the 6-foot-6 former college
basketball player, who also lives with his wife and three children.
``(But) because of the cases I've dealt with in the past, I've been
threatened many times. I'm tough-skinned, but it's comforting to
know Don is here with my family when I have to be away.''
   The mayorship is rotated annually among the five council
members, who serve four-year terms and are paid $330 a month.
   Calling himself a representative of the ``regular Joes,''
Tanenbaum says he ran for office after detecting what he claimed
was a distortion of values among city officials.
   ``The notion here was interest groups and wealthy people get
their candidates in office in order to get what they want done,''
Tanenbaum said. ``After attending a few council meetings, I saw
that developers were treated with sensitivity while residents were
treated like alien creatures.''
   Despite its small size _ some 30,000 residents, who have an
average income of about $40,000 _ Beverly Hills is starting to
share the problems suffered by cities many times its size: traffic,
a high robbery rate and overzealous developers.
   ``We're a schizophrenic city,'' said Councilwoman Donna Ellman.
``At night we are small but during the day we grow up to 200,000
people and we are called upon to provide basic services for all.
   ``It's the businesses that pay for a lot of those services, and
it's a hard balance to maintain a healthy business community yet
retain a small-town residential atmosphere.''
   Retaining a healthy atmosphere in the council also has been
difficult.
   Benjamin Stansbury, who is being replaced as mayor by Tanenbaum,
once called him a ``turkey'' and Councilman Maxwell Salter labeled
him a ``demagogue.'' Relations reached their lowest point last fall
when Tanenbaum called Salter an ``intellectual cretin'' during a
session televised on a cable channel.
   ``I think what he has shown is disrespect for his staff, fellow
council and the public,'' said Brown.
   Tanenbaum says he is more soft-spoken than he was two years ago,
and vows as mayor to get rid of the ``Hatfield-McCoy mentality''
that has permeated the council.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
