   AT&T President Robert E. Allen, who took over from Olson after
he became ill last month, will continue to direct the company until
the board of directors elects a new chairman, company spokeswoman
Lynda Beighley said.
   Olson became ill with the flu on March 18 and had surgery seven
days later. He returned home on April 1 and had been undergoing
chemotherapy as an outpatient since that time.
   ``All of us in the company are shocked at the suddenness of
Jim's death,'' Allen said in a statement. ``He was a dynamic and
visionary leader. We will miss him. Our legacy to him will be the
vigor with which we carry out the strategic course he laid out for
us during his 20 months as our leader.''
