<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Parties     04-18 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Parties,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Will Decide Political Party Issue in California Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether states may bar political party leaders from endorsing
primary election candidates and whether states may regulate
political party structure.
   The justices said they will consider reinstating parts of a
California law overturned as infringements on citizens' rights to
express themselves and associate with whom they please.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last October threw out key
portions of the California election law.
   That decision marked the second time in less than two years that
the appeals court said the state had interfered unconstitutionally
with political parties. The Supreme Court last year ordered the
appeals court to reconsider its initial ruling in light of a 1986
Supreme Court decision on political parties.
   The justices had ruled in 1986 in a case from Connecticut that
states with open primaries may not bar independent voters from
casting ballots to determine party nominees.
   The 9th Circuit court said the 1986 ruling supported its
decision to strike down portions of the California law.
   ``Prohibiting the governing body of a political party from
supporting some candidates and opposing others (in primary
elections) patently infringes both the right of the party to
express itself freely and the right of party members to an
unrestricted flow of political information,'' the appeals court
said.
   ``California's ban on pre-primary endorsements is a form of
paternalism that is inconsistent with the First Amendment,'' it
said.
   The appeals court also struck down rules that dictated the
make-up of state party central committtees and set terms of office
for party chairmen.
   State officials said the ban on primary endorsements was
designed to prevent factionalism within parties and to prevent
voters from being unduly influenced by party leaders.
   California revamped its elections laws around the turn of the
century to break the grip on political parties by wealthy special
interests, particularly the Southern Pacific Railroad Co.
   But the 9th Circuit court said such rules as prohibiting party
leaders from endorsing candidates in primaries now have the effect
of undermining the parties' main goals.
   ``The state has effectively drained party central committees of
political power,'' the appeals court said.
   The state law was challenged by county Democratic and Republican
leaders and by state leaders of the Libertarian Party.
   The case is March Fong Eu vs. San Francisco County Democratic
Central Committee, 87-1269.
</TEXT>
