<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Hastings     04-18 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Hastings,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Appeal by Florida Judge Hastings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected an appeal by
U.S. District Judge Alcee Hastings, who says he unlawfully is being
subjected to possible impeachment.
   The court, without comment, left intact a 1980 law under which
fellow judges asked the House of Representatives to consider
impeaching Hastings for alleged judicial misconduct.
   The justices also refused to block the release of confidential
grand jury documents concerning Hastings to the House Judiciary
Committee.
   Hastings, who lives and works in Miami, contends the 1980 law is
unconstitutional.
   A federal trial jury acquitted Hastings of a bribery charge in
1983 after his friend, Washington lawyer William Borders, was
convicted in a separate trial of soliciting a $150,000 bribe in
return for promised official favors from Hastings.
   Soon after Hastings' acquittal, two federal judges in the 11th
U.S. Circuit, which encompasses Florida, Georgia and Alabama, filed
a complaint charging that he had obstructed justice and lied under
oath during his prosecution.
   An investigative panel of 11th Circuit judges compiled a
381-page report that recommended Hastings be impeached. Acting on
that recommendation, the U.S. Judicial Conference in 1987 asked the
House to consider impeachment.
   The conference, a 27-judge board of directors for the federal
courts headed by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, said Hastings
``has engaged in conduct which might constitute grounds for
impeachment.''
   But the conference made no move to suspend Hastings from
continuing to preside over trials or carrying out his other
judicial duties.
   The House has not yet determined whether to impeach Hastings,
who was appointed by President Jimmy Carter in 1979. If it did, he
would stand trial in the Senate.
   The judges who filed the complaint against Hastings did so under
the provisions of the Judicial Councils Reform and Judicial Conduct
Disability Act of 1980.
   Under the law, any person may file a complaint alleging that a
federal judge or magistrate ``has engaged in conduct prejudicial to
the effective and expeditious administration of the business of the
courts'' or ``is unable to discharge all the duties of office by
reason of mental or physical disability.''
   The chief judge of a judicial circuit has the authority to
dismiss the complaint as frivolous or empanel an investigative
committee of judges.
   If that committee believes impeachment may be warranted, the
1980 law requires it to certify that determination with the
Judicial Conference, which in turn may conduct its own
investigation and send the matter to the House.
   Hastings contends that the law unconstitutionally allows judges
to usurp congressional power by taking impeachment matters before
the House.
   Hastings, the only black federal trial judge in Florida, has
suggested that the allegations against him could be racially
inspired.
   He also has said he may be the victim of a vendetta by Justice
Department officials angered by his rulings that blocked
deportations of Haitian refugees.
   Rehnquist disqualified himself from acting on the emergency
request and the formal appeal from Hastings.
   The cases are Hastings vs. U.S. Judicial Conference, 87-1187,
and Hastings vs. House Judiciary Committee, A-788.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
