<DOCNO> AP880418-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Scotus-Dues     04-18 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Dues,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Affirms Ruling in Washington State Union Dues Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a ruling
that a worker may not be fired for refusing on religious grounds to
pay union dues.
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by a machinists
union in Seattle, Wash., seeking to force a Boeing Co. employee to
pay union dues.
   Thomasine Nichols said her personal religious beliefs bar her
from paying dues to Lodge 751 of the International Association of
Machinists & Aerospace Workers.
   Mrs. Nichols said she believes the Bible teaches that labor
organizations should be abolished. Her view is not shared by the
religious group to which she belongs, the Bethel Temple.
   She offered to contribute a sum equal to her assessed union dues
to a charity.
   Boeing refused to fire her, even though her refusal to pay dues
violated the company's contract with the machinists union.
   The union sued in federal court in 1986. It said Mrs. Nichols
should not be exempt from paying dues because she is not a member
of a religious organization that traditionally opposes union
membership.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last November that
Mrs. Nichols is protected against being fired by the federal Civil
Rights Act of 1972, which requires employers to make reasonable
accommodations for workers' religious beliefs.
   The law requires such accommodations unless they pose ``undue
hardships'' to the employer.
   The appeals court said granting a dues exemption to Mrs. Nichols
does not impose undue hardship on the union.
   ``To prove undue hardship, a union must demonstrate a widespread
refusal to pay union dues,'' the appeals court said.
   The appeals court also rejected the union's claims that a 1985
Supreme Court ruling requires Mrs. Nichols pay the dues.
   The justices in 1985 struck down a Connecticut law that gave
workers a right to designate their own Sabbath as a day off from
work.
   The 9th Circuit court said the 1985 ruling declared the
Connecticut law unconstitutional because of its ``complete failure
to take into account the interests of the employer and other
employees who did not observe a Sabbath.''
   The 1972 civil rights law ``does not give an unqualified right
to employees to have their religious beliefs accommodated,'' the
appeals court said.
   Therefore the federal law adheres to the Constitution's required
separation of church and state, the appeals court said.
   The union's argument that the National Labor Relations Act of
1980 takes precedence over the 1972 law also was rejected by the
appeals court.
   The 1980 law says no worker may be forced to pay union dues if
that violates ``established and traditional tenets or teachings of
a bona fide religion, body or sect.''
   The 9th Circuit court said that rights created by the 1972 law
``are independent and separate from the rights created by the
National Labor Relations Act.''
   Mrs. Nichols was aided in the case by the National Right to Work
Legal Defense Foundation in Springfield, Va.
   The case is International Association of Machinists vs. Boeing,
87-1484.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
