<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-FOIA     04-18 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-FOIA,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Will Decide Freedom of Information Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court said today it will decide
whether public criminal records compiled by the FBI generally must
be released under the Freedom of Information Act.
   The justices agreed to study a Reagan administration attempt to
scuttle an FOIA lawsuit by a CBS News reporter and the Reporters
Committee for Freedom of the Press aimed at obtaining such
documents.
   The FBI maintains identification records called ``rap sheets''
on some 24 million Americans, detailing arrest and conviction
information supplied by federal, state and local law enforcement
agencies.
   CBS correspondent Robert Schakne in 1978 sought all FBI records
of the arrests, indictments, and court dispositions of any charges
against four brothers, two of whom were identified as associates of
reputed Pennsylvania crime boss Russell Bufalino.
   Filed under the FOIA, a 1966 law aimed at curtailing government
secrecy, the request sought information about William, Phillip,
Samuel and Charles Medico.
   Schakne said he was trying to determine if the brothers had
criminal records because their firm, Medico Industries Inc., had
received lucrative defense contracts with the help of former Rep.
Daniel J. Flood, D-Pa.
   Schakne said he requested the FBI files as part of his reporting
on Flood, who had been charged with accepting $50,000 in bribes.
Flood pleaded guilty to conspiracy in 1980 and was placed on
probation.
   The Washington-based Reporters Committee later filed a similar
request.
   In 1980, the Pennsylvania Crime Commission identified Phillip,
Angelo and William Medico as members of the organized crime family
allegedly headed by Bufalino.
   The 1980 report said Bufalino regularly visited the Medico
family business near Wilkes-Barre, Pa., over a 20-year period.
   The report said Flood had used the Medico Industries box at a
local racetrack and attended Samuel Medico's funeral.
   Schakne confined his request to documents that were a ``matter
of public record.''
   The FBI first denied the request but later released the ``rap
sheet'' on the late William Medico.
   The bureau said it had no records on Phillip and Samuel, also
deceased, and refused to release its file on Charles Medico.
Government lawyers said releasing the information would violate
Medico's privacy.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here last year rejected
Justice Department arguments that such FBI records are covered by
privacy exemptions contained in the 1966 law.
   One exemption authorizes withholding information if its
disclosure ``would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of
personal privacy.''
   Another, applying only to law enforcement records, authorizes
withholding if disclosure ``could reasonably be expecged to
constitute an unwarranted invasion of personal privacy.''
   The appeals court ordered U.S. District Judge John Garrett Penn
to review the requested documents and determine if they were
considered public by Pennsylvania authorities.
   If so, the appeals court said, they are discloseable under the
FOIA.
   In the appeal acted on today, government lawyers noted that the
federal appeals court based in New York City has ruled that such
FBI documents are covered by FOIA privacy exemptions and can be
withheld.
   The case is U.S. Department of Justice vs. Reporters Committee,
87-1379.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880418-0103 </DOCNO>
