<HEAD>Company Says Ship Attacked In Persian Gulf Is Safe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf-Shelling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American tug and supply vessel was
reported safe today after being fired on by Iranians responding to
a U.S. attack in the Persian Gulf, a spokesman for the company that
owns the vessel said.
   ``My understanding is that it (the Willi Tide) was fired on, but
it was not hit,'' said Victor Koock, senior vice president and
general counsel for Tidewater Inc. ``All this is unconfirmed, but
that's what I was told a few minutes ago.''
   Koock said the 283-ton vessel sailed back to a Persian Gulf
port, probably in Dubai. He said a crew of about 12 people was
aboard, and he had no reports of injuries.
   The Willi Tide is a specialized vessel that carries supplies to
offshore oil platforms and is also equipped for towing.
   The attack on the Willi Tide came after U.S. warships destroyed
two offshore Iranian oil platforms and an Iranian patrol boat. Iran
responded by rocketing oil facilities and firing on at least two
U.S. vessels.
   The American attack was in retaliation for a mine explosion that
tore a hole in an American frigate last week, injuring 10 crewmen.
   The London-based Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit reported
that Iranian boats attacking the Willi Tide fled after unidentified
warplanes swooped low over the scene.
