<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Falklands     04-18 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Falklands,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Decide Case Stemming from Falkland Islands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in a case stemming from the
1982 war over the Falkland Islands, today agreed to decide whether
Argentina may be sued in U.S. courts for attacking a neutral oil
tanker.
   The justices said they will hear arguments by Argentine
officials, supported by the Reagan administration, aimed at killing
the lawsuit.
   At issue is whether a foreign nation accused of violating
international law may be sued in federal courts in this country by
a foreign corporation engaged in U.S. trade.
   The case stems from an attack on the oil tanker Hercules by
Argentine aircraft on June 8, 1982. The ship was some 600 miles
from the Argentine coast and nearly 500 miles from the Falkland
Islands.
   Argentina and Great Britain were at war over control of the
islands, which Argentina calls the Malvinas.
   The Hercules was owned by United Carriers Inc. and chartered by
Amerada Hess Shipping Corp. to carry oil from Alaska around the
southern tip of South America to a refinery in the U.S. Virgin
Islands.
   United Carriers and Amerada Hess are both Liberian corporations.
   The Hercules was attacked despite a U.S. alert to Great Britain
and Argentina that it was among neutral vessels traveling in the
South Atlantic.
   The badly damaged tanker made it to port in Rio de Janeiro,
Brazil. But officials scuttled the ship on July 20, 1982, because
an unexploded bomb was embedded in one of its tanks.
   United Carriers sued Argentina for $10 million for the destroyed
tanker, and Amerada said it lost $2 million in fuel.
   The suit was filed in federal court in New York City after
Argentine officials refused to consider the claims. The companies
were unable to hire Argentine attorneys to pursue a suit in that
nation's courts.
   A U.S. federal judge threw out the suit but it was reinstated
last September by the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   The appeals court, in ordering a trial, rejected arguments that
Argentina was immune from being sued because of a 1976 U.S. law
granting foreign nations broad protection from such claims.
   The appeals court said that under a different law, enacted by
Congress in 1789, a foreign nation may be sued in U.S. courts by a
foreign corporation or foreign individual when the nation is
accused of violating international law or a U.S. treaty.
   ``It is beyond controversy that attacking a neutral ship in
international waters, without proper cause for suspicion or
investigation, violates international law,'' the appeals court said.
   It added that protections of sovereign immunity do not apply in
the same way that Nazi war criminals at the Nuremberg trials after
World War II were not immune from prosecution.
   The Reagan administration said the appeals court ruling could
have dire consequences for U.S. foreign policy.
   ``The courts of the United States are not the proper forums for
the resolution of the legality of acts of foreign states,'' Justice
Department lawyers said. ``Sensitive foreign policy concerns are
implicated.''
   The government lawyers also said the appeals court decision
``threatens to turn the courts of the United States into tribunals
in which aliens generally (but not U.S. citizens) may seek redress
against foreign governments for conduct that has no substantial
nexus to the United States.''
   The case is Argentine Republic vs. Amerada Hess, 87-1372.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
