<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Crash     04-18 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Crash,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Revive Lawsuit Against FAA Stemming from
California Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to revive a
lawsuit against the Federal Aviation Administration stemming from
an airplane crash near Bishop, Calif., that killed 36 people in
1974.
   The justices, without comment, let stand rulings that the FAA is
immune from charges that its negligence contributed to the accident.
   A Sierra Pacific Airline charter flight crashed into a foothill
of the White Mountains the night of March 13, 1974, just after
taking off from Bishop Airport.
   Relatives of some of the crash victims sued the FAA, charging
that there was inadequate ground lighting near the airport and that
the FAA negligently had failed to conduct night test flights before
publishing an approved departure procedure.
   The suit was filed under the Federal Tort Claims Act, a law that
waives the government's sovereign immunity and allows it to be sued
in some instances.
   But lower courts ruled that the FAA officials who investigated
safety conditions at the Bishop Airport and prepareed departure
procedures for use there were acting ``within the scope of the
discretionary function exception'' to the FTCA.
   The government may not be sued under the law if the allegedly
wrongful actions stemmed from a government official's discretionary
authority.
   The case is West vs. U.S., 87-1270.
</TEXT>
