<2ND_LINE>PM-Williamsburg Bridge,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Ferry Service Starts; $2.5 Billion Needed for Bridges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferry service across the East River began this
morning for some of the nearly 250,000 travelers denied use of the
decrepit Williamsburg Bridge.
   The first boat moved out at 7 a.m. from a hastily built pier
near the Brooklyn side of the bridge and made the 15-minute voyage
to connect with subways at the tip of Manhattan.
   The bridge, a vital link between Manhattan and Queens and
Brooklyn, was closed to cars, trucks and subways last week when
inspectors found it decaying from rust, corrosion and years of
neglect.
   The inauguration of the ferry was ``very smooth,'' according to
Transportation Department spokesman Victor Ross. Transportation
Commissioner Ross Sandler was on hand for a ceremonial opening at a
later departure.
   Sandler said Sunday that ``to get the 371 city bridges with a
poor or fair rating to a good or better rating, we'll have to spend
$2.5 billion'' over the next 10 years. He said the figure would go
up another half billion if the Williamsburg must be replaced.
   He said inspectors were half finished with their examination of
the Williamsburg and ``there's nothing that we've found so far that
we won't be able to fix.''
   Fliers advertising the ferry service are being distributed in
English, Spanish and Yiddish; there is a large orthodox Jewish
population in the Williamsburg section of Brooklyn.
   The city is using two of its smaller ferries, each capable of
carrying 1,280 passengers, that normally run between Staten Island
and Manhattan at night and on weekends.
</TEXT>
