<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Blacks-PennState 1stLd-Writethru a0423 04-18 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Blacks-Penn State, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0423,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minority Recruitment Uncertain After Sit-In Arrests</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Black Protests</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-7, ``Jordan later xxx, to UPDATE with meeting
convened and dropping of charges; a version of this story moved in
Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The arrest of student activists who
staged a sit-in over minority issues has cast a shadow of
uncertainty over Penn State University's efforts to recruit blacks
for next fall, officials say.
   ``The timing of this couldn't be any worse,'' said Scott F.
Healy, Penn State's admissions director, explaining that parents
are sitting down with college-bound offspring now to decide which
school they'll attend this fall.
   ``When you show a student being escorted out of a building in
handcuffs, it isn't a positive image of education,'' Healy said.
   More than 150 students, most of them black, occupied Penn
State's telecommunications building April 8 when university
President Bryce Jordan canceled a meeting with nine black students
who had staged a sit-in outside his office three days earlier.
   Police arrested 89 protesters who remained in the
telecommunications building the next morning.
   Jordan convened an open meeting today with student leaders to
discuss minority issues and agreed to drop all criminal and
university charges against the protesters.
   The outcome of the meeting will heavily influence minority
recruitment for this fall, said Vice Provost Carol Cartwright, who
chairs the university's Equal Opportunity Planning Committee.
   Before the protests, minority applications were up 7 percent
over last year, Healy said. He acknowledged that the arrests could
scare off some minority students.
   ``It could say to minorities, `This is not the place I want to
go for the next four years,''' he said.
   The students involved in the sit-ins have complained of the low
number of blacks enrolled at Penn State, and are expected to
include better minority recruitment in their demands at the meeting.
   Last fall, Penn State failed to reach a court-mandated goal of 5
percent black enrollment. The university has 2,424 blacks
throughout the state system, 3.6 percent of its 67,278 students.
   Courtney Pinkney, president of the student Black Caucus, agrees
the arrests and the publicity surrounding them may have hurt
minority recruitment.
   ``In no way can they blame the black students,'' Ms. Pinkney
said. ``If things would have been correct from the beginning, this
wouldn't have happened.''
   Student activists have not spelled out the demands they plan to
present at the meeting, but protester Robert Blair said they would
be similar to those made by a group of students at a Board of
Trustees meeting last November.
   At that meeting, students complained about low numbers of black
students and faculty, requested the creation of the post of vice
president for minority affairs, and asked that all undergraduates
be required to take black studies.
   In 1986, black students at Penn State's State College campus
stopped helping admissions recruiters and spread word the school
wasn't a good place for blacks.
   ``When you have your own students working against you, it is
very difficult if not impossible to turn the situation around and
get black and Hispanic students to come,'' Healy said.
   This spring, with the admissions office's blessing, students
from the Black Caucus began meeting with minority applicants to
tell them what life at the school is like.
   ``The students wanted to be convinced we were telling the
truth,'' said Gary Kelsey, director of the division of minority
admissions and community affairs.
   Ms. Pinkney, a senior from Philadelphia, said she was recruited
by Penn State when she was in 10th grade.
   ``I thought Penn State was the greatest place on Earth when I
got here. I thought it was very unfortunate and very unfair I was
not told the real deal,'' she said.
</TEXT>
