<2ND_LINE>PM-US Attack-Reax,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Egypt Says U.S. Reprisal Justifiable, Britain Backs Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt today accused Iran of provoking a new
round of military hostilities in the Persian Gulf and said today's
American attacks on two Iranian oil platforms were justified.
   Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid said Iran invited the
American retaliation by laying new mines in the gulf. He urged the
Tehran government to desist from an ``unsound and unwise'' policy.
   ``Iran's return to mine-laying in the gulf damaged a U.S.
military vessel on April 14 and, in doing so, Iran initiated a new
wave of military confrontation in the region,'' Abdel-Meguid said.
   ``We understand the American response and we urge Iran to stop
its policy of provoking others.''
   Britain, meanwhile, backed the U.S. strike against the platforms
and deplored a subsequent Iranian gunboat attack on a British
tanker in the waterway.
   The Foreign Office said Britain was seeking information about
the attack on the 60,184-ton York Marine off the southern gulf
emirate of Sharjah.
   ``We deplore it obviously,'' said a spokesman, who requested
anonymity.
   Gulf-based shipping executives said the fully-loaded oil tanker
York Marine was on fire and its crew had abandoned ship.
   Washington said the attack was launched to punish Iran for the
mine that blew a hole in the U.S. frigate Samuel B. Roberts. The
explosion Thursday injured 10 crewmen.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher supported today's U.S. attack.
   ``We are satisfied from the evidence we have that the mines were
laid by Iran and that the U.S. reaction was entirely justified as a
proportionate response,'' she told reporters.
   Britain has two destroyers and two minesweepers in the gulf. It
said it had not been informed the York Marine was in the waterway
but would have given it protection if asked.
</TEXT>
