<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BankBid 1stLd-Writethru a0619 04-18 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Bid, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0619,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irving Accepts `White Knight' Cash Tender Offer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 3rd graf pvs with conditions of tender
offer, opening date; INSERTS two grafs after 8th pvs, Bank of New
York, with stock prices and comment from Irving chairman; adds
byline; version moved on business wire</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp., facing a hostile tender offer
from Bank of New York Co., said today that it has accepted a
$65-a-share cash tender offer from Banca Commerciale Italiana for
51 percent of its common shares.
   The offer, valued at between $1.1 billion and $1.2 billion, also
includes a special dividend of $10 per share payable to Irving
shareholders upon completion of the deal, said Irving spokesman D.
Emerson Phelps.
   Banca Commerciale, based in Milan, is Italy's second-largest
bank with assets of $60 billion. Irving's assets total $24.3
billion.
   The tender offer begins Tuesday and is conditioned upon a
minimum of 6.25 million shares being tendered and various
regulatory approvals.
   The special dividends would be paid from asset sales, including
sale of Irving's 50-story Wall Street headquarters. Irving said it
also plans to sell its 39 percent equity interest in Banca della
Svizzera Italiana for about $325 million.
   Today's announcement comes just four days after Bank of New
York's shareholders voted to support management's $1 billion-plus
hostile bid for Irving. The tender offer, which began last month,
is for $15 in cash and 1.575 of its common shares for each of
Irving's roughly 18.1 million common shares outstanding.
   Bank of New York, which holds as a 4.9 percent stake in Irving,
is also running a slate of 16 nominees for Irving's board of
directors. Irving's annual shareholders meeting is scheduled for
Thursday.
   Irving has repeatedly spurned the company's takeover offers,
which began about seven months ago. It maintained it wanted to
remain independent but disclosed that it was seeking a ``white
knight'' friendly merger partner.
   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady said his company had no
immediate comment on Irving's announcement. ``We're studying the
announcement this morning,'' he said..
   In midday trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Irving shares
rose 12.5 cents to $61.50, while Bank of New York gained 37.5 cents
to $31.
   In a statement, Irving Chairman Joseph A. Rice, said, ``our
shareholders will benefit far more from the affiliation with BCI
(Banca Commerciale Italiana) than the proposal advanced from BNY.''
   Phelps said Irving's current management is expected to remain in
place. He said a five-member executive committee comprised of
Irving's chairman and president, two Banca Commerciale
representatives and an outside Irving director will oversee the
restructing plan.
   Irving also said it was beginning ``an intensive program of cost
savings'' that is expected to raise net income to about $1.60 a
share in 1988 and $2.75 next year.
   In addition, the banking concern said it would also would
immediately increase Irving's annual common dividend from $2.42 a
share to $4.50.
</TEXT>
