<HEAD>Remains of 13th Century Pope Stolen From Cathedral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>L'AQUILA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of St. Celestine V, a pope
who resigned in 1294 after a five-month papacy, were stolen
overnight from this city's cathedral, authorities said Monday.
   Mayor Enzo Lombardi and other city officials said they presumed
the remains were taken by thieves who expected a ransom, although
no demand had been received.
   Thieves took away the mummified remains of the pope after
forcing open a chapel door and a silver urns in the Cathedral of
Santa Maria di Collemaggio.
   Police said thieves possibly used pass keys for entering the
cathedral through a secondary door.
   Celestine died in 1296, two years after his resignation.
