<HEAD>Crew Rescued from Sinking Ship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 2,878-ton Panamanian cargo ship sank Monday in
rough seas in the East China Sea, but its crew of 14 was rescued by
Japanese helicopters, the Maritime Safety Agency reported.
   An agency official said the 11 South Korean and three Filipino
crew members of the Sandakan were picked up by agency and
Self-Defense Marine Force helicopters while drifting in two life
boats about 125 miles north of Naha, Okinawa. All were said to be
unhurt.
   The crew abandoned the Sandakan shortly after it began listing
to port in rough seas, said the agency official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   He said the Sandakan, owned by Santiago LNG S.A. of Panama, was
heading for Okayama, western Japan, from China when the vessel sank.
