<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Hostage 2ndLd-Writethru a0608 04-18 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Hostage, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0608,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radio Report Says Higgins Killed By Captors</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New 7th graf ``At U.N. headquarters...'', spokeswoman says
UNIFIL has found no confirmation of radio report. </NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Christian-controlled radio station
reported today that U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins has
been killed by his pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem captors.
   The Voice of Lebanon said Higgins was ``killed and buried by his
captors'' early this month in Siddiqine, a village in south Lebanon.
   The Beirut-based Voice of Lebanon has a record of frequent
inaccuracies concerning the foreign hostages in Lebanon. Its report
on Higgins could not be independently verified.
   Timur Goksel, the spokesman for the U.N. Interim Force in south
Lebanon with which Higgins was serving when he was abducted, said
of the report: ``We can neither confirm nor deny the report or
anything related to it.''
   He spoke by telephone from the U.N. group's headquarters in
Naqoura on the Lebanese-Israeli border.
   ``We have no such information, and therefore we cannot comment
on the radio report,'' Goksel added. ``We have checked with our
sources, and everybody was surprised when they heard about the
report.''
   At U.N. headquarters in New York, spokeswoman Nadia Younes later
told reporters that UNIFIL had checked with its sources and found
no confirmation of the radio report.
   The radio said Higgins was killed hours before pro-Syrian
militiamen of Justice Minister Nabih Berri's Amal militia captured
Siddiqine from Hezbollah supporters, apparently to keep Amal from
claiming credit for his liberation.
   Amal and Hezbollah spokesmen in Beirut made no comment on the
report. The two groups have been at odds since Higgins, 43, of
Danville, Ky., was kidnapped near the southern port of Tyre on Feb.
17.
   Siddiqine, 10 miles southeast of Tyre, was a Hezbollah
stronghold before Amal crushed its Shiite Moslem fundamentalist
rivals in a four-day crackdown early this month.
   Amal supports the presence of the U.N. peace-keeping force in
predominantly Shiite south Lebanon. Hezbollah, or the Party of God,
opposes it.
   Amal has charged that Hezbollah masterminded Higgins' abduction
to undermine Amal's control of south Lebanon.
   Hezbollah is a pro-Iranian extremist group that is believed to
be an umbrella for factions holding most of the 22 foreign hostages
in Lebanon. Hezbollah has not claimed to hold any foreign hostages.
   Higgins' abduction was claimed by a group calling itself the
Organization of the Oppressed on Earth, which charged that he was a
CIA spy. Both the U.S. and U.N. have denied the charge.
   Amal spokesmen had said their fighters found no trace of Higgins
in any of the Hezbollah strongholds they have captured, including
Siddiqine.
   The foreigners missing and presumed kidnapped in Lebanon are
nine Americans, four Frenchmen, three Britons, one Irishman, one
Italian, one West German, one Indian, and two unidentified men.
   The longest held is Terry A. Anderson, 40, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
