<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BridgeProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0566 04-18 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bridge Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0566,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Outer Banks Bridge Protest Appears To Have Ended</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs, Lawrence gives up vigil and run for state
Senate, picking up 5th graf pvs, ``Lawrence said xxx; SUBS
10th-11th grafs pvs, ``Lawrence's vigil xxx, to conform</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OREGON INLET, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who had chained himself to an
Outer Banks bridge and demanded that it be saved from erosion today
gave up his three-day vigil along with his run for a state Senate
seat.
   Standing at the bridge catwalk which he had made his soapbox,
Dan Lawrence announced he was ending his protest and throwing his
support to his Democratic opponent, state Sen. Marc Basnight.
   ``I don't want even one person to feel that this was done as a
political stunt, detracting from the great need we have to save
this bridge and save this island,'' Lawrence, a Republican, said
late this morning.
   Lawrence made the announcement after saying earlier today that
he had asked for police protection for his vigil at the
two-mile-long Herbert Bonner Bridge, the only route from Hatteras
Island to the mainland. He also admitted that he had abandoned his
post and gone home for two hours Sunday night.
   ``I was afraid that something stupid was going to happen and I
didn't want to be involved in that,'' Lawrence said. ``I have to
consider my family. I have to consider my own health.''
   Lawrence told Greg Clark, a reporter for radio station WOBR,
that two men drove up to his position on the catwalk and said, ``If
you're here tomorrow, we're going to kill you.''
   Lawrence said he went home Sunday night for two hours, then
returned and spent part of the night in his car at the south side
of the bridge before going to sleep under some trees in Hatteras
Island Park.
   He said his wife had been harassed at the trailer park where
they live, and that his son was suffering emotionally from his
father's vigil.
   ``I need some people out here at night to protect me from the
kook element. There are some kooks out here,'' Lawrence said,
adding that he had been urged by a local high school teacher to
abandon his protest.
   Lawrence admitted the protest was tougher than he had envisioned.
   ``It's easy to say you're going to do something. But I wasn't
ready to face the elements,'' he said.
   Lawrence's protest had drawn praise from Basnight, who joined
Lawrence on the bridge for the announcement that the vigil was over.
   ``I commend him for his efort to try to bring attention to an
injustice,'' Basnight said Sunday. ``Nothing else seems to work.
Maybe something can happen here good.''
   Lawrence, 42, first chained himself to the bridge Friday morning
after the structure was threatened by heavy erosion from a fierce
storm Wednesday.
   Gov. Jim Martin and many local officials and fishermen say
jetties are needed to stabilize the inlet's shifting sands.
   The project was authorized by Congress 17 years ago but the
jetties were never built, mostly due to opposition from
environmentalists and the U.S. Department of the Interior, which
say they wouldn't work and would be environmentally hazardous.
   Hatteras Island, which has about 4,800 year-round residents, is
about 50 miles long and never more than a few miles wide. There has
also been controversy over how and whether to move the historic
Cape Hatteras lighthouse, which has also been threatened by the
ever-encroaching sea.
   When asked if he thought Lawrence's protest would spur officials
to stabilize the Oregon Inlet and the bridge, Basnight said,
``Nobody can answer that, except for the federal officials. We'll
just have to wait and see.''
</TEXT>
