<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO Slaying, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0645,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tunisia Says Israel Behind Assassination Of Abu Jihad</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 8 grafs with details of investigation and Arafat
comment.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Tunisian inquiry into the assassination
of PLO military chief Khalil al-Wazir has concluded the operation
was conducted by Israel, official sources said today.
   Tunisia intends to register a formal complaint against the
Jewish state with the United Nations Security Council, the sources
said. They spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The 52-year-old al-Wazir, best known as Abu Jihad, was shot to
death at his suburban Tunis home early Saturday by a seven-person
commando unit.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization immediately blamed
Israel's secret service, Mossad, for the attack.
   Israeli leaders have refused to comment on the assassination.
   Al-Wazir's killing set off rioting in the Israeli-occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip in which 17 Palestinians died.
   President Zine el Abidine Ben Ali, who ordered the
investigation, has asked his foreign minister to inform the
Security Council.
   The investigation revealed that an Israeli military plane was
about 34 miles outside Tunisian air space at the moment of the
attack, according to the sources.
   Other elements implicating Israel were not immediately disclosed.
   In October 1985, Israel raided the PLO headquarters in Tunis,
killing about 80 Palestinians and 20 Tunisians and injuring 100
other people. PLO chief Yasser Arafat arrived about 30 minutes
after that attack.
   Al-Wazir is to be buried in Damascus, Syria. The body was
scheduled to be flown there Tuesday.
   On Sunday, Arafat said the assassination was ``an Israeli
decision taken at the highest level of the leadership with the
greenlight of the American administration, Israel's strategic
ally,'' the Palestinian news agency WAFA reported.
   In a message to the Palestinian people inside the
Israeli-occupied territories, Arafat paid homage to al-Wazir saying
he ``fell, weapon in his hand, to the bullets of a Mossad (Israeli
secret service) gang.''
   ``To those who thought that the murder of Abu Jihad would snuff
out the uprising of the Palestinian people and reduce its heroic
revolution to nothing, I say that they are dreaming because his
death will stamp a vigorous new breath on this revolution and the
price of his death will be high,'' WAFA quoted Arafat as saying.
</TEXT>
