<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Congress-Gulf 1stLd-Writethru a0628 04-18 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Gulf, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0628,490</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs new material after 5th graf pvs, ``In my;
subs 9th graf pvs, The others, to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional leaders said today that
President Reagan was fully justified in retaliating against an
Iranian mine attack that seriously damaged a U.S. frigate on patrol
in international waters.
   They said also they are pleased that the president consulted
with them before ordering that two Iranian platforms in the Persian
Gulf be destroyed, rather than merely informing them after the fact.
   ``The mines have been clearly identified as manufactured by the
Iranians and sown in the waters by the Iranians,'' said Senate
Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va. ``The Iranians were
carrying out terrorist acts ... I support the decision to destroy
the (Iranian oil drilling) platforms.''
   Said Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas:
   ``In my view, now is the time to send only one message to our
adversaries: That the United States, the president, the Congress,
the people are united and determined to meet our responsibilities
and defend our interests in the gulf. I hope the ayatollah
(Khomeini) gets that message so we can all avoid further bloodshed
and violence,'' Dole said.
   House Speaker Jim Wright of Texas said the White House
discussions were ``very frank'' and that the congressional leaders
pointed out the perils as well as the possible benefits of military
action.
   But Wright said said of Reagan: ``He is the commander in chief
and when action is taken by the United States, it certainly
behooves all of us to close ranks and to give the world a view of a
nation that is united.''
   Byrd also said that Reagan had promised to report to Congress in
writing within 48 hours on his actions, ``consistent with the War
Powers Act.''
   And he said that, ``for the first time, we were consulted before
the executive order was issued and before it was decided _ and that
was good.''
   Byrd, Dole and three other members of the congressional
leadership were called to the White House Sunday night and briefed
on possible actions that might be taken for the mine attack that
seriously damaged the USS Samuel B. Roberts last week.
   The others were House Majority Leader Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash.;
and House Minority Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill.,
   Foley, interviewed on the ``CBS Morning News,'' called the
president's action ``an inevitable consequence of the decision to
reflag Kuwaiti vessels and to provide escorts. I think the
president has a responsibility, obviously, to insure that American
lives and American assets are protected.
   ``The resumption of mining by the Iranian forces has created a
very serious risk, not only to American shipping but to other
neutral shipping and non-belligerent shipping in the area,'' Foley
said.
   He said Reagan intended his move as ``a single action, a
response, and a deterrent to further action.''
   Foley added that because of the volatility of the Middle East,
the White House ``really needs to walk a fine line in terms of
keeping hostilities at a minimum.''
</TEXT>
