<HEAD>UMass Chancellor Lashes Back At Secretary of Education</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, ``Duffey had xxx, to restore dropped word
`brother'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chancellor of the University of
Massachusetts lashed back today at U.S. Education Secretary William
Bennett for his criticism of the way the school handled a protest
by minority students.
   ``Students here were treated with respect but also firmness,''
Chancellor Joseph Duffey said. ``They left the building because
they were treated with respect, not because they got what they
wanted. They also left because they realized they were here to
study.''
   Minority students took over a campus building at UMass for six
days in February to protest campus racism, and Bennett, in a Sunday
speech in New Orleans, said the school was too lenient.
   He accused administrators of sending ``the demonstrators a
basket of fruit and ordered out Chinese food for them and then gave
in to all of their demands ... one wonders what kind of teaching
experience that is.''
   The protestors should have been arrested for trespassing, he
said.
   ``Mr. Bennett seems to believe the only response to protesters
with legitimate concerns is to arrest them,'' Duffy said today.
``The only excuse I can imagine for that is that he's been away
from the campus too long.''
   Duffey had sent the protesters a basket of fruit after receiving
a card from them relaying their condolences because his brother was
hospitalized. Duffey later negotiated a settlement with the
students.
   In his speech to the Education Writers Association convention,
Bennett also criticized the University of Minnesota, which recently
decided to turn away former U.N. Ambadassor Jeane Kirkpatrick, and
Yale University, which canceled a date with former U.S. Supreme
Court nominee Robert Bork.
   In both instances, he said, students had objected to the
conservative speakers.
   ``Universities have become increasingly closed and increasingly
insular and in some cases repressive'' by not allowing certain
speakers onto the campuses, Bennett said. He said most of the
intolerance is for conservative ideas.
   He urged administrators to take a hard line to insure that
universities are open. ``Administrators should not just sit there
and be ambushed,'' Bennett said.
   Students who heckle, shout or otherwise interfere with a
speaker's address should be removed, he said.
   ``They have got to make sure a situation is such that a person
can speak,'' Bennett said.
   Duffey said he agreed with Bennett about keeping campuses open
to controversial speakers.
</TEXT>
