<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Shikanai     04-18 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Shikanai,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Funeral Services Held For Media Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Haruo Shikanai, the chairman of the Fuji Sankei
Communications Group, had died of liver and kidney failure at the
age of 42.
   About 5,000 people, including Prime Minister Noboro Takeshita,
attended Monday funeral services for Shikanai, who died Saturday.
   His father, Nobutaka Shikanai, 76, senior adviser to the Fuji
group, assumed the chairman's post he left to his son in 1985,
group spokesman Haruhisa Yoshino said.
   Among the holdings of Fuji Sankei Communications are Sankei
Shimbun, a nationally circulated daily newspaper; Nippon
Broadcasting Corp, a radio station; Fuji Television Network Inc.;
and 103 smaller companies including publishing houses and
production studios. The conglomerate was established in 1968.
   After studying at Boston University, Shikanai joined Nippon
Broadcasting in 1970 and became vice president of the radio company
and managing director of Sankei Shimbun in 1977, Yoshino said.
   He took over the presidency of Fuji Television three years later
at age 35, and was assigned to serve as the group's chairman. In
1985, he succeeded his father as president of Sankei Shimbun and
Nippon Broadcasting.
   Shikanai introduced color printing for Sankei Shimbun, Japan's
fifth-largest daily with a daily circulation of 2.06 million.
   He is survived by his wife, Mitsuko, and four children.
</TEXT>
