<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GunsPlea     04-18 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guns Plea,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Denver Parishioners Turn Over Handguns, Sign Pledges To Forego
Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic priest who urged parishioners to
turn in their handguns and sign pledges to fight violence says he
will invite other parishes to join his campaign.
   The Rev. Marshall Gourley, pastor of Our Lady of Guadalupe
Church, collected six handguns, two rifles and nearly 400 pledges
Sunday at his church in west Denver.
   The weapons were turned over to Police Chief Ari Zavaras, and
the pledge cards to Mayor Federico Pena. Gourley has asked police
to destroy the weapons.
   Gourley asked his parishioners to give up their guns after he
presided at the funerals of two people who died violently. One was
killed by police and the other killed himself.
   After Sunday's services, Gourley said the problem of guns and
violence goes beyond his parish, adding: ``What we do here is
almost insignificant.''
   Besides enlisting the support of other Denver parishes, Gourley
also called on ``all people of good will in the metro area'' to
discard their weapons because ``there are simply too many guns.''
   ``I fully support him,'' Zavaras said. ``I have strong feelings
about gun control and the unlawful carrying of weapons.''
   Pena, who regularly attends Our Lady of Guadalupe, thanked the
parishioners who supported the program Sunday.
</TEXT>
