<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MingoResignation     04-18 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mingo Resignation,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mingo Sheriff Resigns In Plea Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mingo County sheriff resigned today
as part of a plea agreement with federal prosecutors on counts
alleging that he bought the job in 1982 for $100,000, officials
said.
   Mingo County Commissioner Steve Adkins said the commission
received a letter from Mingo County Sheriff Charles ``Eddie''
Hilbert stating that he had resigned effective at 12:01 a.m. today.
   Hilbert, 45, of Delbarton, was in Huntington today to enter a
plea before U.S. District Judge Charles E. Haden II.
   He was indicted in January on 13 felony counts alleging he
bought the sheriff's office in 1982 and used it to assist relatives
and business associates in illegal activities.
   As part of a plea agreement with the federal government, Hilbert
was required to resign as sheriff, according to Joseph Savage,
assistant U.S. attorney.
   Hilbert also has entered into a proposed plea agreement in Mingo
County Circuit Court, where he was charged with a felony count of
bribery in connection with the sale of the sheriff's job.
   Adkins said he expects the commission to name Jim Webb of
Kermit, a former Mingo County highway supervisor, as the new
sheriff on Tuesday.
   Hilbert is one of nearly 50 public officials or employees in
southern West Virginia who have been charged or convicted in
connection with state and federal investigations of political
corruptin or drug trafficking.
   Later today, former sheriff Johnie Owens _ who sold the office
to Hilbert in 1982 _ was scheduled to be sentenced in U.S. District
Court in Huntington on three counts of tax evasion and one count of
bribery in connection with the sale. He will be sentenced Tuesday
on a state charge of tax evasion in connection with the case.
</TEXT>
