<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     04-18 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALCH SPRINGS, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A church congregation made good on a
challenge to boost attendance, so their minister fulfilled his side
of the bargain and raised his voice from the roof.
   With an eye on gathering rain clouds, the Rev. John Chadwick
preached his sermon Sunday from the roof of the Forest Lawn Baptist
Church in this Dallas suburb.
   ``I don't think there was any danger,'' Chadwick said.
   The church's 40-odd members met his challenge to boost
attendance to 50 for the April 10 service. When Chadwick became
pastor of the 30-year-old church three years ago, there were eight
members.
   Chadwick, dressed in overalls and a cowboy hat, spoke for about
10 minutes on the roof. Then rain began falling, and the
congregation moved inside.
   The rooftop sermon brought curious neighbors onto their porches.
   ``If you can't get the people in the church to come, just shout
it out where the world can hear it,'' said Ruth Chadwick of her
husband's sermon.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York is a city with many landmark buildings
and historic sites, and the Landmarks Preservation Commission is
considering protecting some more _ including an operating stable
and a Pepsi-Cola sign.
   That's right, a stable. As in horses. In Manhattan.
   The stable and sign are among several proposals to be considered
by the commission Tuesday.
   ``There's nothing which says a landmark has to be a building,''
said Joseph Bresnan, executive director of the Landmarks
Preservation Commission.
   The 60-foot neon Pepsi-Cola sign has stood over the firm's
bottling plant in Long Island City since it was erected in 1936.
   ``It's a visible, well-known element on the New York skyline and
we want to learn more about it,'' said commission chairman Gene A.
Norman.
   The stable is the Claremont Riding Academy on Manhattan's upper
West Side. Built in 1892, it was once condemned 25 years ago when
the city sought to tear it down as part of an urban renewal
project. But it's still serving people who ride in Central Park.
   Also on Tuesday's agenda is a 67-year-old lighthouse that stands
along the Hudson River underneath the towering George Washington
Bridge. It's known to generations of children from the story ``The
Little Red Lighthouse and the Great Gray Bridge.''
</TEXT>
