<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iran-Iraq 3rdLd-Writethru a0631 04-18 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0631,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Says U.S. Helicopters Attacked Iranian Land Troops,
Washington Denies It</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Washington's response to
Iranian charge. PICKS up 3rd graf, `Tehran radio ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said today U.S. helicopters attacked
Iranian troops to support an Iraqi offensive that reportedly
recaptured the southern Faw peninsula. U.S. officials denied the
charge.
   The Iranian claim was made hours after American warships
destroyed two Iranian platforms in the Persian Gulf in retaliation
for a mine blast that rocked a U.S. frigate last week.
   Fred Hoffman, a Pentagon spokesman, dismissed the charge as
totally without foundation. No U.S. military forces have been
involved with Iraqi units, he said.
   Tehran Radio, monitored in Nicosia, quoted a Supreme Defense
Council statement as saying: ``In direct, open and practical
support for the Iraqi regime, American forces have entered the
war.''
   The statement was issued after Iraq reported its troops, led by
units of the elite Presidential Guard, recaptured Faw. Iran, which
seized the peninsula two years ago, denied Iraqi had retaken it.
   Iraq said its forces today retook the town of Faw near the tip
of the peninsula. It is the only town on the peninsula.
   ``Victorious Iraqi armed forces entered Faw town today and
hoisted the Iraqi flag,'' the Iraqi News Agency reported in an
urgent dispatch.
   A war communique read over state-run television in Baghdad said
Iranian forces were driven out of the peninsula to the other side
of the Shatt-al-Arab waterway.
   The Supreme Defense Council, which determines Iran's war
strategy, called on all Iranians to join the military and brace for
a ``holy defense'' of their country.
   Tehran Radio said U.S. helicopters attacked Iranian troops in
southern Iraq ``several times'' on Sunday during the Iraqi
offensive.
   There was no immediate reaction to the allegation from
Washington.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said today that during the
U.S. attack on the two oil platforms, Iran patrol boats fired on an
American vessel and a helicopter, but they escaped unscathed.
   U.S. warships sank the patrol boat, Carlucci said.
   Soon after the platform attack, the Iran gunboats fired on a
U.S. tugboat, but it too was not hit. Iranian gunboats also
attacked three facilities in the Mubarak oilfield off Sharjah, an
emirate in the southern gulf.
   Iran also accused Kuwait, the closest Arab state to the war
zone, of aiding the latest Iraqi attack and warned of retaliation.
Kuwait denied the charge.
   Iranian officials, quoted by IRNA, said Kuwait allowed Iraqi
troops to use its Bubiyan Island as a launching board for the
offensive.
   In Washington, the White House said the U.S. Navy attacked the
offshore Sassan and Sirri platforms in retaliation for a mine blast
that damaged the American frigate, Samuel B. Roberts, and wounded
10 crewmen last Thursday.
   Washington said Iran laid the mines in the Persian Gulf. Tehran
has denied the charge.
   Iraqi gunners, meanwhile, today fired four long-range missiles
into Tehran, the holy city of Qom and Isfahan, capital of the
16th-century Persian empire.
   The Iranian agency confirmed the three cities were struck by
missiles, claiming civilian casualties. But it did not give any
figure.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, said the
7th Army Corps and the Presidential Guard, ``destroyed all enemy
forces in the Faw triangle,'' which the Iranians overran in an
offensive in February 1986.
   It said ``small groups'' of Iranian soldiers were entrenched in
a few positions, facing ``death, imminent defeat or captivity.''
   The Iraqi offensive, codenamed ``blessed Ramadan,'' began
Sunday, on the eve of the beginning of Islam's holy month of
fasting.
   It was the first time that Iraq has taken the initiative in the
ground war since mid-1986, when it overran the abandoned Iranian
town of Mehran.
   The Faw peninsula is 50 miles southeast of Iraq's major port
city of Basra. The Iranians had held 120 square miles of the
peninsula for two years. Tehran reportedly has used Faw to launch
anti-ship, Chinese-made Silkworm missiles at Kuwaiti ships and oil
facilities.
</TEXT>
