<DOCNO> AP880418-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1434EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ForestFires     04-18 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fires,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grass, Forest Fires Consume 92,000 Acres So Far This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters from three states on
Monday helped battle grass and forest fires, which have consumed
92,300 acres around the state this year, officials said.
   Authorities called last year, when 88,000 acres burned in 900
fires, the worst in a decade, said Jean Bergerson, information
officer with the state Department of Natural Resources.
   This year, 798 fires, beginning around the first of this month,
already have burned 92,300 acres, Bergerson said. The fire season
usually ends about May 1.
   No injuries have been reported, and property damage has been
confined to 10 structures, most of them abandoned or unoccupied,
she said.
   A 7,000-acre grass fire that began near Warroad in northwestern
Minnesota on Saturday was 80 percent contained Monday, Bergerson
said. ``They're having problems with some burning peat on that
one,'' she said.
   Fifty new grass and forest fires, mostly in central Minnesota,
broke out Sunday but burned only 1,200 acres, Bergerson said.
   On Saturday, 200 fires burned 12,000 acres in central and
northern Minnesota, including a 2,000-acre fire near Willmar,
Bergerson said.
   Lower temperatures and some precipitation helped keep down the
new fires Sunday. No new major fires were reported Monday morning.
   Eighty U.S. Forest Service firefighters from Wisconsin, Michigan
and New Hampshire who arrived in Duluth on Sunday will be doing
mostly mop-up on fires that are contained but smouldering, she said.
   ``It's supposed to be a little warmer than yesterday and there's
a possibility of winds picking up this afternoon,'' Bergerson said.
``So, as the day goes on, we're expecting more fires to crop up
again.''
</TEXT>
