<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     04-18 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Jog Through Seoul to Protest Against Government, United
States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 20,000 anti-government students
shouted protests and scattered anti-U.S. leaflets on Monday, the
anniversary of a 1960 popular uprising.
   National police, meanwhile, were put on top alert after
President Roh Tae-woo called for severe punishment of political
activists who resort to violence. Roh, worried by clashes between
partisans of rival political parties, said his government would not
``tolerate violent and seditious acts'' in campaigning for National
Assembly elections on April 26.
   The government had mobilized about 35,000 riot police over the
weekend to protect campaign rallies nationwide.
   Opposition leader Kim Young-sam accused the governing Democratic
Justice Party of using ``gangsters'' to impede opposition rallies.
He said government officials were turning to the autocratic tactics
of former President Chun Doo-hwan.
   In the southern city of Suwon on Monday, students hurled tear
gas grenades and firebombs at a governing party office, but there
were no reports of injury.
   The students in Seoul chanted ``Down with dictatorship!'' as
they joined in a 10-mile run from Korea University to a
commemorative cemetery and back, turning the annual event into a
huge anti-government demonstration.
   The annual run commemorates the April 1960 popular uprising that
protested election procedures and helped topple autocratic
President Syngman Rhee.
   Riot police remained on alert along the course but did not
intervene.
   The students' leaflets criticized both the government and the
United States. Anti-U.S. sentiment has grown this year as
Washington pressured South Korea to open its markets.
   After Monday's run, about 5,000 students regrouped at Korea
University for a rally supporting labor rights.
   They called for joint struggle with striking workers, charging
the government with suppressing labor unions and their demands for
a better life.
   The students also shouted ``Yankee go home!'' and called for
removal of U.S. nuclear weapons from South Korea. Many Koreans
believe the 40,000 U.S. troops stationed in their country keep
nuclear weapons.
</TEXT>
