<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UnlikelyBidders     04-18 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Unlikely Bidders,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Owned by Public-Housing Tenants Seeks to Move Up in Class</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As bidders for lucrative city contracts go,
LeClaire Service Corp. isn't rich, doesn't wield much clout, and
has no friends in high places.
   But LeClaire, owned and operated by public-housing tenants,
wants a chance.
   ``A chance to become a productive, positive part of society, to
share a piece of the American dream,'' said Irene Johnson, the
driving force behind LeClaire Service, which draws its name,
management and workers from LeClaire Courts, a 615-unit housing
project on the South Side.
   LeClaire has a 15 percent stake in a joint venture bidding for
food and beverage concessions at Midway Airport. Heading the
venture is Flying Food Fare Inc., a company that specializes in
catering to the airline industry and is owned by Chicago
real-estate entrepreneur Sue Ling Gin.
   The contract, which would be for five years and likely will be
awarded within the next few weeks, calls for the operation of 22
concession stands at Midway and could generate revenues of $42
million.
   LeClaire Service, which employs five full-time and two part-time
workers, would own and operate three stands, and as the major
subcontracting partner, be responsible for recruiting half the
employees for all the stands.
   ``Obviously, the jobs would be a benefit, but more important,
the money would roll over in the neighborhood,'' said Ms. Gin,
whose Flying Food would own 70 percent of the venture, with the
remaining 15 percent divided among two Hispanic businesses and a
Chinese-American business group.
   The contract could mean $750,000 annually for the fledgling
company and between 40 and 80 new jobs for LeClaire residents, who
number about 3,500.
   Ms. Johnson considers LeClaire Service a success already. It
provides more than 700 meals daily to seven day-care centers and
has gross sales of about $140,000.
   ``All this began with the idea of making something different out
of public housing,'' she said, ``and we're succeeding every day.''
   LeClaire residents, taking a lesson and some counseling from
public-housing activists in St. Louis, Boston and Washington, took
steps six years ago to become Chicago's first tenant-managed
project.
   ``Once we got that in motion, got tenants interested and
involved in their homes, we decided the next step was economic
development,'' said Ms. Johnson. ``Finding jobs and keeping them
here.''
   There is no income ceiling for residents of LeClaire Courts,
where rent is based on 30 percent of income.
   With help and some training funds from the nearby Clarence
Darrow Community Center, LeClaire residents moved into the food
business five years ago.
   Ms. Gin learned about LeClaire Services when the community
center's executive director asked her to come in and share her
business acumen with members of the group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
