<DOCNO> AP880418-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1541EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Lost-Found     04-18 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lost-Found,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Watch Lost During WWII Recovered, Ring Found On Lakebed After 19
Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A diamond engagement ring is back on its owner's finger 19 years
after it fell in a lake, thanks to some hard work, and a World War
II GI's wristwatch has been returned from France surrounded by
mystery.
   The ring disappeared unnoticed in 1969 while Homerlene Bevan was
playing with her son at Lake Milton outside Youngstown, Ohio. Emma
Bouzek of Prairie du Chien, Wis., has no idea how her brother's
watch was left in France when he returned from the war, or why he
had her married name and hometown inscribed on the back.
   Mrs. Bevan and her husband, Barry, had been able to search for
the ring when Lake Milton receded in 1969 and, more recently, when
the lake was drained for dam repairs.
   ``We were on our hands and knees. We had a little rake for the
mud. Nothing,'' Mrs. Bevan, 47, said last week.
   Mrs. Bevan didn't know exactly where she lost the ring in 1969
because she didn't notice it missing until she got out of the water.
   Bevan decided to give the search one more try April 9 after the
state announced plans to refill the lake. Aided by a friend who had
a new metal detector, Bevan cleared an area about 5 feet from shore.
   ``He (Bevan) went right to the spot, not that anything told him
to, but he went right there,'' she said.
   The metal detector soon alerted them to something.
   ``He (Bevan) just started digging,'' Mrs. Bevan said. ``He dug
and could see a diamond shining, not bright, but the sun kind of
caught it.''
   Mrs. Bevan was not present when the ring was found. Later that
day when she returned home, she said, her husband had his hands in
his pockets and looked shaken.
   She asked him if he was all right and he said, ``Do you believe
in miracles?'' Then he slipped the ring on.
   ``He got tears in his eyes, and so did I,'' she said.
   In Wisconsin, Ms. Bouzek received the wristwatch by mail last
week from a French woman who had written to her in November.
   ``It runs like velvet,'' said Ms. Bouzek, 72. ``It's a Gruen.''
   Ms. Bouzek's brother, John White, was wounded during the
invasion of Normandy in June 1944, and spent some time in a
hospital in France before returning to Prairie du Chien. He later
moved to Milwaukee.
   But he died nearly three years ago at age 66, long before Ms.
Bouzek knew of the watch and its mystery.
   According to Ms. Bouzek, Therese Hervet, 43, of Reims, France,
sent a letter to the name and city inscribed on the back of the
watch. The inscription on the watch read, ``E.R. Bouzek, Prairie du
Chien, Wis.''
   Ms. Hervet wrote that she had found the watch among her
grandfather's belongings. She said her grandfather had purchased it
at an auction in southern France in the 1940s.
   Ms. Bouzek said she wrote back explaining that the watch was her
late brother's.
   She said she was surprised to learn that her brother engraved
her initials and her married name on the back of his watch.
   But if nothing else the watch introduced Ms. Bouzek and Ms.
Hervet, and they have exchanged several letters.
   ``It's like shaking hands in friendship across the ocean,'' she
said. ``I still can't believe it after 44 years.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880418-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1638EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Gulf-Forces 1stLd-Writethru a0690 04-18 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Forces, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0690,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Size of U.S. Naval Force Remains Constant in Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Gulf Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: CORRECTS `Vosper,' 10th graf pvs, bgng: Paul Beaver</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's decision to order military
strikes against two Iranian offshore platforms came without any
build-up in the number of U.S. warships in the region.
   Ever since February, when the Pentagon adjusted its Joint Task
Force Middle East by withdrawing the battleship Iowa and the
helicopter carrier Okinawa, the Navy's presence in the region has
remained fairly constant at between 25 and 30 ships.
   Of that total, roughly half _ including six mine sweepers _
normally operate inside the Persian Gulf, ready to escort
commercial tankers. The other half _ led by the aircraft carrier
Enterprise _ operate in the nearby Gulf of Oman and northern
Arabian Sea.
   According to Pentagon officials who asked not to be named,
Monday's operation saw commanders move several ships from the Gulf
of Oman into the Persian Gulf, including the destroyers Joseph
Strauss, O'Brien, Merrill and Lynde McCormick and the frigate
Bagley.
   That was considered more than enough firepower to deal with the
offshore platforms and any Iranian ships that sought to intervene,
the sources said.
   Fighters and attack jets from the Enterprise also provided
constant air cover over the lower half of the gulf, the sources
said.
   All told, the Navy battle group inside the gulf at the time of
Monday's attack included the command ship Coronado; a combat stores
ship; the six mine sweepers; plus one cruiser, one amphibious
landing ship, four destroyers and seven frigates.
   The Enterprise and a second cruiser remained outside the gulf in
the northern Arabian Sea along with a handful of support ships, the
officials added.
   As for the Iranians, according to Jim McCoy of the Institute for
Strategic Studies, Iran has four 1500-ton, ``quite small''
frigates, built in Britain for the shah of Iran in 1971-72. ``They
are their most modern surface ships, and Iran has been maintaining
patrols with these frigates in the Strait of Hormuz, assisted by a
number of amphibious ships.''
   Paul Beaver, naval editor of Jane's Defence Weekly, adds that
the four are Vosper Mark-5 frigates and have been ``very active
recently.'' He says Iran also has a number of larger patrol craft
which are Cape-class, U.S. Coast Guard-like vessels.
   McCoy said Iran has three destroyers believed non-operational,
one from Britain, two from the United States.
   He said Iran also has at least 50 of ``what are basically
recreational speed boats, 40-footers, with large engines in which
Revolutionary Guards carry out attacks (on tankers) with
rocket-propelled grenades.''
   Beaver calls them Swedish-built Boghammers, and said they are
equipped with machine guns and sometimes mortars. According to
Jane's Iran also has:
   _11 French attack craft (missile) with American Harpoon missile
systems, but because as of 1986 Iran had only nine missiles left,
the boats have been used as gunboats.
   _two (out of four) Corvette 900-ton warships left in operation,
six Hovercraft, two Midget subs whose origin is unknown and which
have not been in operation yet, and two landing ships.
   In the Air, Beaver lists eight F-14 Tomcat fighters, 20 F-4
Phantom fighter bombers and as many as 40 F-5 Tigers, all U.S.
built.
   Also, they have one maritime patrol aircraft, a number of small
spotting craft and a number of Agusta 212 helicopters used by
Revolutionary Guards.
   Don Kerr of the Institute adds that Iran has one P-3 Orion
aircraft ``but it's thought that it has almost nothing electronic
working so is used for visual reconnaisance'' plus out of a
collection of 26 C-130s, maybe now as low as 15 work for transport
purposes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
