<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrapezeDeath     04-18 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trapeze Death,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trapeze Artist's Father Had Begged Her to Quit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIALEAH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The father of a trapeze artist who was
killed when she fell 18 feet during a performance said he had
begged his daughter to quit the act, but that she insisted on
continuing to perform.
   Belinda Nielsen Visingard of Circus USA died Sunday in front of
900 people when she slipped from the trapeze bar and fell head
first to the floor.
   She always performed without a net, her family said.
   Police shut down the circus for the night.
   ``She would have said the show must go on,'' said Gunnar
Amandis, Ms. Visingard's uncle and booking agent. ``The rest of the
crew wanted to keep going in her memory.''
   Finn Nielsen of Sarasota said he had told his 31-year-old
daughter he would support her for the rest of her life if she would
quit her high-flying, daredevil circus performances.
   ``I tried everything I could think of to get her to quit. I told
her she'd never have to work again if she would just stop
performing,'' said Nielsen, a former circus performer himself.
``But nothing could stop her, because this is what she loved to do.
Once you're in this kind of life, you want to stay in it.''
   Amandis said he told her Saturday night to stop taking so many
chances during her routine.
   ``She would start her act with tricks others closed their acts
with,'' Amandis said. ``I told her to ease up a bit, but she just
kept doing her act the way she wanted. Because this was probably
the lowest height she's ever worked from, maybe she wanted to be
more daring.''
   Amandis said Ms. Visingard was almost finished with her routine
when she fell. He saw the accident.
   ``She could've jumped down from that height and not gotten
hurt,'' he said. ``It was a freak accident. It was the way she
fell. No other way would she have been hurt. God must have wanted
to take her.''
   Tom Koenig, 40, of Hialeah, who took his wife and two children
to the show, agreed.
   ``She fell forward, and she was trying to right herself up, and
by doing that she fell right on the side of her face,'' he said.
``She wasn't that high up. She just hit the wrong way.''
   ``At the second she fell, everybody was silent,'' said his wife,
Annie Koenig. ``Everybody thought it was part of the act. Then we
realized what had happened.''
   Amandis said a police check of his niece's equipment revealed
that everything was in perfect order.
   Ms. Visingard, who performed using the name Belinda Amandis, was
born into a circus family in Lansdale, Pa., her parents said. She
joined The Amandis, a family teeterboard act that included her
mother and father, when she was about 8 or 9 years old, her father
said.
   Ms. Visingard started a trapeze act with her ex-husband about
eight years ago, the family said. She always performed without a
net, they said.
   Nielsen and his wife left the circus life about 12 years ago, he
said. He now works as a detention officer for the Sarasota County
Sheriff's Office. But his daughter didn't want to do anything but
perform.
   ``She loved the life,'' said her mother, Ella Nielsen. ``She
loved the people, the crowds, and she loved to do daring things.''
</TEXT>
