<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1537EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran-Iraq Bjt   04-18 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq, Bjt,0753</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Says It Retook Town of Faw on Strategic Peninsula</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said its forces Monday retook the town
of Faw near the tip of a strategic Iraqi peninsula that had been
captured by Iran more than two years ago.
   Iran claimed U.S. helicopters attacked Iranian troops and Kuwait
provided a staging area to support the Iraqi offensive. The United
States and Kuwait denied the charge.
   Thousands of Iranians were killed or wounded in the two-day-old
offensive, named ``Blessed Ramadan'' after the Moslem fasting
month, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
   It was the first time Iraq took the initiative in a major ground
push since the early years of the 7{-year-old war.
   ``Victorious Iraqi armed forces entered Faw town today and
hoisted the Iraqi flag,'' the state-run agency reported in an
urgent dispatch.
   A war communique read over state-run television said Iranian
occupying forces were driven out of the peninsula, over to the
other side of the Shatt-al-Arab waterway that forms its northern
shore.
   Tehran Radio, monitored in Nicosia, quoted a Supreme Defense
Council statement as saying: ``In direct, open and practical
support for the Iraqi regime, American forces have entered the
war.''
   Pentagon spokesman Fred Hoffman said in Washington that Iran's
charge was totally without foundation. No U.S. military forces have
been involved with Iraqi units, he said.
   Earlier in the day, the official Islamic Republic News Agency
reiterated claims that Iranian Revolutionary Guards had ``routed''
the offensive when it was launched Saturday night.
   The agency repeated accusations that Iraq used chemical weapons
against Iranian defenders in the Faw region.
   In the ``war of the cities,'' Iraqi missile batteries fired
long-range rockets into Tehran, the holy city of Qom and Isfahan.
The Iranian agency confirmed the three cities were struck by
missiles and civilians were killed. It gave no figures.
   Iraq said an Iranian missile landed in Baghdad, killing
civilians.
   The Iraqi agency said troops of the Seventh Army Corps, backed
by elite Presidential Guards, took the ``Faw triangle,'' the bulk
of the peninsula that juts out into the Persian Gulf and straddles
Iraq's only sea outlet. It later reported the seizure of the town
of Faw, the only town on the peninsula.
   In the two-pronged offensive, Iraqi forces stormed Iranian
positions from the west across the salt marshes that form most of
the peninsula and also attacked its northern shore.
   ``The invaders are now licking their wounds on the other bank of
the Shatt-al-Arab, distancing themselves from the confrontation
line with the Iraqis,'' said a communique quoted by INA.
   ``God is great. Blessed be the Iraqi victory. Blessed be the
Arabs' victory and blessed be the victory of our armed forces.''
   The Iraqi accounts said the bulk of the Iranian forces in the
peninsula were destroyed, but they did not claim the entire
peninsula was retaken. They said Iraqi forces continued their
advance.
   IRNA, in reports monitored in Cyprus, claimed that ``in an open
confession of their dirty ganging-up, U.S. and Iraqi forces using
Kuwaiti facilities attacked Iranian positions in the Faw region,
southern Iraq'' on Monday.
   It claimed U.S. helicopter gunships ``suddenly appeared on the
battle scene from the sea side and attacked Iranian combatants.''
   The agency claimed Iranian Revolutionary Guards immediately
opened fire on the U.S. helicopters, forcing them to ``hastily drop
their rockets and flee the scene.''
   The accusation came after U.S. forces destroyed two Iranian oil
platforms in the gulf in retaliation for allegedly planting the
mine that almost sank a U.S. frigate last week.
   In a series of clashes later in the day, U.S. forces sank an
Iranian patrol boat and bombed two Iranian frigates, setting them
ablaze, after they shot at U.S. planes and ships, the Pentagon said.
   Since they were driven out of Iranian territory in 1982, Iraqi
forces have waged a largely defensive war.
   The Faw peninsula, about 50 miles southeast of Iraq's major port
city of Basra, was lost to the Iranian attackers in a major
offensive in February 1986.
   Iranian troops carried out a nighttime amphibious landing in
Faw, erecting a pontoon bridge.
   They eventually retained about 120 square miles of the
peninsula, using their new positions to shell Iraq's main air base
near Basra.
   They also reportedly used Faw to launch anti-ship, Chinese-made
Silkworm missiles at Kuwaiti ships and oil facilities.
</TEXT>
