<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Obit-Nevelson Bjt   04-18 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Nevelson, Bjt,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Louise Nevelson, Renowned Sculptor, Dead at 88</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY10,11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Artist Louise Nevelson, who struggled until she
was nearly 60 to win the public's attention, has died at the age of
88 with a reputation as one of the nation's greatest sculptors.
   Mrs. Nevelson, who had been in poor health for several months,
died Sunday at her home in Manhattan's Little Italy.
   She recently completed a 35-foot black steel sculpture for the
National Institutes of Health in Bethesda, Md. A show of her 1950s
work is scheduled this summer at the Pompidou Center in Paris.
   ``She's seen as one of the great artists of our time,'' said
Thomas Messer, director of the Guggenheim museum and an
acquaintance of the late artist.
   Mrs. Nevelson was ``a walking work of art. ... Every gesture in
her life and every form in her art had larger meanings,'' he said.
   A regal woman who wore mainly black, the artist was perhaps best
known for black-on-black wood boxes assembled from ``found''
objects.
   Her work was big, dramatic, often dark and intense. Some critics
felt it was cold, airless and sterile. Others called it graceful,
warm, haunting and uplifting.
   Her works are included in the collections of many major museums
and have been taken on exhibitions around the nation and the world.
   Mrs. Nevelson was born in Kiev, Russia, in 1899. Her family
immigrated when she was 4 and settled in Rockland, Maine.
   ``I felt like an artist,'' she said of the talent that emerged
in childhood. ``I have that blessing, and there was never a time
that I questioned it or doubted it.''
   ``She was enormously honest, enormously gifted and ferociously
independent,'' recalled Maurine Rothschild, president of the
William A. Farnsworth Art Museum in Rockland.
   In 1920, she married Charles Nevelson, a wealthy New York ship
owner, and moved to New York City. They had a son, Myron, and
separated in 1931.
   Mrs. Nevelson then traveled to Munich to study. Upon the rise of
the Nazis, she returned to New York to work with paint, plaster,
terra cotta, marble, aluminum, bronze and bits of wood.
   ``She was one of the most important artists in America, along
with Georgia O'Keeffe,'' said Peter Dittmar, art critic for the Die
Welt newspaper in Bonn, West Germany.
   Although Mrs. Nevelson was a serious artist for half a century,
her work was largely ignored until 1958, when it was included in an
anthology at the Museum of Modern Art.
   ``She was intensely independent and very courageous. She set an
astounding example of artistic integrity and recognition for women
artists,'' said Richard Oldenburg, MOMA director. ``I remember the
flamboyance of her appearance ... her tremendous warmth and spirit.
She had a large reserve of wit _ she was very good company.''
   Mrs. Nevelson's fame grew in 1959 when, at the age of 60, she
won acclaim for her first all-white ``environment,'' titled
``Dawn's Wedding Feast.''
   ``Once she emerged as a major figure in the late '50s, she could
never again be ignored,'' critic Hilton Kramer wrote in an
introduction to ``Nevelson's World'' in 1983. ``She turned out to
be one of those artists who changed the way we look at things.''
   ``Louise Nevelson was an important artist of originality,
strength and integrity who has made a lasting contribution to the
history of 20th century sculpture,'' said Richard Marshall, an
associate curator who organized Nevelson exhibitions at the Whitney
Museum in New York.
   Age did not slow her. In her 84th year, Mrs. Nevelson embarked
on creating sets and costumes for a production of the opera ``Orfeo
and Euridice'' in St. Louis. In 1985, she was among the first
recipients of the National Medal of the Arts.
   ``She wanted to make a major contribution to the world as an
artist. ... The work will remain,'' said Richard Koshalek, director
of the Museum of Contemporary Art in Los Angeles. ``The individual
will be missed the most _ the spirit and dedication and kindness
that Louise Nevelson demonstrated to other artists, museum and the
world in general.''
   Survivors include her son and three granddaughters. Funeral
services will be private. A memorial service will be announced at a
later date.
</TEXT>
