<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Higgins     04-18 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Higgins,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radio Says Kidnapped Marine Has Been Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Beirut radio station reported Monday
that U.S. Marine Lt. Col William R. Higgins was killed by his
kidnappers this month after several weeks in captivity.
   United Nations officials said they had heard nothing to confirm
the report by the Christian-controlled Voice of Lebanon.
   The station, which has broadcast several inaccurate reports
about the hostages in Lebanon, said Higgins was ``killed and buried
by his captors'' early this month in Siddiqine, a village in south
Lebanon.
   Higgins was serving with the U.N. Interim Force in south Lebanon
when he was kidnapped near the southern port of Tyre on Feb. 17.
   Timur Goksel, the spokesman for the U.N. group, said Monday:
``We have no such information, and therefore we cannot comment on
the radio report.''
   ``We have checked with our sources, and everybody was surprised
when they heard about the report,'' he added in a telephone
interview from the U.N. group's headquarters in Naqoura on the
Lebanese-Israeli border.
   At U.N. headquarters in New York, spokeswoman Nadia Younes told
reporters that UNIFIL had checked with its sources and found no
confirmation of the broadcast.
   The radio said Higgins was killed hours before pro-Syrian
militiamen of Justice Minister Nabih Berri's Amal militia captured
Siddiqine from supporters of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, apparently
to keep Amal from claiming credit for his liberation.
   Amal and Hezbollah spokesmen in Beirut did not comment on the
report. The two groups have been at odds since Higgins, 43, of
Danville, Ky., was kidnapped.
   Siddiqine, 10 miles southeast of Tyre, was a Hezbollah
stronghold before Amal crushed its Shiite Moslem fundamentalist
rivals in a four-day battle early this month.
   Amal supports the presence of the U.N. peacekeeping force in
predominantly Shiite south Lebanon. Hezbollah, or the Party of God,
opposes it.
   Amal has charged that Hezbollah masterminded Higgins' abduction
to undermine Amal's control of south Lebanon.
   Hezbollah is believed to be an umbrella for factions holding
most of the 22 foreign hostages in Lebanon. It has not claimed to
hold any foreign hostages.
   Higgins' abduction was claimed by a group calling itself the
Organization of the Oppressed on Earth, which charged that he was a
CIA spy. Both the United States and United Nations have denied the
charge.
   Amal spokesmen had said their fighters found no trace of Higgins
in any of the Hezbollah strongholds they captured.
   The foreigners missing and presumed kidnapped in Lebanon are
nine Americans, four Frenchmen, three Britons, one Irishman, one
Italian, one West German, one Indian, and two unidentified men.
   The longest held is Terry A. Anderson, 40, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
