<1ST_LINE>u w BC-US-Gulf-Text     04-18 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-US-Gulf-Text,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Gulf Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the statement by White
House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater on Monday's U.S. military action
in the Persian Gulf:
   ``Acting under his authority as commander-in-chief, the
president has directed U.S. forces at 1 a.m. EDT today to strike
Iranian military targets in the southern Persian Gulf. Our forces
attacked oil platforms at Sirri and Sassan in the southern Gulf.
These platforms are used as command and control radar stations for
the Iranian military.
   The attacks are under way at this time.
   These actions were taken in response to Iran's recent resumption
of minelaying in international waters and its mine attack on the
USS Samuel B. Roberts. The government of Iran has be of the cash offer
and
restructuring at between $1.1 billion to $1.2 billion.
   Spokesman D. Emerson Phelps said the deal would allow Irving
management to retain control of the company, although the board of
directors would be expanded to include four representatives from
Banca Commerciale.
   The Banca Commerciale offer, which was approved by both
companies' boards and was set to begin Tuesday, includes the
purchase of 9.5 million Irving shares, or 51 percent of its common
stock outstanding, for $65 a share. In addition, a special
$10-a-share dividend would be payable to shareholders upon
completion of the deal, Irving said.
   The company said stockholders could receive cash for about half
of their shares, and retain the other half and ``thereby
participate in the realization of Irving's attractive long-term
potential.''
   ``Our shareholders will benefit far more from the affiliation
with BCI (Banca Commerciale Italiana) than the proposal advanced
from BNY (Bank of New York),'' Irving Chairman Joseph A. Rice said
in a statement. ``Irving anticipates increases in its revenues as a
result of its ongoing relationship with BCI.''
   Irving's announcement comes just days after Bank of New York's
shareholders voted to support management's $1 billion-plus rare
hostile bid for Irving. The tender offer, which began last month
after regulatory approval, is for $15 in cash and 1.575 of its
common shares for each of Irving's roughly 18.1 common shares
outstanding.
   Bank of New York, which holds a 4.9 percent stake in Irving,
also is running a slate of 16 nominees to Irving's board of
directors. Irving's annual meeting is scheduled for Thursday,
although most business will be conducted at a reconvened meeting on
Saturday to give sharholders time to digest the latest offer,
Irving said.
   Irving has repeatedly spurned Bank of New York's takeover
proposals, which began about seven months ago. It had maintained it
wanted to remain independent but disclosed recently it was seeking
a ``white knight'' friendly merger partner as an alternative.
   Hostile takeovers are rare in the banking industry. Although a
few have been tried over the years, most have resulted in the
target companies reaching friendly mergers with third parties. A
merger between Bank of New York and Irving would have created one
of the nation's 15 largest bank holding companies with combined
assets of more than $40 billion.
   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady said his company was
studying the Banca Commerciale offer and had no immediate comment.
   Michael Starr, a banking analyst with Duff & Phelps Inc. in
Chicago, said Bank of New York could sweeten its current offer, but
then it would have to resubmit itself to the lengthy regulatory
process that includes hearings before the Federal Reserve and New
York State Banking boards.
   Analysts said they weren't surprised that Irving sought help
from a foreign bank, since many large U.S. banks lack the capital
for big acquisitions. However, some experts said they found the
terms of the deal a bit complex and said that probabaly accounted
for the relatively lackluster activity on Wall Street.
   In New York Stock Exchange trading, Irving shares rose slightly,
then fell $1 to $60.37{. Bank of New York shares gained $1 to
$31.65{.
   ``I thought the Street would have viewed the stock as being
worth more,'' said James L. Bellessa Jr., a banking analyst with
Great Falls, Mont.-based D.A. Davidson & Co.``I think part of the
problem is the Street doesn't understand it all.''
   Bellessa, though, called the deal ``a good alternative to what
Bank of New York was proposing.''
   As part of its restructuring Irving said it would begin ``an
intensive program of cost savings'' that could raise net income to
about $1.60 a share in 1988 and $2.75 next year. In addition, the
banking concern said it would immediately increase Irving's annual
common dividend from $2.42 a share to $4.50.
   Irving lost $193.27 million last year, after raising its
loan-loss reserves to cover troubled Third World debt.
   To pay for the special $10-a-share dividend, which is part of
the Banca Commerciale deal, Irving said it planned to sell its Wall
Street headquarters and its 39 percent equity interest in Banca
della Svizzera Italiana for more than the current market price of
about $325 million.
   Banca Commerciale, based in Milan, has assets of around $60
billion and is Italy's second largest bank, behind Banca Nazionale
del Lavoro. About 64 percent of Banca Commerciale is owned by the
giant state holding company Istituto per la Ricostruzione
Industriale. Irving's assets total $24.12 billion.
</TEXT>
