<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ABC-Stoddard     04-18 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ABC-Stoddard,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stoddard Disappointed in `Dolly,' `Moonlighting'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC is considering buying out Dolly Parton's
contract and canning her variety show ``Dolly!'' which proved a
disappointment in the ratings, ABC Entertainment President Brandon
Stoddard said Monday.
   ``We're now in a situation where we frankly don't know what
we're going to do about `Dolly!' next year,'' Stoddard told a news
conference.
   ``As you all know, we actually have the right not to do the
show. There is a penalty payment we would pay if we did not go
ahead on the second year,'' Stoddard said. Parton got a two-year
guarantee in her multimillion-dollar contract with ABC. Stoddard
would not say how much the penalty would be.
   Stoddard listed ``Dolly!'' and ``Moonlighting'' as his two
biggest disappointments in a season that saw ABC eke out a
second-place finish after coming in last the previous year. NBC has
won its third season in a row, and CBS finished last for the first
time ever.
   ``Moonlighting,'' formerly a top-10 show, dropped into the top
20 this season, due to frequent repeats and episodes without Cybill
Shepherd, who was pregnant. Nevertheless, Stoddard said, the show
likely will come back next season.
   Stoddard was not optimistic about an early end to the strike by
the Writers Guild of America and said if it lasts into the summer,
it could substantially delay the start of the fall season.
   That could chase more viewers away from the three networks which
have seen a 9 percent decline in audiences since 1986-87, according
to the A.C. Nielsen Co.
   A delay would mean more reruns and more viewers would presumably
turn to cable or other alternatives, Stoddard said.
   ``I think the net effect of that is that even when we come back
on the air, it could be the loss of a couple more share points for
the networks,'' he said. ``It's not a happy thought.
   ``In addition to that, when the strike is finished, and we start
putting programs on the air, there's going to be tremendous
pressure to get something up on that screen, and maybe it ain't
perfect when we do. I think there also could be some erosion caused
by the lack of quality. This is a very serious problem.''
   He said ABC is considering repeating miniseries should the
strike cause a significant delay in the start of the new season.
   But the 30-hour miniseries ``War and Remembrance,'' which would
be available for the fall, won't be wasted then when NBC will have
the Summer Olympics, Stoddard said. Instead, the ballyhooed
miniseries will likely be saved for the February 1989 sweeps period.
   Stoddard also said, while happy the network was second for the
season in the Nielsen ratings, with an average, prime-time rating
of 13.7 to CBS' 13.5, the performance really was ``not that
terrific.'' NBC had a 16.1.
   Without high-rated prime-time sports _ the World Series, the
Super Bowl and the Winter Olympics _ ABC actually was third.
   The rating is a percentage of the nation's 88.6 million homes
with televisions.
   As for ABC's new shows, Stoddard said there would be some early
pickups announced in a week or so. Those are likely to include
``The Wonder Years'' and ``thirtysomething.''
   Stoddard said it looked good for a renewal of ``Hooperman,'' but
a decision on ``The `Slap' Maxwell Story'' is a ``tough call.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
