<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Iran-Warning     04-18 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Iran-Warning,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Issues Fresh Warning to Iran</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA </BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shortly after the U.S. military attack on two
Iranian oil platforms in the Persian Gulf, the United States issued
a fresh message to Iran warning that additional provocations would
be met with a firm U.S. response, the State Department said Monday.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said Iranian
authorities were told that the United States was exercising its
right of self-defense following the mine explosion last Friday in
which the USS Samuel B. Roberts was damaged, injuring U.S. Navy
personnel.
   ``The extreme seriousness with which the government of the
United States views such unacceptable activity by Iranian vessels
should be understood by the Islamic government of Iran,'' the
message said.
   ``Any further provocative or hostile Iranian military or
terrorist actions against U.S. personnel or targets will receive a
firm U.S. response.''
   There was no further elaboration and Redman refused to speculate
what response the administration has in mind.
   Redman said five NATO allies _ Britain, Italy, West Germany, the
Netherlands, and Belgium _ were notified before Monday's attack
that the action was pending. All have naval vessels in the Persian
Gulf.
   A group of other countries, including the Soviet Union and Iraq,
was informed as the attack commenced, Redman said.
   Another U.S. official, insisting on anonymity, said a cable was
sent to all U.S. diplomatic posts abroad at approximately the same
time the attack took place advising them of the U.S. action and
asking them to guard against possible retaliatory terrorist
incidents.
   The official said requests for U.S. posts abroad to increase
their state of readiness at such times are normal practice.
   Redman said Iran had been warned four times about mining in gulf
waters since last July when a reflagged Kuwaiti vessel, the
Bridgeton, struck a mine near Farsi Island. He said other warnings
followed in September and October.
   The note to Iran said that despite these warnings and the fact
that U.S. forces in the gulf have not threatened Iranian forces,
Iran ``has persisted in this illegal and reckless conduct.''
   Redman said the message was sent to Iranian authorities through
the Swiss, which handles U.S. interests in Iran in the absence of
diplomatic relations between the two countries.
</TEXT>
