<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama Bjt   04-18 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama, Bjt,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banks Reopen, but Only for Deposits</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some banks opened for the first time
in six weeks Monday, but only to accept deposits, and people who
still have currency in this cash-poor economy were in no rush to
give it up.
   Business was brisk at a few major foreign banks, but slow at
institutions owned and operated by Panamanians.
   About 30 people were outside Chase Manhattan when it opened.
Virtually all were depositing checks they have been unable to cash
for 45 days because U.S. economic sanctions have dried up the money
supply in Panama, whose currency is the dollar.
   ``I'll keep my cash at home,'' said Frank Farrell, who is
retired and was depositing several dividend checks.``Later on,
maybe I'll deposit cash.''
   Asked if he felt secure putting checks in a bank that had been
closed since March 4 by order of an insolvent government, Farrell
replied: ``I don't worry. Chase is solid.''
   The banks were closed after Panamanians began withdrawing large
sums of money on Feb. 26. That was the day Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, the real power in Panama, dismissed civilian President
Eric Arturo Delvalle for trying to fire him as commander of the
armed forces and police.
   The Reagan administration subsequently ordered the Federal
Reserve to halt the flow of dollars to Panama. Lawyers acting for
Delvalle were able to freeze Panamanian funds in U.S. banks.
   Washington also has imposed other economic sanctions on Panama
in an effort to out Noriega, who is under indictment in U.S.
federal courts on charges of drug trafficking and money laundering.
He denies the charges.
   A middle-aged woman in line at the Chase office said she was
depositing only checks because ``I need the cash to eat.''
   Short lines lines also formed outside Citibank and the Bank of
America but Panamanian-owned banks, whose solvency is in question,
did not appear even to be getting many checks for deposit.
   A few minutes after it opened, only six customers were in the
spacious lobby of the National Bank of Panama, largest of the
locally owned banks.
   The Panamanian Banking Association says its members will not
resume full service until the government can assure a steady,
adequate supply of dollars. Most of the more than 120 banks doing
business in Panama belong to the association.
   Since the banks closed, Panama has operated on a cash-only basis
and the government has been able to make only partial salary
payments to employees.
   Only banks licensed to provide full services were included in
the Banking Commission's reopening order. Many foreign banks accept
checking, savings and time deposits and provide fund transfers, but
do not make loans or offer other banking services.
   One bank manager said privately the reopening for deposits only
would ``reestablish the check as an acceptable payment'' in lieu of
dollars.
   ``Panama is a check economy, if you want to use that word,'' he
said. ``This is an initial step to reestablish the reopening of
banks ... but I really don't know if this is going to work or not.''
   He said clients depositing checks would not be able to draw cash
from their accounts until or unless the banks resume full services,
``but if you owe money to somebody and he will accept a check, you
can write a check on your new balance.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
