<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Gulf-Pentagon 7thLd-Writethru a0665-a0731-a0736-a0743-a0755
04-18 1268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Pentagon, 7th Ld-Writethru,</2ND_LINE>
<TEXT>
   a0665-a0731-a0736-a0743-a0755,1200
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines pvs. Removes last four grafs pvs to shorten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Iranian navy frigates were attacked and
disabled today by American forces and four smaller gunboats either
sunk or damaged in a wave of fighting across the lower half of the
Persian Gulf, the Pentagon said.
   No American injuries or fatalities were reported, but Defense
Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said a Cobra attack helicopter with two
crewmen aboard was late in returning to a Navy cruiser and that a
search had been mounted for the aircraft.
   The naval action with Iran began when U.S. warships attacked and
destroyed two offshore platforms in retaliation for last week's
mining of the frigate Samuel B. Roberts.
   Carlucci, appearing at his second press briefing of the day,
described as ``foolhardy behavior'' Iran's decision to escalate the
fighting today. He said he assumed the attacks could only be
explained as stemming from fanaticism.
   Earlier today, Carlucci and other Pentagon officials disclosed
that an Iranian patrol boat had been sunk after firing a missile at
the cruiser Wainwright, and that two Iranian navy frigates had been
attacked and disabled after firing on U.S. aircraft.
   During his second briefing, Carlucci announced that a Navy A-6
Intruder jet had sunk at least one and possibly three small Iranian
gunboats after observing them attack commercial vessels and oil
rigs off the coast of the United Arab Emirates.
   That confrontation occurred around 7:30 a.m. EDT, Carlucci said,
or about 6{ hours after U.S. forces attacked the Iranian offshore
platforms.
   Navy jets were assigned to patrol the area after reports were
received indicating an American commercial boat, the Willy Tide,
had been attacked, Carlucci indicated.
   The defense secretary described the U.S. attack on the platforms
as a ``measured response'' given available evidence proving Iran
had sown a new minefield in the gulf last week.
   All of the fighting that occurred after the attacks on the
offshore platforms was in the cause of American self-defense,
Carlucci said.
   Asked if he were surprised by the Iranian decision to confront
U.S. forces directly, the secretary replied: ``I wouldn't use the
word surprised because the Iranians have been known to engage in
this kind of, frankly, foolhardy behavior before.
   ``I might say we were disappointed. We hoped that they would
heed the warnings that we gave. But when they did not, we took
appropriate action.''
   Asked how he would explain Iran's decision to ignore U.S.
warnings, he said: ``I'm not sure that it's explainable in terms of
Western logic at this point. I have to only assume that it's some
kind of a fanatical reaction or slavish obedience to a contingency
plan.
   ``It certainly makes no sense whatsoever in military terms. And
we hope that tomorrow that will bring peace in the region.''
   The Pentagon said the missing American helicopter had been on a
routine surveillance mission from the cruiser Wainwright in the
lower central gulf, and that there was no indication the aircraft
had become involved in hostile action. As of 3:30 p.m. EDT,
Carlucci said, the helicopter was about 40 minutes overdue and
efforts to establish radio contact had been unsuccessful.
   The Pentagon said it had launched a search-and-rescue mission,
but had not spotted the helicopter.
   Earlier, the Pentagon said the two Iranian frigates had been
attacked and disabled after firing missiles at U.S. jets flying
overhead.
   The Defense Department said the last of those confrontations
ccurred around 9:40 a.m. EDT, when a frigate identified as the
Sabalan fired on A-6 Intruder attack jets from the carrier
Enterprise.
   ``The aircraft returned fire and hit the Sabalan with a single
laser-guided bomb,'' the Pentagon added.
   ``As darkness fell, the Sabalan was down by the stern with tugs
fore and aft. We do not intend to renew attacks on the Sabalan
unless she exhibits further hostile intent.''
   The fight with the Sabalan came just 70 minutes after a similar
confrontation with an identical frigate named the Sahand. It also
was attacked and set afire after firing missiles at the U.S.
aircraft, the Pentagon said.
   The confrontation with the Sahand occurred in the Strait of
Hormuz, the entrance to the Persian Gulf, around 8:30 a.m. EDT,
about 7{ hours after the United States bombarded and destroyed two
Iranian offshore platforms, said Dan Howard, the Pentagon's chief
spokesman.
   Earlier, an Iranian patrol boat was sunk after advancing on U.S.
warships; an American helicopter came under fire from another
gunboat, and one U.S. warship fired on two approaching Iranian jet
fighters, although it was unclear whether they were hit.
   Howard gave this account of the Sahand incident:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Iranian frigate, a 310-foot warship named the Sahand,
steamed out of the naval base at Bandar Abbas earlier this morning
and ``was noticed closing rapidly upon three U.S. warships.''
   ``The Sahand ignored repeated warnings from a U.S. E-2
(early-warning) aircraft to turn away or to be considered hostile.
About 8:30 a.m. (EDT), the Sahand fired upon three A-6 Intruder
aircraft on patrol in the area off the USS Enterprise.
   ``The Intruders returned fire with two Harpoon missiles and a
number of laser-guided bombs. Shortly thereafter, the USS Strauss,
a destroyer, engaged the Sahand with an additional Harpoon. All the
ordnance appears to have hit the frigate and it's heavily damaged.
   ``It's on fire at the moment and the smoke is so heavy that it's
difficult to do a further assessment at this point.''
   Howard added that the Strauss had been patrolling the area in
and around the Strait of Hormuz along with two other ships, the
destroyer O'Brien and the frigate Jack Williams.
   Neither the A-6 attack jets nor the U.S. warships sustained any
damage and there were no reports of any American injuries or
casualties, the spokesman said.
   Howard revealed the battle with the Sahand this morning a bit
more than an hour after Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci and
Adm. William Crowe, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
appeared at an early-morning briefing to discuss the U.S. attacks.
   The destruction of the two Iranian offshore platforms was
ordered by President Reagan on Sunday night in retaliation for the
mine strike that almost sank the frigate Samuel B. Roberts last
week, Carlucci said.
   Carlucci said there was no doubt the mine field in which the
Roberts became entrapped had been laid recently by Iran. Mines
discovered in the area carry the same type of serial numbers as
those captured last year aboard an Iranian mine-laying ship,
Carlucci said.
   According to Carlucci and Crowe, today's operation began around
1 a.m. EDT with two groups of Navy warships attacking two oil
platforms in the central Persian Gulf.
   Both of the platforms were ultimately destroyed _ one by naval
gunfire and the other by planted explosives, the two said.
   But in the process of attacking one of the platforms, the
so-called Sassan platform, the U.S. ships came under fire from a
machine gun on the facility, Crowe said.
   And immediately after the attack on the second platform, the
Sirri platform, an Iranian patrol boat roughly 150 feet in length
began advancing on the three American warships and ignored warnings
to keep its distance, the admiral continued.
   ``It (the Iranian boat) acknowledged the message but continued
to close,'' Crowe said. ``After several warnings, we engaged and he
fired at us simultaneously with a missile.
   ``The Simpson fired three Standard missiles, two of which hit
the (Iranian vessel). The Wainwright fired one, which hit the
(Iranian). We subsequently closed on it and fired another missile
and it sunk. We found no people in the water.''
</TEXT>
