<DOCNO> AP880418-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1954EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Bombs     04-18 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Bombs,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Link Checked Between German Blasts, PLO Assassination</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bomb blasts on Monday wrecked
a Jewish community center and a Saudi Arabian airlines office, and
authorities looked into a possible link with the weekend
assassination of a senior PLO leader.
   No one was injured in the early morning blasts in Frankfurt, and
no one claimed responsibility.
   Police said the devices, which went off about 15 minutes apart
within a mile of each other, probably were planted by the same
attackers. Frankfurt prosecutor's spokesman Jochen Schroers said
that ``evidence at both sites is similar.''
   He said a connection with Saturday's slaying of the Palestine
Liberation Organization miliary chief in Tunisia ``is just
speculation at this point.''
   ``But a connection is possible,'' he added. ``Such a political
motive can't be ruled out.''
   Khalil al-Wazir, also known as Abu Jihad, was killed early
Saturday by commandos who stormed his suburban Tunis home. The PLO,
a Tunisian government panel, and Israeli press reports have said
Israel carried out the assassination. Israel has remained silent.
   A leading member of the opposition Social Democratic Party also
discussed the possibility of a link between the slaying and the
Frankfurt blasts in an interview Monday with Saarland state radio.
   However, Hans Koschink said there were no ``clear signs'' of
such a connection.
   The head of West Germany's Jewish Communities, Heinz Galinski,
issued a statement Monday in West Berlin calling on authorities to
tighten security near Jewish property.
   ``It is not understandable for me that even today _ especially
in view of the increasing number of threatening and abusive letters
_ Jewish communities have difficulty when they try to get
sufficient security for their property,'' Galinski said.
   Meanwhile, police looked for a silver-gray BMW car that
witnesses saw before the blast at the Jewish Community Center, a
police spokesman said, requesting anonymity.
   The blast at the center blew off outdoor lighting fixtures,
badly damaged the front entrance, and left a foot-deep hole in the
ground.
   The explosion at the Saudi airlines office gutted the interior
and shattered windows in nearby buildings, including at the Air
Canada office.
   Authorities estimated overall damage at several hundred thousand
dollars.
</TEXT>
