<2ND_LINE>AM-Report At-A-Glance,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Safety Panel Report at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Air Safety Commission Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are highlights from the report by the
President's Commission on Aviation Safety:
   _ The nation's air transportation system is ``safe, for now,''
but the government regulatory structure ``designed to ensure
aviation safety is inadequate to deal with future growth and
technological change.''
   _ There is a need for ``a major structural overhaul'' of the
Federal Aviation Administration, making it an independent agency
outside the Transportation Department.
   _ An independent aviation ``safety czar'' should be appointed as
part of the new FAA and given authority to oversee safety matters.
With a seven-year term, the new aviation safety director could
initiate new safety rules and block proposed regulations.
   _ No need has been demonstrated for re-imposing federal
regulation of the airline industry, although the government must
streamline its regulatory activities to deal with rapidly changing
events in a deregulated industry.
   _ Surveillance of airlines should be improved with heavier
reliance on in-depth inspections, surprise inspections and closer
examination of airlines undergoing major changes.
   _ Safety requirements for commuter airlines should elevated
gradually to the same level as those for larger commercial airlines.
   _ Small private planes flying near major airports should be
required to have equipment that informs ground controllers of their
altitude.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
