<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Runaway     04-18 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Runaway,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen Goes On Spending Spree At Resort</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OCEAN CITY, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager who got a bad report card
took $74,000 from his parents, ran away to this seaside resort and
went on a spending spree in an $800 a day stretch limousine, police
said.
   The 15-year-old runaway had just over $53,000 left when he was
apprehended Saturday evening at a go-cart track in West Ocean City,
police said Monday.
   The boy left his suburban Pittsburgh home Tuesday with $74,000
in a cardboard box, State Police Cpl. Harry Edwards said. His
father was described as a self-employed businessman who often kept
cash at home.
   The teen-ager then hopped a bus to Ocean City and checked into a
motel where rooms cost $32 to $34 a night.
   He quickly made friends, and together they rented a limousine
for two days from Resort Transportation Co. A clerk said the boys
had the driver take them shopping.
   ``They thought they'd get some high fashion,'' said Edwards.
``They bought up a lot of jewelry at stores on the Boardwalk. You
know, necklaces, watches, bracelets. But they had no taste in
jewelry. ... They even had a knock-off Rolex watch. It said Rolex
on the front, and on the back, in ink that rubs off, it said
Taiwan.''
   The boys ate mostly in pizza joints, ``and everywhere they went,
they tipped, they tipped well,'' Edwards said.
   ``He was very nice. ... No one here suspected anything,'' said
motel clerk Vontina Collick.
   The spree came to an end after the boy's parents learned of his
whereabouts and contacted state police. Police also were alerted by
someone who found the teen-ager's spending habits unusual.
   The boy was released to his mother Sunday afternoon.
   Police also arrested Eric Deshawn Faulkner, 20, of Ocean City
and charged him with stealing $2,500 from the runaway, Edwards
said. Police were searching for a third suspect who allegedly took
a handful of money from the box during a party in the motel, police
said.
</TEXT>
