<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Nixon     04-18 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nixon,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nixon Says Dukakis Would Be Smart to Support Reagan in Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Nixon advised Democrat Michael Dukakis
on Monday to back President Reagan on America's retaliatory actions
in the Persian Gulf to dispel any impression that he is weak on
foreign policy.
   He said, also, that the United States should make clear to
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev that ``the Russians are playing
Russian Roulette with the situation there.''
   President Reagan should make it clear to the Soviets, who he
said are playing on both sides in the war between Iran and Iraq,
that ``this is an area we consider absolutely vital and that
eventually they are going to hurt their relations with us unless
they join us in trying to get this war brought to an end,'' Nixon
said.
   Nixon described the conflict as ``not a war that we want either
side to win'' and added: ``There has never been a war in which both
sides deserved to lose more than this war.''
   Incidents in the Persian Gulf have the effect of strengthening
the candidacy of Vice President George Bush, Nixon said, adding
that if he were Dukakis ``I would take a hard line on this.''
   ``When the United States comes under attack and they (the
people) realize our interests are involved, they rally around the
president and his vice president, in this case,'' the former
president said.
   ``I don't think George Bush is going to make a political issue
out of this and that is why I think Dukakis ought ... to join the
president and George Bush in making it clear to the Iranians they
are confronting a united United States on this issue and that we're
not going to be divided.''
   Dukakis said Monday, ``We just don't have sufficient information
for me to comment on what's happened in the Middle East in the last
few days and it would just be inappropriate for me to comment.''
   Nixon's interview, on CNN, was one of a series of appearances he
is making to promote his new book, ``1999.''
   He said Dukakis would be helped by taking a strong line in the
Persian Gulf conflict ``because he opposed the move even into
Grenada.''
   The former president, who has predicted that Republican Bush
will beat Democrat Dukakis by a narrow margin in November, said
that what he called Dukakis' weakness in foreign policy has not
been brought out ``due to the fact that everybody is concentrating
on Jesse Jackson at the moment because of his spectacularly
successful campaign.''
   As he has before, Nixon described Dukakis' foreign policy as
``right out of George McGovern's playbook.''
   ``If people get the idea that you are going to have a president
who is smart, tough, strong _ which he is _ but is weak in the
foreign policy area, it will be devastating to him. I think it will
serve his interest in this case to support the president.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
