<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Cuba     04-18 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Cuba,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuba To Allow Prisoners and Families To Leave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba has given exit permits to 225 former or
current political prisoners and their families, and a portion of
the group is expected to fly to the United States this week, the
State Department said Monday.
   Spokesman Charles Redman said this represents about one-eighth
of the more than 2,000 persons whom the U.S. has authorized for
entry into the United States as refugees.
   Another official, asking not to be identified, said the initial
group is due to arrive in Miami on Wednesday and is expected to
number about 25 persons. The remainder will fly to Miami over the
next several weeks.
   Consistent with past practice, Cuba is likely to send the
emigres in small groups in order to limit opportunities for
propaganda spectacles by exile groups or by the Reagan
administration, the official said.
   Redman said the 225 had been processed for emigration by the
U.S. diplomatic mission in Havana last August from a list drawn up
by the U.S. Catholic Conference. The list was later amended by the
Cuban government, he said.
   Of the 91 in the prisoner category, 22 are long-term inmates who
have refused political rehabilitation.
   The expected departure of the first group of Cubans coincides
with the arrival in Cuba this week of Cardinal John O'Connor, the
archbishop of New York City.
   He is believed to be the highest ranking American Roman Catholic
official to travel to Cuba since the 1959 revolution.
   The U.S. official said there has been speculation but no firm
evidence that the Cuban decision to allow the emigres to leave the
island was linked to O'Connor's visit. He is going to Cuba after a
visit to the Dominican Republic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
