<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PandaPermit     04-18 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panda Permit,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Wildlife Fund Urges Denial Of Michigan Panda Permit
Application</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed exhibition in Michigan of two giant
pandas from China would undermine international laws governing
imports of endangered species, the World Wildlife Fund said Monday
in urging denial of an import permit.
   However, Michigan United Conservation Clubs, an exhibition
sponsor, said the permit may be unnecessary because Chinese
officials have agreed to provide pandas exempt from a treaty
governing endangered-species imports.
   The World Wildlife Fund, a private organization seeking to
preserve wild animals, said in a letter to the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service: ``The imported wildlife will be used for
commercial purposs, and the import will neither serve scientific
purposes nor enhance the propagation or survival of the species.''
   Such use of the pandas would violate both U.S. endangered
species laws and the Convention on International Trade of
Endangered Species, the letter said.
   Evidence of poaching of the rare giant panda in China prompted
the World Wildlife Fund to oppose the Michigan exhibition, said
William Reilly, the organization's president.
   ``Had we known a year ago what we have learned in the past few
months about the plight of the panda and the pressure posed by
exhibition loans, we almost certainly would have opposed most, if
not all, previous short-term loans just as rigorously,'' Reilly
said.
   Reilly said approval of the permit would increase the demand for
the import of giant pandas into the United States for commercial
purposes.
   Tom Washington, MUCC executive director, denied the exhibition
was commercial. ``Certainly, we are not a circus, or a carnival, or
even a zoo, for that matter,'' he said. ``There is a whole string
of hypocricy involved here.''
   MUCC received a letter over the weekend from Sichuan Province's
foreign affairs office providing assurance that ``they will provide
us with a pair of pandas born before 1984,'' Washington said. The
animals would not require an import permit, he said.
   The exhibitors of the pandas in Michigan would pay Chinese
authorities at least $300,000, with the money to be used to build a
panda captive-breeding facility and to improve the animals'
habitat, Washington said.
   The Michigan Department of Natural Resources and MUCC in
February asked the Fish and Wildlife Service to allow the pandas
shown at a 100-day summer exhibition, called Pandarama, at the
Michigan State Fairgrounds in Detroit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
