<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Angola     04-18 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South African General Describes South African Role In Angola</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Breaking a long official
silence, the armed forces chief on Monday gave details of his
troops' role in Angola and said Angola had exaggerated the size of
the South African force operating there.
   Gen. Jannie Geldenhuys, in his first detailed statement on South
Africa's involvement in Angola's civil war, said there had never
been more than 3,000 South African troopers in Angola at any one
time in the past year.
   Angola's Marxist government claims there are 9,000 South African
military personnel fighting alongside rebels of the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola, or UNITA.
   There are an estimated 40,000 Cuban soldiers and hundreds of
Soviet advisers in Angola helping the government forces.
   Geldenhuys announced last November that South African troops had
intervened on behalf of UNITA. Since then, the military has been
widely criticized for providing minimal information about its role
in the war.
   The general's statement Monday indicated the intervention began
in May 1987, since the losses he announced were for a period
beginning then.
   In the months since, Geldenhuys said, 31 South African soldiers
have been killed and three tanks, four other combat vehicles and
two aircraft have been lost.
   The casualty figures did not include black units composed of
South-West Africans and Angolan exiles. There have been unofficial
reports that those units have suffered higher losses than white
South African units.
   Geldenhuys did not give casualty figures for the UNITA rebels.
He said Angolan government losses for the past year totaled 4,768
men, but it was not clear if the losses referred to the number
killed or both killed and wounded.
   The general repeated a statement he made in December that South
African forces were in the process of withdrawing. He declined to
report a timetable, saying such information could aid the enemy.
   He said the South African troops had captured certain weapons
``unknown to the Western world'' and several countries were seeking
access to them. He did not elaborate.
   Angola's foreign minister, Alfredo Van Dunem, said Friday more
than 6,000 South African soldiers were preparing for a renewed
attack against the strategic southern town of Cuito Cuanavale.
   He said the troops beseiging the garrison town were part of a
South African force of 9,000 soldiers, 600 artillery pieces and 500
tanks and armored cars in Angola.
   Cuito Cuanavale has been under attack for four months by UNITA
rebels and South African troops.
   The town is 190 miles north of the border with South
African-ruled South-West Africa, also known as Namibia. It has an
airstrip and is used as a staging base for army operations against
UNITA guerrillas.
   UNITA lost to the Marxist Popular Liberation Movement of Angola
in a battle for power after Angola received its independence from
Portugal in November 1975.
   UNITA, which is suported by the United States, is demanding the
Marxists share power.
   The government has rejected negotiations with the rebels. It has
said it would agree to a gradual withdrawal of the Cuban troops if
South Africa removed its forces and halted aid to UNITA.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880418-0188 </DOCNO>
