<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Gulf-Glance     04-18 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Glance,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The U.S.-Iran Clash At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are Monday's developments in the Persian Gulf:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MANAMA, Bahrain _ American forces destroyed two of Iran's
Persian Gulf oil platforms, sank or damaged four attack boats and
disabled two frigates that fired missiles at American planes. Iran
responded with attacks on Arab oil facilities; U.S., British and
Cypriot commercial vessels, and a press helicopter chartered by NBC.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ No American casualties were reported, but Defense
Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said a Cobra attack helicopter with two
crewmen was late in returning to a Navy cruiser and a search had
begun.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   UNITED NATIONS _ U.S. Ambassador Herber Okun briefed members of
the Security Council on the military action and said the council
should impose an arms embargo on Iran.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   NICOSIA, Cyprus _ Iran said Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati
wrote a protest letter to U.S. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar that said, in part: ``Iran will never submit to the policy
of violence and intimidation, and will definitely respond to the
cowardly U.S. attacks.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ Washington said destruction of the oil platforms
was a ``measured response'' to the explosion of a mine, allegedly
planted by Iran, that damaged an American frigate last week and
wounded 10 sailors. President Reagan said: ``We will protect our
ships and, if they threaten us, they'll pay a price. We undertook
this action to make sure the Iranians have no illusions about the
cost of irresponsible behavior.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MANAMA _ In the ground war between Iran and Iraq, the Iraqis
claimed to have regained most of the southern Faw peninsula Iranian
forces captured more than two years ago, including the town of Faw.
Iran said U.S. helicopter gunships fired at Iranian troops and
``American forces have entered the war,'' but the United States
denied it.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional leaders supported Reagan's decision
to retaliate against Iran, and applauded him for consulting them in
advance.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   NEW YORK _ Oil prices rose. Contracts for May delivery of West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, closed at $18.52 per
42-gallon barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange, up 15 cents
from Friday.
</TEXT>
