<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 2022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NoriegaDeal     04-18 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Noriega Deal,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Venezuelan President Tells of Past Agreement for Noriega to
Quit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLAUDE E. ERBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega had
signed an agreement to leave power voluntarily in May, it was
disclosed Monday, but the deal fell through when Panama's president
tried to fire the general in February.
   The report came from former Venezuelan President Carlos Andres
Perez, who said he negotiated the deal with Noriega together with
former presidents Alfonso Lopez Michelsen of Colombia and Daniel
Oduber of Costa Rica.
   Perez said in an interview the U.S. government was aware of his
group's negotiations with Noriega, which took place in Panama last
November and in January and February of this year.
   The deal was signed Feb. 24, three weeks after Noriega was
indicted on drug charges in Miami and one day before Panama's
then-President Eric Arturo Delvalle announced he was firing him.
Instead, Noriega engineered Delvalle's removal from the presidency.
   The former Venezuelan president said negotiations with Noriega
had been undertaken ``to help lead Panama back toward democracy,''
and had the support of the United States and Spain.
   He said Spain's Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez knew of the
initiative and indicated Noriega could come to Spain after leaving
Panama.
   The deal with Noriega envisioned his resignation from command of
the National Guard, Panama's politically powerful army, and his
replacment ``by an officer removed from politics, whose mission
would be the preservation of public order under civilian control.''
Concurrently, steps would be taken to prepare for free elections
and to restore full freedom of expression.
   Perez said Noriega's departure from Panama was not part of the
deal, but ``would have been a natural outgrowth of the process.
Once he was out of the guard, it was inevitable that he would have
to leave the country.''
   ``Initially,'' Perez said, ``we were told by the United States
that Noriega could come here (to the United States). We had no idea
that a criminal investigation and indictment were in the works.''
   Perez, who has been meeting with bankers and business leaders in
the United States, is a candidate for the presidency of Venezuela
in elections to be held in November. He served as president from
1974 to 1979.
   Perez said ``news of Noriega's removal came as a complete
surprise to us,'' and ``apparently followed'' a meeting between
Delvalle and the U.S. assistant secretary of state for
inter-American affairs, Elliott Abrams. He said the move came just
as he and his fellow negotiators were preparing to report the
signing of the agreement with Noriega to Secretary of State George
P. Shultz.
   Perez said the agreement had been intended to remain
confidential, but the need for secrecy disappeared once the
circumstances in Panama changed. He said he mentioned its existence
in a statement issued in Caracas in February, but it gained little
attention at the time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880418-0191 </DOCNO>
