<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalBriefs     04-18 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Briefs,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Western Chairmen Meet With Reagan, Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Party chairmen from 18 Western
states met with Vice President George Bush on Monday to urge him to
select a Westerner as his running mate.
   The chairmen met with Bush over breakfast and with President
Reagan during lunch to discuss GOP politics in the West.
   T. J. Baily, Oregon GOP chairman, said he and others told Bush
he could strengthen his ticket in the West if he picked a Western
vice presidential candidate.
   ``Bush said he did not have a short list or a long list of
possible running mates,'' said Baily, adding that Bush indicated it
may be difficult to select a running mate on a regional basis only.
   Baily said that although Reagan and other GOP presidential
candidates have done well in the West in recent elections, ``we
can't take anything for granted. The West could be the difference
in winning this time.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Late-Night NY Primary Coverage Planned at Networks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The major networks plan late-night wrap-ups on
the New York state primary Tuesday night, the networks said Monday.
   At CBS, Dan Rather will anchor an 11:30 p.m. half-hour report on
the race between Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore, Jesse Jackson and
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, said spokeswoman Donna Dees.
   Tom Brokaw will handle the anchor chores at the same time on NBC
for its 30 minute wrap-up, said network spokesman Bill McAndrew. In
addition, McAndrew said, Brokaw will provide network updates on the
race in prime time ``as developments warrant.''
   ABC's ``Nightline,'' anchored by Ted Koppel, will present an
expanded primary special which will run longer than the program's
usual 30 minutes, said network spokeswoman Elise Adde.
</TEXT>
