<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Tongass 2ndLd-Writethru a0751 04-18 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tongass, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0751,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Should Repeal Law Requiring Timber Production, GAO Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 4th graf pvs, bgng: ``The Tongass ...'' to identify
Idaho forest.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress should repeal the money-losing law
that requires the U.S. Forest Service to market a minimum supply of
timber from Tongass National Forest in Alaska, the General
Accounting Office said Monday.
   GAO, the investigative wing of Congress, said the requirement
contributed to a net loss by taxpayers of about $22.1 million in
1986 in sales of commercial timber from the Tongass, the nation's
largest national forest.
   A 1980 law requires that the Forest Service offer to sell at
least 4.5 billion board feet of Tongass timber each decade and
guarantees at least $40 million in spending a year to support the
sales program.
   The Tongass is the only national forest with a minimum sales
goal set by law, although Sen. James McClure, R-Idaho, has proposed
a similar guarantee for the Panhandle National Forest in his state.
   Last month, the House Interior Committee approved legislation to
repeal the guaranteed minimum sales offerings from the Tongass. A
similar bill is pending in the Senate Energy and Natural Resources
Committee.
   The proposals are being pushed by environmental and conservation
groups who say the guarantee leads to unnecessary roadbuilding by
the Forest Service and needless harvesting of 400-year-old trees.
   The GAO study, requested by Sens. William Proxmire, D-Wis., and
Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, said that sales offerings of timber from the
forest should be subject to market supply-and-demand forces.
   GAO said that from 1981 through 1986, the last year for which
data were available, sales of Tongass timber averaged 245 million
board feet a year, some 105 million below the yearly average needed
to meet the 10-year goal.
   Focusing on 1986, GAO said the Forest Service spent $47.9
million on the Tongass and realized only $3.3 million in revenues.
The net loss to taxpayers was $22.1 million because some spending
was for timber production in future years, according to the study.
   From 1981 through 1986, the Forest Service spent $131 million to
prepare for timber sales that were not needed to meet demand, the
study said.
   GAO said that because of the guarantee ``the Forest Service has
incurred substantial expenses to prepare and offer timber it could
not sell under depressed market conditions and made added
investments in timber not needed to meet this demand. ...
   ``We think clarifications and fundamental changes are
necessary,'' said GAO, noting that demand for Tongass timber has
not met the projections made when the 1980 law was enacted.
   ``The timber supply provision should be revised so that the
amount supplied would be based on the anticipated demand for timber
and on the data currently being formulated by the Forest Service
... rather than on a rigid per-decade requirement,'' the study said.
   One reason given by advocates of the guarantee was to ensure
employment in Southeast Alaska following passage of the 1980 law,
which barred commercial activities in about one-third of the 16.8
million acre Tongass.
   GAO said Tongass-related timber jobs declined from 2,700 in 1980
to 1,420 in 1986 ``primarily because of the decreased harvest
levels resulting from declining demand for timber and increased
production by the Alaska native corporations that directly compete
with the Tongass timber industry.''
   The Forest Service chief, F. Dale Robertson, said in a letter to
GAO that the proposal to scrap the Tongass guarantee ``has merit.''
   Stevens said in a prepared statement that the GAO focused on a
low-demand portion of an economic cycle and that timber has since
rebounded. He said money must be spent on the Tongass even in low
periods in order to meet peak demand.
   He also noted that the guaranteed timber offerings were part of
the 1980 compromise with conservation groups that set aside 5.4
million acres of the forest as protected wilderness.
</TEXT>
