<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Meese-GrandJury 1stLd-Writethru a0747 04-18 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Grand Jury, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0747,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Appears Before Grand Jury For Fifth Time</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs 3rd graf bgng: One of ... to UPDATE with comment from
Meese lawyers</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III appeared for
four hours before a federal grand jury Monday in the criminal
investigation of his activities that began nearly a year ago.
   It was his fifth grand jury appearance in the probe by
independent counsel James McKay since coming under criminal
investigation last May 11.
   Meese's attorneys, Nathan Lewin and James Rocap, said in a
statement that the attorney general ``answered all questions'' and
they said they remain confident that Meese won't be indicted and
that the probe will be completed ``in the near future.''
   McKay has been delving into a $40,000-a-year job for Meese's
wife, Meese's involvement with a $1-billion Iraqi oil pipeline, the
attorney general's ownership of $14,000 in regional Bell Telephone
stock and Meese's ties to scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp.
   The attorney general's most recent grand jury appearance in the
McKay probe was last Nov. 4, when prosecutors from McKay's office
were focusing on the Wedtech matter.
   Last Thursday, two members of the family that arranged to pay
the salary of Meese's wife were questioned in front of the grand
jury.
   The Bender family arranged to pay the salary of Ursula Meese
while leasing office space to the Justice Department.
   The Associated Press reported last Wednesday that a partnership
headed by Howard M. Bender won a $50-million lease on Justice
Department offices after the Bender Foundation had put up money to
pay Mrs. Meese's salary at the Multiple Sclerosis Society.
   Mrs. Meese is to be questioned by McKay's office later this
month in connection with the job.
   Longtime Meese friend E. Robert Wallach, who is under indictment
in the Wedtech scandal, had a role in helping arrange the job for
Mrs. Meese, Wallach's attorney has told The Washington Post.
   McKay said 2{ weeks ago that he had insufficient evidence to
seek an indictment of Meese in connection with the oil pipeline or
the telephone stock but that his investigation would continue at
least through the end of April.
   In connection with the oil pipeline project, Meese referred
Wallach to then-national security adviser Robert McFarlane in May
1985. The referral led to a meeting the next month involving
McFarlane, Wallach and Wallach's client, Swiss oilman Bruce
Rappaport, a partner in the pipeline project.
   Rappaport paid a $150,000 legal fee to Wallach, who deposited it
in a stock trading account owned by Meese's financial manager, W.
Franklyn Chinn. Chinn in effect pooled Wallach's money with that of
Meese and other customers to help generate $40,000 in stock trading
profits on a $50,000 investment in just 18 months. Wallach
introduced Meese to Chinn.
   McKay also has been investigating Meese's holdings of telephone
stock in 1985 and 1986 when Meese met with executives of four of
the seven regional Bell companies.
   The phone companies wanted the Justice Department to reverse its
position and to recommend that the so-called Baby Bells be
permitted to enter several new types of business. A year after his
meetings with the Bell executives, Meese approved the
recommendation reversing earlier department policy.
   Meese listed his telephone stock as having been sold on federal
financial disclosure forms for 1985 and 1986, but the attorney
general actually had transferred the holdings to Chinn. Meese
regained possession of the stock and sold it last September.
   McKay also has been examining Meese's efforts on behalf of
Wedtech. At Wallach's behest, then White House counselor Meese
intervened on behalf of the Bronx, N.Y., defense contractor,
directing his White House staff to ensure that the company got a
fair hearing from the Army in connection with a $32 million engine
contract.
</TEXT>
