<1ST_LINE>u w AM-GulfOptions     04-18 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Options,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Once Iran Linked With Mining, Military Response Was Chosen Quickly</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Gulf Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration quickly decided last
week that if it could find evidence Iran planted the mine that
almost sank a Navy frigate, it would use military force to
retaliate, officials said Monday.
   Top aides to President Reagan also recommended, however, the
retaliation be ``proportionate'' and not involve any direct action
against Iranian installations on land, the officials said.
   The result was a simultaneous attack Monday morning on two
Iranian offshore platforms.
   ``The frame of reference was pretty well established from the
very beginning,'' said one of the officials, who like the others
agreed to discuss the matter only if not identified.
   ``We knew something had to be done, but there were not a lot of
options considered.''
   ``We had hit some of their offshore platforms before, and that
was pretty much the only thing we considered this time,'' another
source said.
   ``We're walking a line here of trying to protect freedom of
navigation in international waters. These platforms have been used
to support attacks on commercial shipping. We also need
congressional support and international support. We're not trying
to directly immerse ourselves in the Iran-Iraq war.''
   The latest confrontation with Iran began last Thursday when the
frigate Samuel B. Roberts struck an underwater mine in the central
gulf just hours after successfully shepherding an oil tanker to
Kuwait. Ten sailors were injured, although the crew managed to save
the ship.
   By the time Reagan met with his top security aides on Friday,
``it had been established conclusively that this was an Iranian
mine and that it had been deliberately planted and was not a
drifter,'' one source said.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said Monday there was ``no
doubt'' the mine had been sown by Iran. Citing a match of serial
numbers on the explosives with earlier captured mines, he added:
``It is very clear that they are new mines of Iranian manufacture.''
   Reagan, after another briefing Sunday night, gave the final
go-ahead for the retaliatory mission.
   Then, much to the surprise of top Pentagon officials, the
Iranians decided to confront U.S. forces directly in different
parts of the gulf rather than simply abandon the platforms. Two
Iranian frigates were disabled and one large patrol boat and three
smaller ones sunk or crippled by American forces in a day of
fighting.
   Carlucci suggested at one point Monday the confrontations
stemmed from Iranian fanaticism, adding the United States acted
only in self-defense when it attacked the various Iranian ships.
   ``We hope Iran will now realize the futility of its attempts to
interfere with peaceful international shipping in the Persian
Gulf,'' Carlucci added.
   ``We do not seek a confrontation with Iran, but we do intend to
continue our efforts to ensure freedom of navigation in the gulf.
And should the Iranians resume their attacks, our ships are
prepared to defend themselves just as they did today.''
</TEXT>
