<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PLOKilling     04-18 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO Killing,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tunisia Says Israeli Commandos Killed PLO Military Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOUBAKER GHARIANI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli commandos operating with air
support assassinated PLO military chief Khalil al-Wazir, Tunisian
investigators concluded in a report released Monday.
   President Zine el Abidine Ben Ali condemned the ``flagrant,
premeditated aggression against Tunisian sovereignty'' and said his
government would file a complaint with the the U.N. Security
Council.
   Al-Wazir, 52, also known as Abu Jihad (Father of the Holy War),
was killed by seven commandos who burst into his home in a Tunis
suburb early Saturday. He was chief aide to Yasser Arafat, chairman
of the Palestine Liberation Organization, and was the PLO military
commander.
   The body is to be flown to Damascus, Syria, on Tuesday for
burial.
   Arafat blamed Israel's Mossad secret service immediately after
the assassination. News of the killing cause the worst violence in
the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip since riots began
Dec. 8, with 17 Palestinians reported killed Saturday.
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman condemned the
killing of al-Wazir. ``Violence is not the solution to the problems
of the Middle East,'' he said in Washington.
   Tunisian government investigators said they established Israeli
responsibility for ``this cowardly terrorist act which it (Israel)
planned and executed.''
   Their report said an Israeli military Boeing 707, registry
number 4X977, was about 35 miles outside Tunisian air space at the
moment of the attack.
   It jammed communications in Sidi Bou Said, the northern suburb
where al-Wazir lived, the report said. The plane was flying ``in
the international air corridor in a way so as not to expose itself
to Tunisian air forces,'' the investigators said.
   ``The terrorist group which assassinated the Palestinian leader
had sophisticated technological support which put this operation
beyond the framework of normal terrorists and into the kind of
terrorism that only states are in a position to practice,'' the
report declared.
   In October 1985, the Israeli air force raided the PLO
headquarters, killing about 80 Palestinians and 20 Tunisians and
wounding 100 people. Arafat was not there.
   Israeli leaders have said nothing about responsibility for the
killing, but Israeli sources said Monday it was the work of Mossad,
the navy and an elite commando unit.
   Arafat moved his headquarters to Tunis after the 1982 Israeli
invasion drove the PLO out of Lebanon.
</TEXT>
