<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CyanideDeaths     04-18 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cyanide Deaths,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Daughter May Testify Against Mother Charged In Drug Tampering Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The daughter of the first person in the nation
charged with causing death by tampering with over-the-counter drug
capsules is prepared to testify for the prosecution, government
lawyers said Monday.
   The revelation was contained in a pretrial brief filed by
Assistant U.S. Attorney Joanne Maida as jury selection began in the
trial of Stella Nickell, 44, in U.S. District Court.
   She is charged with two counts of causing a death by product
tampering and three of tampering with a product involved in
interstate commerce. Maximum penalties are life in prison on each
of the first two charges and 10 years on each of the other three,
which stem from the discovery of unsold bottles containing
cyanide-laced capsules on store shelves.
   Mrs. Nickell's husband, Bruce, 52, and Susan Katherine Snow, 40,
both of Auburn, died in June 1986 after ingesting tainted capsules
of Extra-Strength Excedrin. Authorities have not suggested any
other links between the victims.
   The deaths set off a nationwide tampering scare and prompted
Excedrin manufacturer Bristol-Myers to recall its capsuled
non-prescription medicine.
   That December, Mrs. Nickell ``called her daughter, Cindy
Hamilton, and informed her that the FBI had claimed that she had
failed'' a lie-detector test, Ms. Maida's brief said.
   ``After learning this from her mother, Cindy Hamilton came
forward in January 1987 with information, previously unknown to the
authorities, that Stella Nickell had been planning the death of her
husband, Bruce, for several years,'' the brief said.
   The document said Ms. Hamilton, about whom no further
information was given, also told investigators her mother never
specifically mentioned Bruce Nickell as a target but had done
library research on how someone might be killed.
   Investigators found Mrs. Nickell's fingerprints on pages of the
book ``Deadly Harvest'' that cover cyanide poisoning, previously
filed court documents showed.
   She has been held without bail since her indictment in December.
   Judge William L. Dwyer and attorneys for both sides expect the
trial to last three weeks.
</TEXT>
