<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 2014EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Reax     04-18 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Reax,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Backs U.S. Attack On Iran, Soviet Warns Of Escalation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain said the U.S. attack on Iranian oil platforms Monday was
``entirely justified'' but the Soviet Union said it could prompt
more fighting in the Persian Gulf.
   Western European nations Monday suspended their mine-clearing
operations in the gulf because of the destruction of the two oil
platforms, a Dutch official said.
   U.S. forces also sank or damaged four Iranian attack boats and
bombed two Iranian naval frigates after they fired on American
planes.
   American officials said the platform raids were in retaliation
for a mine explosion Thursday that damaged an American frigate and
wounded 10 sailors.
   Iran has denied laying the mine.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain told reporters she
was ``satisfied from the evidence we have that the mines were laid
by Iran and that the U.S. reaction was entirely justified as a
proportionate response.''
   Foreign Office Minister David Mellor told the House of Commons
that the U.S. attack was ``a measured and proportionate response''
to renewed mine-laying in the gulf by Iran.
   Egyptian officials in Cairo also supported the American actions.
   ``We understand the American response and we urge Iran to stop
its policy of provoking others,'' Foreign Minister Esmat
Abdel-Meguid said in a statement.
   In the Soviet Union, a television commentator said President
Reagan ordered the attack ``under pressure from the extreme
right,'' and because he ``wanted to show American society and the
whole world that he is acting from a position of strength.''
   ``This is a road to nowhere,'' said commentator Farid
Seiful-Mulyukov on the nightly news program Vremya.
   The official news agency Tass said the raids brought tension in
the Persian Gulf to a ``critical level'' once again.
   Iran's foreign minister, Ali Akbar Velayati, protested the raid
to the United Nations and threatened retaliation, Iran's official
Islamic Republic News Agency said in dispatches monitored in
Nicosia, Cyprus.
   In Athens, Greek officials said the American attack did not
contribute to a ``de-escalation of tension prevailing in the
region, but on the contrary could dangerously escalate the conflict
between Iran and Iraq.''
   The U.S.-Iranian confrontation was a subject of discussion at a
meeting of the Western European Union in The Hague. The group is a
defense forum comprised of the Netherlands, Britain, Belgium,
France, West Germany, Italy and Luxembourg.
   The British were expected to use the meeting to seek a statement
in support of the U.S. raid.
   Early Monday, the U.S. government told the flotilla of Belgian,
Dutch, Italian and British mine-clearing vessels in the gulf of its
plans to attack.
   Dutch Defense Minister Willem van Eekelen said the ships
immediately suspended operations.
   The mine-clearing vessels ``are awaiting new instructions,'' Van
Eekelen said. He added that there were no plans to order the ships
out of the gulf.
   In retaliation for Monday's U.S. raid, Iran attacked the
British-flagged York Marine, several other vessels and oil
facilities.
   British Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe, in the Netherlands
for the Western European Union meeting, said he was ``absolutely
outraged that there should be an attack on a defenseless
British-flagged vessel.''
</TEXT>
