<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1911EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Demjanjuk-Courtroom     04-18 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Demjanjuk-Courtroom,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spectators Applaud Verdict; Demjanjuk Family Walks Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Demjanjuk, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spectators burst into applause when John
Demjanjuk was convicted of war crimes Monday, but his family walked
out halfway through the 12-hour reading of the verdict. He heard it
in a cell, lying on a cot with back pains.
   An assistant prosecutor said a survivor of the Treblinka death
camp in Nazi-occupied Poland, Eliyahu Rosenberg, beamed after the
verdict, hugged him and said: ``I feel better now.''
   Rosenberg was one of five survivors who identified Demjanjuk,
68, as the brutal death camp guard ``Ivan the Terrible,'' who
terrorized prisoners and ran the gas chambers at Treblinka.
   Demjanjuk listened to the reading of the 450-page judgement from
a cot in a courthouse holding cell, where he was taken after
complaining of back pains.
   When the court session opened, guards carried him feet-first
across the courtroom stage into the cell after he began weeping and
refused to leave the police van. The trial was conducted in a
converted movie theater.
   Two other Holocaust survivors who testified against Demjanjuk
were among more than 600 spectators.
   At one point, survivor Pinchas Epstein was helped from the
courtroom in tears after judges quoting from his testimony said
Ivan ``would gloat at the crushed faces, the blood flowing after he
brutalized people.''
   Six hours into the opinion, Demjanjuk's wife Vera, daughter
Lydia, son John Jr. and son-in-law Ed Nishnic walked out of the
courtroom in protest.
   ``We just couldn't sit there any longer and listen to that
garbage,'' said Nishnic, who raised $650,000 for the defense.
   John Jr., 22, said: ``It's a disgrace to the word justice. These
are old-fashioned hanging judges. As far as I'm concerned, this was
nothing more than a Soviet show trial. Whenever one of our
witnesses came on, they got the hammer.''
   Nishnic said: ``This is going to go down in history as the most
lopsided case ever conducted anywhere in the world.''
   Defense lawyer John Gill contended that the three-judge court
automatically rejected defense arguments.
   ``My God in heaven, according to the judges we didn't do
anything right,'' he said. ``They ruled against us on every single
point.''
   Mrs. Demjanjuk, 62, was seen crying and wringing her hands
during a lunch break. ``I can't sit down. I can't sit down,'' she
said.
   Although the courtroom remained full through the often tedious
reading, many spectators fell asleep, read newspapers or slipped
outside for a smoke or snack.
   Dov Levine, the presiding judge, quoted twice from the Bible. In
one instance, he said Samuel 18:26 supported the contention of a
Treblinka survivor who said he recognized Demjanjuk by the way he
walked.
   ``In the Bible we find references to identifying an individual
by his gait,'' Levine said.
   After the reading, Demjanjuk walked slowly to a police van
supported by two policemen and surrounded by 16 other guards. He
looked somber, his head was bowed and his hands were clasped.
   When reporters hidden from view behind a 6-foot-high screen
asked how he felt after the verdict, he looked up and appeared
surprised.
   ``I'm very good!'' he shouted. ``I'm an innocent man! I will
appeal and I'm sure I will win!''
   As police hustled him toward the van, he added: ``This is
ridiculous what happened hayom,'' using the Hebrew word for
``today.''
</TEXT>
