<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 2051EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MarathonNewspage     04-18 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marathon Newspage,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hussein Wins Closest Boston Marathon Ever</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kenya's Ibrahim Hussein won the Boston Marathon by
one second Monday, becoming the first African champion of the
world's oldest marathon. Portugal's Rosa Mota won the women's
division for the second straight year.
   The one-second margin made it the closest finish the 92-year-old
race has ever had.
   Hussein and Juma Ikangaa of Tanzania ran shoulder-to-shoulder
from about the 22-mile point until the closing strides of the
26-mile, 385-yard course.
   With Ikangaa a step in front with about 100 yards to go, Hussein
burst past and beat him to the finish line. His winning time was 2
hours, 8 minutes, 43 seconds, the second-fastest time for the
Boston Marathon. Australian Rob de Castella's 1986 performance in
2:07:51 holds the record.
   Hussein's one-second victory eclipsed two previous two-second
margins to become the closest Boston Marathon ever. Ireland's John
Treacy, 1984 Olympic silver medalist, finished third in 2:09:15.
   Mota, 1984 Olympic bronze medalist, took the women's title with
a time of 2:24:30. Tuija Jousimaa, of Finland, was the second
woman's finisher in 2:29:26, with Canada's Odette LaPierre third in
2:30:35.
   Hussein and Mota each won $45,000 plus a car valued at more than
$35,000 for their victories.
   More than 6,700 runners participated in the race under rainy
skies.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
