<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Politics     04-18 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Politics,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Saves Tax Legislation Despite Intra-Party Revolt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government
saved its tax legislation Monday despite a revolt in the ranks that
cut her usual huge majority in the House of Commons to 25.
   After noisy debate, a 320-295 vote defeated an amendment by
Conservative Party rebels to the government bill on property taxes,
which critics say is unfair to the poor.
   It was one of the government's worst days in Parliament, where
the Conservatives have a majority of 101 seats, since Mrs. Thatcher
took office nine years ago.
   Rebellious rank-and-file Conservative members rallied behind
Michael Mates and voted for his amendment, which would have tied
the tax to a person's ability to pay rather than assessing a flat
rate regardless of income.
   Neil Kinnock, leader of the opposition socialist Labor Party,
was jubilant about the Tory rebellion and declared in the Commons:
``The flagship is badly holed and sinking fast!''
   During the often rowdy session, Mates denied he was challenging
Mrs. Thatcher.
   ``We are debating principles, not personalities,'' he said in a
43-minute speech punctuated by heckling from his own party. ``I
don't find this a comfortable position, to be standing here
offering criticism of the government.''
   At issue was a clause of the Local Government Finance Bill
levying property taxes on each adult in a household instead of on
the house or apartment in which they live, as the case is now.
   Last week, Tory revolts cut government majorities to 74 and 81
in votes on the introduction of charges for dental and eye checkups
under the National Health Service.
   Those charges, which follow a shakeup in the system of welfare
payments, are part of of the third-term program Mrs. Thatcher says
is designed to end the ``dependency culture.''
   Conservatives to the political left of the prime minister say
the program feeds the belief that her government is right-wing and
uncaring.
   In addition to charges for some health services, the tax
legislation reduces the top rate on income from 60 percent to 40.
   The government says the new property tax system, to take effect
in 1990, will be fairer, spreading the liability to 35 million
people from the current 18 million heads of households.
</TEXT>
