<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FourSlain     04-18 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Four Slain,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 1,200 Attend Services for Slain Siblings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,200 mourners paid their
last respects Monday to four siblings brutally slain in a mobile
home, killings one family member blamed on a convoluted judicial
system.
   Jennifer Mann, 19, her sisters Shannon, 17, and Martha, 15, and
brother Ernest, 11, were buried Monday after a memorial service at
Mission Park South funeral home.
   An assailant broke into their mobile home early Friday and
attacked them with steak knives, some broken by the force of the
blows. The girls were sexually mutilated, officials said.
   The girl's parents, Ernest and Becky Mann, who are separated,
were not home during the attack.
   Shannon Mann's former boyfriend, Leo Narvaiz Jr., 20, was
arrested shortly after the attack and charged with four counts of
murder. He remained in the Bexar County Jail in lieu of $4.05
million bond.
   Grady Mann Jr., an uncle of the victims, blamed authorities for
the deaths because Narvaiz was not arrested quickly enough for an
earlier threat.
   ``We feel the Mann children were victims of a system that has
lost the meaning of a basic principle that our founding fathers
felt was foremost _ the right to life, liberty and the pursuit of
happiness,'' Mann said outside the funeral home.
   ``For the Mann children, these rights are gone forever.''
   At the time of the killings, police had been looking for Narvaiz
because of a complaint filed by Ricky Moore, 24, who was dating
Shannon Mann. Moore alleged that Narvaiz had damaged his pickup
truck and threatened him with a knife on March 28.
   Moore criticized police for not arresting Narvaiz sooner, but
officials blamed a clogged justice system for the delay.
   Police have said Narvaiz is the sole suspect in the slayings,
but they are analyzing the tape of a frenzied call one of the girls
made to a 911 emergency exchange for further clues.
   ``It is our hope this tragedy might serve as a catalyst for all
of us nationally to personally protest the system that has
evolved,'' Grady Mann said.
   ``The system protects and shelters the rights of the few and in
so doing neglects the needs of the many,'' he said. ``The time for
change is now, lest another family need go through the agony and
torture of loss, whether one or many.''
   After Monday's five-minute graveside service, the victims'
father rose and screamed, ``I want my boy. I want my boy.''
   Earlier, mourners filed past four identical, gray caskets
bearing the victims' snapshots in the funeral home. The coffins
were surrounded by hundreds of roses. Pink carnations were placed
on top of the girls' coffins and blue carnations on the boy's.
   Friends of the Manns have set up two funds to help defray the
family's funeral costs, which are expected to total more than
$10,000.
</TEXT>
