<1ST_LINE>r i AM-KenyaMassacre     04-18 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya Massacre,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survivor tells of Massacre of 192 Villagers by Cattle Rustlers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mojong Lorika wept Monday as he described
how his 2-year-old son was killed by cattle rustlers who massacred
192 Kenyan villagers, the Kenya News Agency reported Monday.
   The agency said that in an interview, Lorika said that when
raiders burst into his home at 5 a.m. last Wednesday he ``grabbed
his son and took cover in a corner.'' But the rustlers opened fire
and a bullet struck the child in the head, killing him instantly.
   Laban Kitele, a minister of state, said police tracked the gang
of 50 rustlers from the raided village, 30 miles west of the border
town of Lokichoggio, and killed 40 in a gunbattle. He said the
other rustlers escaped across the border into Sudan. He mentioned
no police casualties.
   Kitele, in a statement Sunday, also said the police recovered
3,000 of about 3,500 cattle, sheep, goats and donkeys that had been
seized by the rustlers.
   He described the rustlers as a ``terror gang'' of Sudanese from
the Toposas tribe and Ndongiros from Ethiopia and said they were
armed with automatic rifles and machetes.
   There are several nomadic tribes in East Africa that believe all
animals were given to them by God and it is their right and duty to
win them back.
   The state-run news agency's correspondent interviewed Lorika at
the Lodwar district hospital where 19 of 50 wounded survivors were
being treated.
   The news agency quoted medical health officer John Adongosi as
saying eight of the patients were in critical condition from bullet
wounds and machete gashes. It said six severely wounded victims
were flown to Nairobi for surgery.
   Wednesday's massacre occured in the remote Turkana district in
northwestern Kenya. Heavy rains in the mountainous region made
roads to the raided village impassable and turned a nearby dirt
airstrip into a muddy bog.
   The Sunday Nation, an independent newspaper, reported the sky
over the ravaged village was black with vultures.
   Kitele's statement also referred to a March 30 attack by
rustlers on a camp of nomads in northern Kenya, during which they
hacked to death 15 people and fled with some 2,000 goats.
   ``Rustlers have lost all respect for human life to the extent
that they will massacre human beings in cold blood,'' Kitele said.
``I wish to warn anybody within Kenya or outside still harboring
ideas of rustling to desist .... Government response to rustling
will always be prompt and aggressive hot pursuit.''
   Nomads regularly cross the borders in East Africa in search of
pasture for their animals.
   The Daily Nation, also an independent newspaper, called Monday
for the East African nations to establish a joint organization to
wage war on stock thieves.
   ``It is easy for raiders to pounce on a village on this side,
kill people and take livestock before vanishing to the other side,
where international law forbids our forces from following them,''
the paper said.
   Mohamed Yusuf Haji, a provincial commissioner, managed to visit
the massacre site and he told The Sunday Nation he found only bones
and skulls left by vultures and scavenging animals.
</TEXT>
