<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0727,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Urges Backers To Turn Out In Force For N.Y. Primary</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Jackson comment on death
threats; picks up 2nd graf pvs, Standing in, DELETES grafs 7 and
10-11 pvs, which outdated</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said Monday that the atmosphere in
the New York primary campaign has been ``so divisive and so
violent'' that he has received more death threats than at any other
time in the 1988 presidential campaign.
   In response to questions about the attacks on him by Mayor
Edward Koch, Jackson said, ``The name-calling and the accusations
and the attempts of a provocation by the mayor have not been good
for the city or the campaign.''
   Koch has kept up a drumbeat of attacks on Jackson.
   Early in the campaign, the mayor said that Jews and other
supporters of Israel would ``have to be crazy'' to vote for Jackson.
   In a television interview on Sunday, the mayor said Jackson has
lied when he had claimed to be the last person Martin Luther King
Jr. spoke to before he died after being shot in Memphis and again
when he denied he had ever used the terms ``Hymie'' and
``Hymietown.'' The terms are considered offensive to Jews and
Jackson later apologized for using them.
   ``We have received more death threats in this campaign than in
all the other combined because the climate has been so divisive and
so violent,'' Jackson told a news conference.
   Jackson customarily receives far more death threats than any of
the other candidates, and travels with heavy Secret Service and
other protection.
   Later, he exhorted his supporters to turn out in force for the
New York primary and give him an upset victory that could scramble
the odds in the race for the Democratic presidential nomination.
   Standing in the rain at a get-out-the-vote rally in East Harlem,
Jackson said, ``If you will stand in the rain today, you will vote
in the rain tomorrow. ... We've come too close. Nothing can stop us
now.''
   Recent polls said Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis was getting
the most support among likely Democratic voters with Jackson
running a strong second. Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee was a
distant third.
   Turnout was the big unknown in efforts to predict the outcome on
Tuesday and Jackson spent the last full day of campaigning trying
to keep enthusiasm high among his strongest supporters.
   He scheduled three rallies in different parts of Harlem where
black and Hispanic voters turned out in large numbers to support
him in the 1984 New York presidential primary, and a fourth in
Chinatown.
   ``The race is getting closer and turnout is the key,'' said New
York pollster Lee Miringoff. He said a low turnout would favor
Jackson, whose supporters are seen as generally being more fervent
than those of the other candidates, and thus more likely to follow
through and vote.
   In a speech to the non-partisan Association for a Better New
York, Jackson never mentioned Koch by name but referred to ``those
who are inclined because of their fears to be bent toward
hysteria.''
   He went on, ``Leaders must set a high moral tone. I will not
surrender that tone to diversions.''
   However, Gerald Austin, Jackson's campaign manager, had less
restraint, saying, ``Koch is a lunatic. He's a lunatic by New York
standards.''
   The mayor, campaigning with Gore, dismissed the criticism from
the Jackson camp.
   ``So should I decline to say these things simply because he says
it's divisive?'' said the mayor. ``I mean he's not an icon. He's a
candidate. Candidates have to be able to take it and respond.''
</TEXT>
