<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KennedyFiles     04-18 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kennedy Files,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Archives to Open Police Reports on Robert Kennedy
Assassination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conspiracy theorists, scholars and a
man wounded during the 1968 assassination of Robert F. Kennedy were
waiting anxiously Monday for the release of police files on the
killing.
   ``This is a kind of vindication of citizens' efforts to force
this material out,'' said Gregory Stone, a professor on leave from
the University of Wisconsin who has devoted himself to studying
Kennedy's killing.
   Secretary of State March Fong Eu plans to open the Los Angeles
Police Department's voluminous investigative files on the
assassination Tuesday. They include some 2,500 photographs, 50,000
pages of written material and interviews with 4,000 witnesses,
officials said.
   Eu's spokeswoman, Melissa Warren, said her office had been
inundated with calls since announcing the impending release,
including many from Massachusetts, Kennedy's home state, and New
York, which he represented as a senator.
   ``There have been dozens of calls from all over the state, all
over the country, from news people, from historians and the just
plain interested,'' she said.
   Most of the material has been sealed since shortly after Kennedy
was gunned down at the Ambassador Hotel on June 5, 1968. A summary
of police files was released in 1986, but names and details then
considered sensitive were deleted.
   The summary concluded that Sirhan Bishara Sirhan, a Jordanian
immigrant, was the lone assassin. It found no evidence of a second
gunman or a conspiracy.
   The summary also concluded that Sirhan, who is serving a life
sentence at Soledad Prison for the killing, was sane and was not
under the influence of alcohol when he shot Kennedy moments after
he had claimed victory in the California Democratic presidential
primary.
   Sirhan has said he does not remember shooting Kennedy and blamed
his amnesia on alcohol.
   Although Sirhan shot Kennedy in full view of numerous
spectators, controversy arose later about how many shots were fired
and whether a second gunman was involved.
   Paul Schrade, then a Kennedy aide, suffered a gunshot wound
during the assassination. Investigators have said the bullet that
hit his head first passed through Kennedy's suit jacket. Schrade
has disputed that account as physically impossible and hopes the
released files will answer some of his questions.
   ``I'm pleased that this is happening,'' said Schrade, who fought
for years to open the files. But he said it would take months for
investigators to sort through the material and find any new
information which may exist.
   The only things withheld from disclosure, Eu said, are autopsy
photos, criminal ``rap sheets'' and fingerprint cards, juvenile
case records, internal police personnel records and records that
originated with the FBI or other non-Los Angeles police agencies.
   Microfilm copies of most documents will be sold for $275. A
complete set of materials including video and audio tapes will cost
$412.
   Copies of the materials also will be open to the public at the
archives.
   California Chief Archivist John F. Burns, who catalogued and
microfilmed the material, said the FBI would be releasing its own
file at an unspecified time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
