<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Election     04-18 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Election,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arena Protests Salvadoran Election Count</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The right-wing Arena party
filed a protest Monday with the Supreme Court, claiming the Central
Elections Council wrongly deprived it of a majority in the National
Assembly.
   A complaint filed by the Republican Nationalist Alliance, known
as Arena, said the council should have allotted it 31 of the 60
seats in the assembly.
   The council's final decision from the March 20 elections gave 30
seats to Arena and 23 to President Jose Napoleon Duarte's centrist
Christian Democratic Party.
   The election was a crushing defeat for the Christian Democrats
who had held 33 seats while Arena had only 13.
   Arena's protest claimed the elections council should have
allotted only 22 seats to the Christian Democrats instead of 23.
   Arena did not challenge the seven seats awarded to the National
Conciliation Party, which although it is conservative has said it
will align itself with the Christian Democrats to form a voting
bloc equal to Arena's 30 seats.
   The disputed legislative seat is from the easternmost province
of La Union.
   In the outgoing legislature the National Conciliation Party had
12 seats and there were two independent.
   The three-member Central Elections Council, which supervises the
vote count, had one representative from each of the major parties.
   Arena's representative had walked out of the council, claiming
the count was incorrect, but the Christian Democrat and National
Conciliation members continued with the count and announced the
results.
   All parties have agreed the dispute over the La Union seat will
not prevent the installation of the new assembly as scheduled on
May 1.
</TEXT>
