<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0676 04-18 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0676,0791</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Arabs Killed, More Protests of Al-Wazir Assassination</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs 10th graf `Official sources' to update with report and
statement</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army curfews and strikes to protest the killing
of a PLO leader paralyzed the occupied lands Monday and hospital
officials said soldiers shot two Arabs to death, including a woman
who was taking her children home.
   At least 167 Palestinians have been reported killed since riots
began Dec. 8 in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which Israel has
occupied since capturing them from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967
Middle East war. An Israeli soldier and civilian also have been
slain.
   Israel ordered the closure of Jerusalem's only English-language
magazine owned by Palestinians, alleging that it is financed and
directed by terrorist organizations. Its managing editor denied the
allegations.
   Buildings in the West Bank were draped with black flags of
mourning for assassinated PLO leader Khalil al-Wazir. Hundreds of
Palestinians paid condolence calls in Nablus to al-Wazir's cousin
during three days of mourning, said Adnan Zahran of Nablus.
   ``Nablus is a city of ghosts,'' the 30-year-old engineer told
The Associated Press by telephone the West Bank's largest city,
which was in its second day of curfew.
   Al-Wazir, also called Abu Jihad (Father of the Holy War), was
killed early Saturday by commandos who burst into his home in a
surburb of Tunis, Tunisia.
   News of the death inspired riots in the West Bank and Gaza in
which 17 Palestinians were killed and more than 100 wounded. It was
the bloodiest day in the territories since the rebellion began.
   In a message to Arabs in the occupied lands, Palestinian
Liberation Organization chairman Yasser Arafat said al-Wazir, his
chief aide and the PLO's military commander, ``fell, weapon in his
hand, to the bullets of a Mossad gang.'' The Mossad is the Israeli
secret service.
   Arafat said he had lost ``a brother, a friend, a revolutionary
companion and one of the symbols of the liberation fight of the
Palestinian people. ... The price of his death will be high.''
   Tunisian investigators concluded Israel was responsible.
President Zine el Abidine Ben Ali said Tunisia would complain to
the U.N. Security Council of the ``flagrant, premeditated
aggression against Tunisian sovereignty.''
   Israel has said nothing officially, but Israeli sources have
said the assassination was the work of Mossad, the navy and an
elite commando unit.
   In Gaza City, a 30-year-old mother of six was killed Monday
while trying to get her children indoors, away from a fight in a
nearby street between young Arabs and Israeli soldiers, her
mother-in-law said.
   Aidah Othman Totah, whose children are aged 9 months to 11
years, managed to get three inside and went looking for others,
then ``came back shouting, crying `I was wounded,''' Farida Nimer
Dib told The AP in the family's house.
   ``She fell on the floor and I held her in my arms. ... Suddenly
I saw blood coming out of her mouth. Then her arms dropped and she
died,'' Mrs. Dib said.
   The woman was buried in at a funeral attended by about 300
mourners shouting, ``Stones are as strong as guns!'' Arab witnesses
said. Soldiers dispersed them with tear gas.
   Army officials confirmed Mrs. Totah's death but said soldiers
``had nothing whatsoever'' to do with it. They said no soldiers
fired live ammunition in the area.
   The army said troopers shot and killed a 20-year-old Palestinian
during a protest at Rafah in the Gaza Strip. Arab reports
identified him as Mohammed Zereb.
   Israeli officials issued an order closing the weekly Al Awdah,
published in English and Arabic. The magazine was given until May 1
to appeal, said managing editor Elias Zananiri, who denied the
allegations of terrorist support and direction.
   His magazine is published by the same Palestinians who ran the
Palestine Press Service, which monitored the rebellion in the
occupied territories until it was closed last month.
   Army reports said 28 Palestinian refugee camps, towns or cities
were either under curfew or closed to journalists.
   Former Defense Minister Ariel Sharon applauded the killing of
al-Wazir with the comment: ``One has to knock off the murderous
heads of the terror organizations.''
   Ariel Merari, an expert on terrorism at Tel Aviv University's
Jaffee Center for Strategic Studies, said Monday the killing
appeared to be an Israeli operation. He had speculated initially
that al-Wazir was assassinated by a rival Palestinian faction.
   Three PLO leaders, including previous military commander Kamel
Adwan, were killed in 1973 by an Israeli squad that entered and
left Beirut via the sea, as the commandos in Tunis apparently did.
</TEXT>
