<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Vincent     04-18 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Vincent,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Drops Drug Charge Against Actor Jan-Michael Vincent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pills carried by actor Jan-Michael Vincent
when he was arrested last week for investigation of possessing
drugs were caffeine tablets and not illegal amphetamines,
authorities said.
   Based on laboratory tests, the district attorney's office on
Monday declined to charge Vincent with felony possession of
amphetamine, as alleged by the Sheriff's Department, said spokesman
Andy Reynolds.
   In addition, no charges will be filed in connection with the
remnants of a marijuana cigarette found in the ashtray of the car
Vincent was riding in, Reynolds said. The car was borrowed and
there was no evidence linking Vincent to the marijuana, he said.
   Deputies on patrol in Agoura Hills on Wednesday stopped a car
driven by Vincent's wife because its registration had expired,
authorities said. Vincent, 42, a passenger in the car, was arrested
after 12 white tablets were found.
   Attorney Ronald Carpol, who represents Vincent, couldn't be
reached for comment.
   Vincent, who played a tough helicopter pilot in the canceled
CBS-TV version of ``Airwolf'' and won a Golden Globe nomination for
his role in the film ``Going Home,'' lives in Malibu.
</TEXT>
