<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-Gulf 2ndLd-Writethru a0711 04-18 0928</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Gulf, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0711,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Say U.S. Attack on Oil Platforms Was `Appropriate'
Response</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Inserts 2 grafs after 19th graf bgng: ``Congress has ... to
add Hatfield accusing Senate of complacency, warning of potential
for military casualties. Picks up 20th graf pvs bgng: Sen.
Claiborne ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional leaders joined ranks Monday to
support President Reagan's decision to retaliate against Iran for a
mine attack that seriously damaged a U.S. Navy frigate in the
Persian Gulf.
   They applauded Reagan for consulting with Congress in advance of
his decision to order Navy ships destroy two Iranian oil drilling
platforms in the gulf on Monday. Several called the military action
``appropriate and measured.''
   Others said that by engaging in genuine consultation in advance
_ instead of merely informing Congress later, as he has in the past
_ Reagan may have defused a possible congressional fight over
whether he should have invoked the War Powers Act before ordering
the Navy to retaliate.
   ``There will be no fight ... as long as they keep consulting,''
said Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., the House deputy Democratic leader.
   ``The mines have been clearly identified as manufactured by the
Iranians and sown in the waters by the Iranians,'' said Senate
Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va. ``The Iranians were
carrying out terrorist acts. ... I support the decision to destroy
the (Iranian) platforms.''
   Senate Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas told his colleagues:
   ``In my view, now is the time to send only one message to our
adversaries: That the United States, the president, the Congress
and the people are united and determined to meet our
responsibilities and defend our interests in the gulf.
   ``I hope the ayatollah (Khomeini) gets that message so we can
all avoid further bloodshed and violence,'' Dole said.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, said the White House
discussions were ``very frank'' and candid and that the
congressional leaders pointed out the perils as well as the
possible benefits of taking military action.
   Wright said of Reagan: ``He is the commander in chief and when
action is taken by the United States, it certainly behooves all of
us to close ranks and to give the world a view of a nation that is
united.''
   ``It seems to me the critical thing is that what was done was
done in a measured fashion against inanimate objects to demonstrate
we had the capacity to close down Iranian oil production,'' Wright
said.
   Wright, Byrd, Dole and House Majority Leader Thomas Foley,
D-Wash., and Minority Leader Bob Michel, R-Ill., were summoned to
the White House on Sunday evening and briefed on last Thursday's
mine attack on the USS Samuel B. Roberts.
   ``For the first time, we were consulted before the executive
order was issued and before it was decided _ and that was good,''
Byrd said.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., called the U.S. response appropriate
and said Congress should not begin ``a chorus of calls for
invocation of the War Powers Act.''
   He urged lawmakers to support Reagan, wait 24 hours to 48 hours,
then evaluate whether the U.S. actions have been proper.
   ``It's clear we have a very dangerous situation,'' McCain said.
``If it begins to appear that there will be further escalation, I
think (the president) needs to talk directly to the American
people. ... The worst mistake would be for them to be kept in the
dark.''
   But Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., one of the Senate's strongest
advocates of invoking the War Powers Act in the Persian Gulf, said
the latest incidents demonstrate that by refusing to follow the
requirements of the law, the administration and Congress, ``have
evaded their obligation to develop a long-term national policy.''
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said, however, he believed the
Iranian missile attack on a U.S. warship in the gulf had exposed
Americans to hostilities and therefore had already triggered the
act's 60-day clock.
   ``Congress has a responsibility to become involved,'' Specter
said, but added that if calm is restored lawmakers may not press
the issue. ``It depends on future events as to how vigorously it
would be pursued,'' he said.
   Sen. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., who has urged that the War Powers
Act be invoked, accused the Senate of being ``lulled into
complacency'' about the gulf in recent months.
   ``I don't hear many voices calling for the War Powers
Resolution. In fact, most everybody seems to be cheering the
action. My fear is that it will take dead bodies _ the dead bodies
of U.S. servicemen _ to force us to face our responsibility,''
Hatfield said.
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, said the administration's retaliation ``was a
measured and correct response.'' But he said the War Powers Act
should have been invoked ``many months ago so that the
administration and the Congress could be working in tandem and not
at cross purposes.''
   Adams said: ``Any time you have mining, a U.S. vessel hitting
back, shelling platforms, these are certainly acts of war and the
War Powers Act should be invoked.''
   As for Reagan's action, he said, ``of course, I support
protecting our people, taking defensive actions.''
   Under the War Powers Act, hostilities involving U.S. military
forces trigger a 90-day period during which the president must
report to Congress on the situation and Congress must vote on
whether or not to keep those forces deployed. Otherwise U.S. units
must be withdrawn.
   Presidents of both parties have opposed the act as an
infringement of their powers as commander in chief.
</TEXT>
