<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CardinalO'Connor     04-18 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cardinal O'Connor,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>O'Connor Addresses AIDS Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John O'Connor
of New York on Monday addressed an AIDS conference with a plea that
victims of the incurable disease be treated with compassion and
dignity.
   ``We have 17 Catholic hospitals in the archdiocese of New
York,'' the Roman Catholic prelate said. ``I have personally urged
that any person coming to any one of these hospitals seeking
assistance because of the possibility of AIDS be treated with
absolute, total and unconditional dignity.''
   ``I spend many nights in one of those hospitals, St. Clare's,''
visiting AIDS patients, he said. ``Often, I empty their bed pans,
comb their hair or mop their brow ... I have realized more and more
that every single one is a sacred human person made in the image
and likeness of almighty God.''
   Following his address at Catholic University, the 68-year-old
O'Connor flew by private plane to Cuba.
   He is to celebrate a Mass in Santiago de Cuba Monday evening and
then go to Havana to commemorate the 200th anniversary of the birth
of the Rev. Felix Varela, a Cuban priest who spent many years in
New York and became vicar general of the archdiocese.
   O'Connor arrived in the Dominican Republic on Sunday and
baptized the 7-month-old son of a niece of President Joaquin
Balaguer.
   Before addressing the AIDS conference, O'Connor dedicated new
equipment at Robert Reid Cabral Children's Hospital and attended
ground-breaking ceremonies for the Child Jesus Children's Hospital.
   The Child Jesus facility is being built with funds provided by
the Foundation for Catholic Health Care in the Dominican Republic.
The foundation, which O'Connor helped set up last year, sponsored
the conference on AIDS.
   O'Connor will be the highest-ranking U.S. Catholic leader to
visit Cuba since Fidel Castro came to power in 1959 and established
a communist regime. Castro has recently eased restrictions on
religious activities in Cuba.
</TEXT>
