<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hijack-Kuwait 1stLd-Writethru a0643 04-18 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijack-Kuwait, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0643,0761</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sheikdom Takes Tough Stand on Hijacker Demand</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 6th: The gunmen ... with financial aid
to relatives of slain hostages and soccer team offering to replace
hostages. Pick up 7th graf pvs: A senior ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Refusal to meet the demands of gunmen who hijacked
a Kuwait Airways jetliner has become a source of national pride in
this Persian Gulf sheikdom.
   Some Kuwaitis also see it as vital to the survival of their
country, which is threatened by a 7{-year-old war between Iran and
Iraq that rages only 50 miles to the north. Iran accuses Kuwait of
aiding Iraq in the war and has attacked its main oil-export
terminal.
   ``I think Kuwait has set an example that you never, ever
negotiate with terrorists,'' said Faisal Al-Marzouk, editor of the
newspaper Al-Anbaa.
   ``I think it's unfortunate that the United States, West Germany,
France have always wanted to negotiate the release of hostages held
in Lebanon,'' he said in an interview.
   For two weeks this land of about 1.7 million residents, only 40
percent of whom are citizens, has rejected the demands of hijackers
who seized the Boeing 747 on April 5. It now is at the airport in
Algiers.
   The gunmen want Kuwait to free 17 pro-Iranians convicted of
bombing the U.S. and French embassies in 1983 in return for the
plane and about 35 hostages still held on it, including three
members of Kuwait's royal family. They have killed two Kuwaiti
passengers and have said they would massacre the rest.
   Kuwait's emir, Sheik Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah, ordered financial
aid Monday for the families of the two men slain by the hijackers.
   A government statment said the emir ordered that all outstanding
debts of the two victims and their families be written off and that
the full salaries of the slain men be paid to their families.
   In Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, a visiting Kuwaiti soccer team
offered to replace the hostages.
   Malaysia's Bernama news agency said the 52-member team,
competing for the Asian Cup, released a statement saying the
members would ``sacrifice themselves'' for their country.
   It reported the Kuwaiti team's president, Sheikh Fahad Al-Ahmad
Al-Jabar Al-Sabah, a younger brother of the emir, said the soccer
players were ready to depart for Algeria.
   A senior Western diplomat said many Kuwaitis view the hijacking
as an affront.
   ``The Kuwaitis aren't going to back down. It's a matter of
national pride,'' said another with extensive official contacts.
   Al-Marzouk, the editor, said: ``Even if they kill all the
hostages on the plane, we'll never, ever release the killers who
are here in Kuwait.''
   Several previous attempts have been made to force the release of
the 17 prisoners, who were convicted in 1984. Three are sentenced
to death.
   Lebanese extremists believed related to some of the 17 hijacked
a Kuwait Airways jetliner in December 1984 on a flight from Dubai
to Karachi, Pakistan, and force it to Tehran. The five-day ordeal
ended when Iranian security men entered the plane in disguise and
surprised the hijackers. Two of the four Americans on board were
killed by the terrorists.
   Release of the imprisoned bombers also has been set as a
condition for freeing American hostages held by Moslem extremists
in Lebanon.
   Kuwait even refused to grant Church of England envoy Terry Waite
a visa in 1985 when he asked to come and discuss his efforts to
free foreign hostages. Waite disappeared in Beirut in January 1987
and is believed held hostage.
   U.S. officials who sold weapons to Iran to try to free the
Americans are said to have pressed Kuwait briefly, but
unsuccessfully, to release the prisoners.
   Diplomats, who spoke on condition of anonymity, cited several
reasons for Kuwait's hard line:
   _ As a rich but weak country close to powerful and often hostile
neighbors, it cannot afford to become a target of blackmail.
   _ Kuwaiti officials have expressed fear that, ``if they knuckled
under ... they would put every civilized country at risk.''
   _ Fear that bowing to the hijackers would create conflict in
Kuwait between the majority Sunni and minority Shiite Moslem sects.
Kuwait is ruled by Sunnis but many of its Shiite minority are
ethnic Iranians, and Iran is predominantly Shiite.
   ``They're just not going to let their country go the way of
Lebanon,'' which has been ravaged by civil war since 1975, a
European diplomat said.
</TEXT>
