<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Demjanjuk-Reax     04-18 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Demjanjuk-Reax,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ukrainians Outraged At Conviction, Other Groups Applaud Verdict</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Demjanjuk Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOROTHY GAST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suporters of retired autoworker John Demjanjuk
said Monday that his conviction in Israel on war crimes charges
would arouse anti-Semitic feelings in America.
   ``I think people will be outraged because they know Demjanjuk is
innocent,'' said Peter Jacyk of Toronto, who helped raise money for
Demjanjuk's defense.
   ``In the long run, it will have a very negative effect on Israel
and Jews. It will definitely be long-remembered,'' Jacyk said.
   A panel of Israeli judges on convicted Demjanjuk on Monday of
war crimes, saying they had no doubt that he was the sadistic death
camp guard ``Ivan the Terrible,'' who killed 850,000 Jews during
World War II.
   Demjanjuk, 68, a Ukrainian immigrant who lived in suburban
Cleveland before being stripped of his citizenship, is scheduled
for sentencing April 25. He faces death or life imprisonment.
   Bill Liscynesky of the Cleveland suburb of Parma, who heads the
local United Ukrainian Organizations, said the conviction was
``bound to have a negative effect on the American population's view
of Israel.''
   ``The majority of Americans feel that Demjanjuk is innocent,''
Liscynesky said.
   The United Ukrainian Organization is an umbrella group for 48
Ukrainian groups in greater Cleveland that have about 20,000 active
members, Liscynsky said. He said ``telephones are probably very
hot'' spreading the word among local Ukrainians about Demjanjuk's
conviction Monday.
   More than 200 people gathered Sunday at St. Vladimir's Cathedral
in Parma, a Ukrainian Orthodox church, to pray for Demjanjuk and
his family.
   A former Cleveland lawyer who helped win Demjanjuk's extradition
to Israel in 1986 said Demjanjuk was justly treated by Israel and
deserved to be convicted.
   ``I think there was no doubt that he was given a fair trial,
that every possible defense was raised and thoroughly defended,''
said Alvin Lodish, a former Justice Department lawyer who now is in
private practice in Miami. ``There can be no doubt who John
Demjanjuk really is.''
   Demjanjuk's former attorney, Mark O'Connor of Buffalo, N.Y.,
said Demjanjuk's lawyers would need to alter their defense away
from emotionally attacking prosecutors and judges.
   ``It can't be said that he (Demjanjuk) didn't have every
opportunity to present evidence,'' said O'Connor. ``He could not
have had fairer trial.''
   The Albany, N.Y., chapter of the Holocaust Survivors and Friends
in Pursuit of Justice, which has 3,000 members across the country,
applauded the verdict.
   ``We commend the state of Israel for accepting this
reponsibility, and we hope they will continue to prosecute Nazi war
criminals who have found haven throughout the world,'' the group
said in a statement as read by Deborah Rausch, who had attended
part of the trial.
   In New York City, Abraham H. Foxman, national director of the
Anti-Defamation League, said the conviction was ``gratifying
evidence that even 40 years after the Holocaust, justice can
prevail over evil.''
   Elizabeth Holtzman, the Brooklyn district attorney, said thee
verdict sent ``the world a signal that Nazi war criminals cannot
escape.''
   As a member of Congress, Holtzman was author of an amendment
allowing for the deportation of Nazi war criminals from the United
States and barring those linked to Nazi atrocities from entering
the country.
</TEXT>
