<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0809 04-18 0859</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0809,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Irks Reporters By Refusing To Discuss Early Comment On
Gulf Action</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 14 grafs, flap over Dukakis backing off on
statement on Persian Gulf; picks up 3rd graf pvs, bgng ``Just
don't; DELETES outdated grafs 7-10 pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis, dashing across New
York Monday on the eve of the state's primary, state, backed off on
an initial statement calling the U.S. attack on Iranian oil
platforms a ``measured response.''
   The Massachusetts governor declined to comment on the Middle
East developments at two news conferences he held during a long day
of campaigning.
   But aides confirmed that he had told one reporter early in the
day that he considered the U.S. move a ``measured response.''
   Late in the day, Dukakis declined to meet with reporters on his
campaign plane who wanted to question him about the initial
statement, sending aides instead.
   Madeleine Albright, his senior foreign policy adviser, said
Dukakis altered his position on the initial attack because of
subsequent events.
   In exchanges that continued throughout the day on Monday,
American forces destroyed two of Iran's Persian Gulf oil platforms,
sank or damaged four attack boats and disabled two frigates that
fired missiles at American planes, U.S. officials reported.
   ``The feeling was that so many pieces of this story were hard to
put together, that it was hard to figure out what the whole story
was, and so he felt he didn't want to continue with the initial
statement,'' Albright said.
   Asked whether Dukakis stood by the early statement, she said,
``A combination of several series of escalations make one question
whether it was an appropriate reaction.''
   Dukakis would not come to the rear of his airplane to meet with
reporters to explain the situtation. When questioned by a reporter
getting off his airplane in New York Monday night, he referred
questions to press secretary Mark Gearan.
   During the day, Dukakis, who has been accused by rival Albert
Gore Jr. of inexperience in foreign policy matters, talked with
aides about the situation in the Persian Gulf, but said little
about the subject.
   ``We just don't have sufficient information for me to comment on
what's happened in the Middle East in the last few days, and it
would just be inappropriate for me to comment,'' he said.
   He continued to avoid the issue and spoke with extreme caution
to reporters aboard his plane on Middle East questions, including
about reports that Israel was behind the slaying of a Palestine
Liberation Organization official in Tunisia.
   Asked if he would consider such an assassination morally wrong,
he said: ``I don't want to answer hypotheticals on that. I don't
have the facts.''
   Dukakis spent Monday making stops in major television markets in
a bid to get maximum exposure just before New York's important
Democratic presidential primary. Late polls showed him leading
Jesse Jackson and far ahead of Gore.
   ``Just don't forget to vote tomorrow,'' he told workers at the
American Brass Co. in Buffalo, where he spoke to workers on the
floor of the brass mill.
   ``If we can win tomorrow with your help, we're going to be on
our way to the nomination, and I have no doubt that the Democratic
nominee for the presidency is going to beat George Bush in
November,'' he said.
   Aides continued to suggest the race in New York was tightening
between Dukakis and Jackson, although Dukakis told reporters, ``I'm
always optimistic.''
   From Buffalo, he flew back to Manhattan and a noontime crowd in
the heart of the financial district with cousin Olympia Dukakis,
the Oscar-winning actress.
   Dukakis made appearances in Syracuse, where he called for
greater drug education efforts, and Rochester, where he told a
college crowd that voter turnout was the key on Tuesday.
   Olympia Dukakis, mentioned by her cousin at nearly every
campaign stop, used Greek to praise the Massachusetts governor to a
crowd gathered on a drizzly day in the small Nassau Street mall
near Wall Street.
   ``She's given us our battle cry _ `Let's go, Mike,''' he said,
paraphrasing her words at the Academy Awards ceremony a week ago.
   Dukakis compared himself to John Kennedy as a son of
Massachusetts running for president and said, ``History is going to
repeat itself in 1988.''
   Dukakis visited Buffalo two days after throwing out a ceremonial
first pitch _ which landed in the dirt in front of the batter's box
_ at a Buffalo Bisons minor league baseball game Saturday in the
city's new outdoor baseball stadium. Back on Monday, he called the
ball park ``a terrifc example of Buffalo coming back'' and adressed
local hopes to land a big-league team.
   ``I can't make this as a commitment, but I want to say this to
you: If Michael Dukakis is elected president, I'll do what I can to
get a major league team to Buffalo,'' Dukakis said.
   At the American Brass Co. plant, he praised cooperation between
labor and management following a buy-out by management.
   He repeated his support for federal legislation, as in
Massachusetts, requiring notice before plants are closed.
</TEXT>
