<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 2245EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Novak     04-18 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Novak,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Silent Screen Actress Eva Novak Dead At 90</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Silent movie actress Eva Novak, who starred
as Tom Mix's love interest in 10 of his Westerns and did her own
stunts as well, has died after a bout with pneumonia. She was 90.
   Miss Novak died Sunday evening at the Motion Picture Country
Hospital in Los Angeles, said producer Walter Seltzer, whose wife
is a niece of the actress.
   Miss Novak and her sister, Jane, came to Hollywood from their
native St. Louis in their mid-teens to become stars of the silent
era, Seltzer said.
   Eva worked in slapstick comedies and was a bathing beauty for
Mack Sennett. Among her films as leading lady for Tom Mix were
``Sky High,'' and ``Trailin'.'' She also was the leading lady in
three films for William S. Hart.
   In those early Westerns, Miss Novak performed all her own
stunts, relying on advice from Mix.
   In 1921 she married director and stuntman William Reed, and the
couple went to Australia in the late 1920s and made a series of
Westerns there.
   She returned to the United States in the 1930s and appeared in
several talking films with such new stars as Jack Benny.
   She also played numerous parts for director John Ford, an old
friend who cast her in such classics as ``She Wore A Yellow
Ribbon,'' ``Stagecoach,'' and ``Fort Apache.'' She also played a
nun in ``The Bells of St. Mary's.''
   In 1980, when she was 82, she was assigned by the Republican
party to work in her neighborhood in Sherman Oaks on behalf of
Ronald Reagan, an old friend and fellow Screen Actors Guild board
member.
   Miss Novak is survived by her sister, Jane, two daughters, 10
grandchildren, and 15 great-grandchildren.
   A private memorial mass on Wednesday will be followed by burial
at San Fernando Mission Cemetery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
