<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 2246EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSStudent     04-18 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Student,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen Back In Public School After Furor Over AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLINTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old hemophiliac who had a a
positive test for AIDS was back in public school Monday, seven
months after a furor prompted his parents to pull him out of
classes, a school official said.
   DeWayne Mowery, who had been taking classes alone, is enrolled
at Clinton Junior High School, said Ann McRae, supervisor of
special education at Anderson County schools.
   He is expected to finish the school year there, she said.
   Health officials have said DeWayne, who has not shown symptoms
of AIDS in spite of the positive test, apparently got the virus
through contaminated clotting factor. The substance is made from a
blood component.
   Staff, students and parents there feel equipped to deal with
DeWayne's situation because they have been attending special
programs, organized by the principal, Harold Heath, to learn about
AIDS and about hemophilia, said Ms. McRae.
   Last fall, DeWayne attended Lake City Middle School for three
days, but his parents pulled him out after they said the family had
received threats.
   During that time many parents kept their children from classes,
and angry parents and students picketed the school grounds. DeWayne
was driven to a back entrance of the small school.
   Last month, Norma Mowery, DeWayne's mother, attended a hearing
in Nashville of President Reagan's AIDS commission and told the
panel she resented that her son did not have access to education
that included socializing with other children.
   She told the commission that any child ``should not have to
sneak around and go to the back door to get into school. He should
not have to be afraid for his life because he wants to learn.''
   Before Monday, DeWayne had been riding a bus alone to meet with
his teacher at an Anderson County special school. He was the only
student in the classes.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring. As of April 11, 33,060
people have died of AIDS in the United States.
</TEXT>
