<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Louise Nevelson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louise Nevelson, a artist who struggled until
she was nearly 60 to win the public's attention, died Sunday at age
88.
   Mrs. Nevelson traveled to Munich to study. Upon the rise of the
Nazis, she returned to New York to work with paint, plaster, terra
cotta, marble, aluminum, bronze and bits of wood.
   Although Mrs. Nevelson was a serious artist for half a century,
her work was largely ignored until 1958, when it was included in an
anthology at the Museum of Modern Art. Her fame grew in 1959 when,
at the age of 60, she won acclaim for her first all-white
``environment,'' titled ``Dawn's Wedding Feast.''
   She recently completed a 35-foot black steel sculpture for the
National Institutes of Health in Bethesda, Md. A show of her 1950s
work is scheduled this summer at the Pompidou Center in Paris. Mrs.
Nevelson's works are included in the collections of many major
museums and have been taken on exhibitions around the nation and
the world.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Patrick Mphephu</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patrick Mphephu, 63, the
president-for-life of Venda, died Monday.
   Mphephu was Venda's first and only president. He headed a
one-party state with strong backing from traditional chiefs and
headmen of clans. Mphephu became the territory's paramount leader
in 1950. In the 1970s, his party lost elections but retained power
by jailing its rivals.
   No foreign country has recognized Venda since it was declared a
republic in 1979. It occupies about 2,500 square miles in the
northeast corner of South Africa.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Haruo Shikanai</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Haruo Shikanai, the chairman of the Fuji Sankei
Communications Group, died Saturday of liver and kidney failure. He
was 42.
   Shikanai joined Nippon Broadcasting in 1970. He became vice
president of the radio company and managing director of Sankei
Shimbun in 1977.
   Shikanai took over the presidency of Fuji Television three years
later and was assigned to serve as the group's chairman. In 1985,
he succeeded his father, Nobutaka Shikanai, 76, senior adviser to
the Fuji group, as president of Sankei Shimbun and Nippon
Broadcasting.
   Shikanai introduced color printing for Sankei Shimbun, Japan's
fifth-largest daily with a daily circulation of 2.06 million.
   Among the holdings of Fuji Sankei Communications are Sankei
Shimbun, a nationally circulated daily newspaper; Nippon
Broadcasting Corp, a radio station; Fuji Television Network Inc.;
and 103 smaller companies including publishing houses and
production studios. The conglomerate was established in 1968.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Yuri Egorov</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yuri Egorov, 33, a Soviet-born
pianist who defected to the Netherlands in 1977, died Saturday of
meningitis.
   Egorov complained of a lack of artistic freedom in the Soviet
Union and went into hiding during an Italian tour in 1977. He
settled in the Netherlands shortly afterward.
   His concert career included appearances in Chicago, New York,
Philadelphia, Paris and Brussels.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John Reardon</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTE FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Reardon, a baritone who regularly
appeared as the opera maker ``Reardon'' in the children's public
television program ``Mister Rogers' Neighborhood,'' died Saturday
of pneumonia at the age of 58.
   Reardon's career spanned 30 years of opera and musical theater,
beginning with his Broadway appearance in ``Do Re Mi.'' At the
Metropolitan Opera in New York, he starred in many new productions,
including ``Carmen.''
   Reardon's long association with composer-conductor Leonard
Bernstein included recordings of Bernstein's ``On the Town'' and
Franz Haydn's ``Creation.'' His last public performance was March
11 with the Buffalo (N.Y.) Philharmonic Orchestra.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Stanton Delaplane</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stanton Delaplane, a Pulitzer Prize-winning
columnist for the San Francisco Chronicle, died Monday at age 80.
   Delaplane joined the Chronicle in 1936 as a reporter before
becoming a syndicated columnist. He won the Pulitzer Prize for
articles in 1941 about ``the Free State of Jefferson.'' He also won
two National Headliners awards and dozens of lesser honors.
Delaplane was also credited for introducing Irish coffee to the
U.S.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>James Wells</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James R. Wells, a longtime teletype
operator for The Associated Press in Kansas City, died Saturday. He
was 77.
   Wells joined the AP at Kansas City in 1927 and worked briefly in
the Dallas bureau in 1930 but spent most of 42 years with the AP in
Kansas City before retiring in 1972.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>James Olson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James E. Olson, whose bulldog tenacity led him
from working in manholes in North Dakota to the chairmanship of
AT&T, died Monday after a month-long battle with colon cancer. He
was 62.
   Olson landed his first job in the Bell System at age 17, when he
hauled buckets of silt out of telephone manholes in North Dakota.
The same summer he got work as a cable splicer's helper with
Northwestern Bell Telephone Co. in Grand Forks, N.D.
   Twenty-three years later, Olson had become vice president and
general manager in the company's Iowa area. He was transferred to
Indiana Bell as vice president for operations in 1970 and became
president of that company two years later.
   In 1974, Olson assumed the presidency of Illinois Bell and in
1977 became executive vice president of AT&T headquarters in New
York. He was made president and chief operating officer in June
1985 after serving as vice chairman of the board since 1979. He
became chairman in September 1986.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Eva Novak</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
