<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 2250EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BridgeProtest     04-18 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bridge Protest,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Senate Candidate Ends Vigil, Political Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OREGON INLET, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A candidate for the state Senate
abandoned his vigil on a bridge he said was threatened by erosion
and pulled out of the race Monday, saying his protest had turned
attention away from the bridge.
   ``I don't want to take away from the problem down here,'' Dan
Lawrence said as he announced he would support his rival for the
Senate, state Sen. Marc Basnight. Lawrence is a Republican and
Basnight a Democrat.
   ``I don't want even one person to feel that this was done as a
political stunt, (to) detract from the great need we have to save
this bridge and save this island,'' he said.
   Lawrence started his vigil Friday by chaining himself to a
catwalk that adjoins the 2{-mile Herbert Bonner Bridge, the only
link between the northern end of the Outer Banks and Hatteras
Island.
   He said he had not anticipated the problems that plagued his
protest, which included poor weather and a death threat on Sunday
night. Following the threat, Lawrence returned for a short time
Sunday night before going back to the bridge for the final hours of
his vigil.
   ``I'm giving up, folks. I'm going home. My family has suffered a
lot,'' he said. ``I can't take it anymore. I'm hungry.''
   Lawrence was concerned that the onslaught of the Atlantic Ocean
would lead to further erosion that would not only eat away at the
coastline, but undermine bridge supports. State Department of
Transportation officials say the bridge is not in danger of
collapse, and that periodic checks of the supports are made to
ensure that any damage can be repaired as soon as possible.
   Before the bridge was built in 1962, residents along the coast
had to rely on ferry boats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
