<NOTE>Eds: This package does not contain the following items from the
News Digest: MANAMA, Bahrain _ Gulf Rdp; WASH _ US-Gulf Rdp;
ALGIERS, Algeria _ Hijack; JERUSALEM _ Demjanjuk; NEW YORK _
Political Rdp; GREENWICH, Conn. _ Helmsley-Curse.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said its forces Monday retook the town
of Faw near the tip of a strategic Iraqi peninsula that had been
captured by Iran more than two years ago.
   Iran claimed U.S. helicopters attacked Iranian troops and Kuwait
provided a staging area to support the Iraqi offensive. The United
States and Kuwait denied the charge.
   Thousands of Iranians were killed or wounded in the two-day-old
offensive, named ``Blessed Ramadan'' after the Moslem fasting
month, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
   It was the first time Iraq took the initiative in a major ground
push since the early years of the 7{-year-old war.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army curfews and strikes to protest the killing
of a PLO leader paralyzed the occupied lands Monday, and hospital
officials said soldiers shot two Arabs to death, including a woman
who was taking her children home.
   At least 167 Palestinians have been reported killed since riots
began Dec. 8 in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which Israel has
occupied since capturing them from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967
Middle East war. An Israeli soldier and civilian also have been
slain.
   Israel ordered the closure of Jerusalem's only English-language
magazine owned by Palestinians, alleging that it is financed and
directed by terrorist organizations. Its managing editor denied the
allegations.
   Buildings in the West Bank were draped with black flags of
mourning for assassinated PLO leader Khalil al-Wazir. Hundreds of
Palestinians paid condolence calls in Nablus to al-Wazir's cousin
during three days of mourning, said Adnan Zahran of Nablus.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic Church's tax-exempt status
gives it an unfair advantage in the political battle over abortion
rights, the Supreme Court was told Monday.
   The court was urged by a ``pro-choice'' coalition to keep alive
an 8-year-old lawsuit that seeks to strip the church of its tax
exemption because of its anti-abortion lobbying.
   The suit is against the federal government, not the church.
   The justices are being asked to decide whether the suit can go
forward _ not whether the church's tax exemption should be revoked.
A decision is expected to be announced by July.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A presidential commission concluded Monday
that the U.S. air transport system is safe for the time being, but
urged appointment of a ``safety czar'' in a newly independent
Federal Aviation Administration whose officials would be insulated
from political pressures.
   ``The nation's air transportation system is safe, for now,''
said John M. Albertine, chairman of the Aviation Safety Commission
whose final report was issued after a nine-month study of the
rapidly growing airline industry.
   ``However, that safety is being maintained to an increasing
extent through delays and through what I can only characterize as
heroic efforts of air traffic controllers, airways facilities
technicians, safety inspectors'' and others, Albertine said.
   The report said there was widespread public concern about the
safety of air travel, coinciding with burgeoning technological
advances and a backlog of safety improvements waiting to be written
into government regulations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some banks opened for the first time
in six weeks Monday, but only to accept deposits, and people who
still have currency in this cash-poor economy were in no rush to
give it up.
   Business was brisk at a few major foreign banks, but slow at
institutions owned and operated by Panamanians.
   About 30 people were outside Chase Manhattan when it opened.
Virtually all were depositing checks they have been unable to cash
for 45 days because U.S. economic sanctions have dried up the money
supply in Panama, whose currency is the dollar.
   ``I'll keep my cash at home,'' said Frank Farrell, who is
retired and was depositing several dividend checks.``Later on,
maybe I'll deposit cash.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Penn State University's president
agreed Monday to drop charges against students arrested during a
sit-in protesting racial policy, but wouldn't commit new funds for
recruiting black students and faculty.
   ``Most of the students who occupied the building were motivated
by a genuine belief that immediate action was required to address
the concerns of Penn State's black community,'' university
President Bryce Jordan said in granting amnesty to the protesters.
   School admissions officials had expressed worry that the arrests
would discourage other blacks from attending the school.
   At an open meeting with his senior adminstrators and black
student leaders, Jordan defended his decision to end a 15-hour
sit-in at the university's telecommunications building April 9 by
arresting 89 protesters, most of them black students.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Artist Louise Nevelson, who struggled until she
was nearly 60 to win the public's attention, has died at the age of
88 with a reputation as one of the nation's greatest sculptors.
   Mrs. Nevelson, who had been in poor health for several months,
died Sunday at her home in Manhattan's Little Italy.
   She recently completed a 35-foot black steel sculpture for the
National Institutes of Health in Bethesda, Md. A show of her 1950s
work is scheduled this summer at the Pompidou Center in Paris.
   ``She's seen as one of the great artists of our time,'' said
Thomas Messer, director of the Guggenheim museum and an
acquaintance of the late artist.
</TEXT>
