<1ST_LINE>a a BC-History Adv24   04-18 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv24,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Adv24</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 24</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   Today is Sunday, April 24, the 115th day of 1988. There are 251
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On April 24, 1800, Congress approved a bill establishing the
Library of Congress in Washington D.C., appropriating $5,000 ``for
the purchase of such books as may be necessary.''
   On this date:
   In 1704, the first American newspaper printed on a regular
basis, the Boston News Letter, was published for the first time.
   In 1792, the French national anthem ``La Marseillaise'' was
composed by Claude-Joseph Rouget de Lisle.
   In 1877, federal troops were ordered out of New Orleans, ending
the North's post-Civil War rule in the South.
   In 1897, William W. Price began work at the Washington Star,
where he became the first reporter to cover the White House on a
regular basis.
   In 1898, Spain declared war on the United States after rejecting
America's ultimatum to withdraw from Cuba.
   In 1915, the Turkish Ottoman Empire began the mass deportation
of Armenians during World War I. Hundreds of thousands of Armenians
are believed to have died en route.
   In 1916, Irish nationalists in Dublin launched the Easter
Rising, which was put down by British forces several days later.
   In 1953, British statesman Winston Churchill was knighted by
Queen Elizabeth II at Buckingham Palace.
   In 1961, following the Bay of Pigs fiasco, the White House
issued a statement on behalf of President John F. Kennedy in which
he accepted ``sole responsibility for the events of the past days.''
   In 1962, the Massachusetts Institute of Technology accomplished
the first satellite relay of a television signal, between Camp
Parks, Calif., and Westford, Mass.
   In 1968, leftist students at Columbia University in New York
began a week-long occupation of several campus buildings.
   In 1970, the People's Republic of China launched its first
satellite, which transmitted a popular Communist Chinese song,
``The East is Red.''
   In 1986, the Duchess of Windsor, for whom King Edward VIII had
given up the British throne, died in Paris at age 89.
   Ten years ago: The survivors from a South Korean jetliner that
had been fired on and forced down after entering Soviet airspace
April 20 arrived at their destinations in Japan and South Korea,
expressing relief and anger over their close call.
   Five years ago: Austria's governing Socialists lost their
absolute majority in Parliament during national elections,
prompting Chancellor Bruno Kreisky to announce he would resign
after 13 years in office.
   One year ago: Eighteen people, including 12 U.S. military
personnel, were injured when a roadside bomb exploded in the Greek
port of Piraeus, spraying a military bus with shrapnel and debris.
The guerrilla group ``November 17'' claimed responsibility.
   Today's Birthdays: Poet Robert Penn Warren is 83. Critic Stanley
Kauffmann is 72. Actress Shirley MacLaine is 54. Actress Jill
Ireland is 52. Actress-singer Barbra Streisand is 46.
   Thought for Today: ``To change and to improve are two different
things.'' -- German proverb.
   (Advance for use Sunday, April 24)
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880418-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 0742EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-History Adv25   04-18 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv25,0453</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday, April 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   Today is Monday, April 25, the 116th day of 1988. There are 250
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On April 25, 1980, the White House announced that an attempt to
rescue the American hostages in Iran had failed, and that eight
U.S. servicemen had died in the fiery collision of two aircraft.
   On this date:
   In 1792, a highwayman named Nicolas-Jacques Pelletier became the
first person under French law to be executed by the guillotine.
   In 1859, ground was broken for the Suez Canal.
   In 1874, radio pioneer Guglielmo Marconi was born in Bologna,
Italy.
   In 1898, the United States formally declared war on Spain.
   In 1901, New York became the first state to require automobile
license plates. The fee was $1.
   In 1908, broadcast journalist Edward R. Murrow was born in Pole
Creek, N.C.
   In 1945, delegates from 45 countries met in San Francisco to
organize the United Nations.
   In 1945, U.S. and Soviet forces met at Torgau, Germany, on the
Elbe River.
   In 1959, the St. Lawrence Seaway opened to shipping.
   In 1974, military officers promising democracy ousted Portugal's
premier, Marcello Caetano.
   In 1976, Portugal held its first free parliamentary elections in
half a century, giving the Socialist Party a plurality.
   In 1982, Israel withdrew its remaining soldiers from the Sinai,
leaving the peninsula under Egyptian control as agreed to under the
Camp David accords.
   Ten years ago: The U.S. Supreme Court struck down all pension
plans requiring women to contribute larger portions of their
salaries than men, ruling that women cannot be forced to make
larger pension payments just because they generally live longer.
   Five years ago: Soviet leader Yuri V. Andropov responded to a
letter he received from Samantha Smith of Manchester, Maine, in
which the 10-year-old schoolgirl had expressed concern about
nuclear war. Promising the Soviet Union would ``never'' be the
first to use nuclear weapons, Andropov invited Samantha to visit
his country.
   One year ago: Tens of thousands of people gathered in Washington
for three days of protests against U.S. foreign policy,
particularly toward Central America and South Africa.
   Today's Birthdays: Supreme Court Justice William Brennan is 82.
Jazz singer Ella Fitzgerald is 70. Movie director-writer Paul
Mazursky (``Down and Out in Beverly Hills'') is 58. Former Harlem
Globetrotter Meadowlark Lemon is 56. Actor Al Pacino is 48. Actress
Talia Shire is 42.
   Thought for Today: ``Prophecy is the wit of a fool.'' --Vladimir
Nabokov, Russian-born author (1899-1977).
