<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   Today is Friday, April 29, the 120th day of 1988. There are 246
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On April 29, 1945, American soldiers liberated the Nazi
concentration camp in Dachau, Germany, where tens of thousands of
people had perished.
   On this date:
   In 1429, Joan of Arc entered the besieged city of Orleans to
lead a victory over the English.
   In 1861, Maryland's House of Delegates voted against seceding
from the Union.
   In 1862, New Orleans fell to Union forces during the Civil War.
   In 1863, newspaper publisher William Randolph Hearst was born in
San Francisco.
   In 1894, several hundred unemployed men known as ``Coxey's
Army'' swarmed into Washington to ask Congress for help.
   In 1913, Swedish-born engineer Gideon Sundback of Hoboken, N.J.,
patented the zipper.
   In 1916, the Easter Rising in Dublin collapsed as the Irish
nationalists who had seized control of the General Post Office
surrendered to British authorities.
   In 1946, 28 former Japanese leaders were indicted in Tokyo as
war criminals.
   In 1974, President Richard M. Nixon announced he was releasing
edited transcripts of some of the secret White House tape
recordings related to the Watergate scandal.
   In 1977, Pope Paul XI and the Archbishop of Canterbury, Dr.
Donald Coggan, participated in a Christian unity service in the
Vatican's Sistine Chapel.
   In 1985, the space shuttle ``Challenger'' lifted off with seven
astronauts and a ``mini-zoo'' of monkeys and rats.
   Ten years ago: The Soviet Union released the pilot and navigator
of a South Korean jetliner that was fired on and forced down after
entering Soviet airspace April 20, killing two passengers.
   Five years ago: Harold Washington was sworn in as Chicago's
first black mayor, vowing to freeze hiring and fire recent
political appointees to ease the city's fiscal crisis.
   One year ago: Ronnie DeSillers, a 7-year-old liver transplant
recipient whose story had prompted thousands of Americans,
including President Reagan, to lend support, died at a Pittsburgh
hospital while awaiting a fourth transplant.
   Today's Birthdays: Emperor Hirohito of Japan is 87. Movie
director Fred Zinnemann (``From Here to Eternity'') is 81. Actor
Tom Ewell is 79. Actress Celeste Holm is 69. Football coach George
Allen is 66. Poet Rod McKuen is 55. Conductor Zubin Mehta is 52.
Singer Tommy James is 41. Actress Kate Mulgrew is 33.
   Thought for Today: ``Isn't privacy about keeping taboos in their
place.'' -- Kate Millett, American feminist writer.
