<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   Today is Saturday, April 30, the 121st day of 1988. There are
245 days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   Forty years ago, on April 30, 1948, the Organization of American
States, dedicated to promoting solidarity and peace among nations
in the Western Hemisphere, held its first meeting, in Bogota,
Colombia.
   On this date:
   In 1789, George Washington took office in New York as the first
President of the United States.
   In 1803, the United States purchased the Louisiana Territory
from France.
   In 1812, Louisiana entered the Union as the 18th state.
   In 1900, Hawaii was organized as a U.S. territory.
   In 1900, engineer John Luther ``Casey'' Jones of the Illinois
Central Railroad was killed in a wreck near Vaughan, Miss., as he
stayed at his controls, trying to save the passengers.
   In 1939, the New York World's Fair, billed as a look at ``The
World of Tomorrow,'' officially opened.
   In 1945, as Russian troops approached his bunker in Berlin,
Adolf Hitler committed suicide along with his wife of one day, Eva
Braun.
   In 1945, ``Arthur Godfrey Time'' made its debut on the CBS radio
network.
   In 1947, President Harry S. Truman signed a measure officially
changing the name of Boulder Dam to Hoover Dam.
   In 1968, police ended a week-long occupation of several
buildings at Columbia University in New York as they routed
left-wing student demonstrators.
   In 1970, President Richard M. Nixon announced the U.S. was
sending troops into Cambodia, an action that sparked widespread
protests.
   In 1973, President Richard M. Nixon announced the resignations
of his aides H.R. Haldeman and John Ehrlichman, along with Attorney
General Richard G. Kleindienst and White House counsel John Dean.
   In 1975, the South Vietnamese capital of Saigon fell to
Communist forces as President Duong Van Minh announced an
unconditional surrender.
   In 1980, three gunmen seized control of the Iranian embassy in
London, seizing about 20 hostages. (British commandos stormed the
building May 5.)
   In 1980, Queen Juliana of the Netherlands abdicated on her 71st
birthday. She was succeeded by her daughter, Princess Beatrix.
   Ten years ago: Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin arrived in
the United States for a week of observances celebrating the 30th
anniversary of Israel's independence and for talks with President
Jimmy Carter and Secretary of State Cyrus R. Vance.
   Five years ago: Death claimed George Balanchine -- acclaimed as
one of the greatest choreographers of his time -- in New York at
age 79, as well as blues singer and guitarist Muddy Waters, in
suburban Chicago at age 68.
   One year ago: Pope John Paul II began a five-day visit to West
Germany. President Reagan welcomed Japanese Prime Minister Yasuhiro
Nakasone to the White House. Education Secretary William J. Bennett
called for mandatory ``AIDS'' testing for several groups of people,
including hospital patients and prison inmates.
   Today's Birthdays: Princess Juliana of the Netherlands is 79.
Actress Eve Arden is 76. Singer Willie Nelson is 55. Actor-talk
show host Gary Collins is 50. Actress Jill Clayburgh is 44.
   Thought for Today: ``All generalizations are dangerous -- even
this one.'' -- Alexandre Dumas, fils, French author and dramatist
(1824-1895).
   (Advance for use Saturday, April 30)
