<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--FilmReview Adv00   04-18 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Film Review, Adv 00,0492</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``A Time of Destiny''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sometimes a mere title can afford a negative tip-off to the
nature of a movie _ like the new Columbia Pictures release, ``A
Time of Destiny.'' What does ``A Time of Destiny'' portend? Events
leading up to the Crucifixion? Napoleon's climactic years? The last
days of John F. Kennedy?
   Then you learn that the movie concerns a blood feud in a
Basque-American family set against a World War II background. And
it becomes glaringly apparent that both the title and the film ring
false.
   The co-starring of William Hurt and Timothy Hutton indicates the
pretensions of ``A Time for Destiny.'' But Hurt has never been seen
at such a disadvantage, and Hutton's earnest efforts cannot rescue
the sodden script from sinking into a bog, just like one of the
major characters.
   The plot is almost impossible to synopsize, since it is related
in confusing flashbacks _ sometimes flashbacks within flashbacks.
The scene is San Diego in wartime. A tightly knit Basque family is
ruled imperiously by the father, Francisco Rabal. When his favorite
daughter, Melissa Leo, elopes with a GI, Timothy Hutton, the father
pursues and snatches her from the bridal chamber. Hutton pursues
them in the stormy night, and the father is drowned when his car
falls into a lake.
   The outcast son, William Hurt, turns up for the funeral. He
blames Hutton for the father's death and vows vengeance. The
husband-and-wife screenwriters, Anna Thomas and Gregory Nava (she
also produced and he directed) would have us believe that Hurt was
able to enlist and be assigned to Hutton's very same army unit,
following him into combat in Italy.
   That's only part of the film's unbelievability. Hurt tries to
kill Hutton in combat, then they seem to become buddies. But at
war's end, Hurt remembers his vow, and the final, unconvincing
battle comes at the California mission where Hutton married the
family's daughter.
   The leaden melodrama never achieves conviction, and little is
offered to explain Hurt's dementia, except for flashbacks of the
father locking his son in a barn. It's painful to witness an actor
of Hurt's stature floundering in an impossible role. It's also
distressful to see Thomas and Nava stumble after their admirable
``El Norte.''
   ``A Time of Destiny'' is rated PG-13, probably for language.
Running time: 115 minutes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
