<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0500</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House spokesman Larry Speakes quit
as chief spokesman for Merrill Lynch & Co. after creating an uproar
by admitting he had concocted quotes for President Reagan.
   Speakes said in a statement Friday that his resignation was
``the best course of action for Merrill Lynch and for me
personally. Merrill Lynch is a great firm and the industry leader,
and I've enjoyed being part of it.''
   The announcement reflected intense pressure on Speakes to resign
as head of communications at the Wall Street investment giant
because of his disclosures in a book about his tenure as White
House spokesman. He said in the book that he had attributed to
Reagan comments the president never said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation got its first big dose of inflation
this year as wholesale prices rose at an annual rate of 7 percent
in March, the government said.
   The Labor Department's producer price index rose 0.6 percent
last month, marking the biggest increase since April 1987 and more
than erasing a 0.2 percent decline in February, according to the
report released Friday.
   Falling energy and food prices that had been keeping a lid on
inflationary pressures shot upwards in March.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bad news on wholesale prices sent new inflation
jitters through the financial markets, but stock prices stabilized
a day after a $100 billion drop.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 8.29 points Friday
to 2,013.93 after plunging 101.46 points the previous day in
response to a disappointing report on the U.S. trade deficit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Production at the nation's factories, mines
and utilities edged up a sluggish 0.1 percent in March, somewhat
counterbalancing signs that inflation is reheating.
   The Federal Reserve Board said Friday that gains in production
of autos and business equipment offset declines in construction
supplies and consumer goods other than cars.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Businesses plan to increase capital spending
by 8 percent this year, raising hopes that manufacturers will
expand factory capacity enough to ease long-term inflation
pressures.
   The Commerce Department said Friday that U.S. companies expect
to spend $419.9 billion, after adjustments for inflation, on
expansion and modernization this year. If realized, that would be
the best gain since a 9.6 percent rise in 1985.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World finance leaders wrapped up a tumultuous
meeting of the International Monetary Fund with more words of
assurance to nervous financial markets and further efforts to
rescue the U.S. dollar.
   The semi-annual meeting of the 151-nation IMF, which ended
Friday, was dominated by the dollar's steep plunge after four
months of relative stability.
   In an effort to brake the nosedive, the United States and its
allies launched a multimillion-dollar intervention effort, selling
off their reserves of Japanese yen, German marks and other
currencies and buying dollars.
</TEXT>
