<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines, alarmed by the mushrooming
popularity of frequent-flier programs and their potential financial
impact, announced changes that effectively pull in the reins on
free flying.
   Other major U.S. airlines, facing potential revenue losses from
their frequent-flier programs, could well follow Friday's
initiative by Chicago-based United, the nation's largest carrier.
   The frequent-flier plans reward passengers with free tickets or
upgrades to first class after they have flown a set number of
miles. United's new program sets up a two-tier system of travel
awards.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal court judge blocked investors led by
Britain's Brian C. Beazer from proceeding with a $1.7 billion
hostile takeover attempt of Koppers Co.
   U.S. District Judge Maurice B. Cohill Jr., ruling in a suit
filed by Koppers, said Friday the Beazer group cannot solicit
shares, acquire them or exercise voting rights under the shares it
already owns.
   Cohill said the unwanted corporate suitors cannot continue with
their $60-per-share tender offer until the case is settled by a
trial.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. announced it will resume paying a
quarterly dividend and will sell off an additional $2 billion in
assets as part of its restructuring.
   At its first meeting since Texaco emerged from Chapter 11
federal bankruptcy court reorganization on April 7, the oil giant's
board of directors on Friday authorized a 75-cent quarterly
dividend, a move analysts said is intended to bolster shareholder
support for the current management team.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sheet and towel giant J.P. Stevens & Co. said
its board has backed a $1.22 billion buyout bid from a New York
investment firm, spurning a lower offer from rival fabric maker
West Point-Pepperell Inc.
   In the continuing takeover battle for the textile giant, Odyssey
Partners was offering $68.50 a share in cash for Stevens'
outstanding shares under a tender offer due to expire April 22.
   Stevens fell 50 cents a share to close at $67.62{ Friday in New
York Stock Exchange composite trading.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. Chairman Roger Smith
received at least $2.2 million for 1987 in salary, exercised stock
options and stock grants, the nation's largest automaker reported
in its proxy statement.
   Smith received $867,000 in salary, earned $513,121 exercising
stock options and was awarded a stock bonus worth $800,000 when it
was granted on Dec. 7, according to the document released Friday.
The stock, issued more than three years ago, is worth considerably
more now.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices pulled out of Thursday's steep slide with an uneven
showing Friday marked by strength in some blue-chip issues.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 101.46 on Thursday
for its fifth largest point loss ever, rose 8.29 to 2,013.93. It
finished the week with a net loss of 76.26 points.
   Bond prices tumbled and interest rates jumped for the second
consecutive session. The dollar closed mixed, while gold prices
increased.
   On other markets, oil futures advanced for the fifth straight
day.
</TEXT>
