<1ST_LINE>u f PM-AutoTalks 1stLd-Writethru f0009 04-18 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0009,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler, UAW Open Contract Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with four grafs to UPDATE with opening of talks,
picking up 4th graf pvs, ``Both sides xxx; Also moved on general
newswires</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede DETROIT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top leaders of Chrysler Corp. and
the United Auto Workers shook hands and exchanged weight jokes
today before settling down to talks on a contract covering 67,600
workers in nine states.
   UAW President Owen Bieber and Chrysler Motors Corp. Chairman
Gerald Greenwald shook hands over a conference table, as did UAW
Vice President Marc Stepp and Chrysler Vice President Anthony St.
John.
   The four joked about Stepp's efforts to lose weight but did not
discuss the negotiations before Bieber, Stepp and St. John went
behind closed doors. Greenwald said he would not take part in the
talks.
   The officials are trying to draft an agreement to replace one
expiring Sept. 14. Bargainers led by Stepp were to spend today and
Tuesday outlining the union's demands.
   Both sides will work within a pattern contract, established last
fall at Ford Motor Co. and adopted at General Motors Corp. The
contract must be fitted to the smaller Chrysler Corp., the nation's
third-largest automaker.
   The UAW also is seeking a two-year duration for the contract so
it will expire with the GM and Ford pacts in 1990. The talks, which
normally would begin in mid-July, cover wages, benefits and working
conditions.
   The pattern contract forbids plant closings not announced before
talks started and layoffs for any reason except production cuts
caused by slow sales.
   It also includes six-month studies in which managers and workers
at each plant search together for ways to make their workplaces
more efficient, including organizing workers into teams on the
assembly line.
   Harley Shaiken, a labor and technology expert at the University
of California, San Diego, said Ford and GM are more interested in
getting workers and managers to examine their plants together than
in the actual results of the studies.
   But at Chrysler, where local unions at six plants have agreed to
so-called Modern Operating Agreements and the company is pushing
for their adoption at all plants, the studies will have a different
interpretation, Shaiken said Sunday.
   ``Chrysler is smaller and it is seeking to make the turn more
rapidly in a direction Ford and GM also are headed in,'' he said.
``For Chrysler, (the studies) would be viewed as directly paving
the way for Modern Operating Agreements.''
   In an interview earlier this year, St. John pointed out the
studies as a highlight of the GM and Ford contracts.
   At plants with the agreements, managers and workers share
decisions and design jobs so they can be performed by a team of
workers. Each team member learns all tasks involved in the team's
assignment.
   Workers can increase the amount they earn by learning additional
jobs. The cross-training cuts down absenteeism costs because fewer
stand-by workers are needed. Teams inspect their own work, reducing
the need for inspectors and workers who repair mistakes.
   Chrysler agreed to early talks after its attempt to sell its
Acustar Inc. parts subsidiary sparked a bitter companywide backlash
that forced it to back down from the sale in early March.
   Also damaging workers' trust in the company was Chrysler's
decision to close a former American Motors Corp. assembly plant in
Kenosha, Wis., by year's end, idling 5,500 workers instead of
keeping them working at least five more years as originally planned.
   Chrysler's contract covers 59,500 active and 8,000 laid-off
workers in Alabama, Delaware, California, Indiana, Michigan,
Missouri, New York, Ohio, and Wisconsin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880418-0259 </DOCNO>
