<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1128EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-OilPrices     04-18 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Sharply Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices moved strongly higher today, driven
by heightened tensions in the Persian Gulf, concerns about an
upcoming OPEC meeting and technical factors, one analyst said.
   Near midday, contracts for May delivery of West Texas
Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, stood at $18.81 per
42-gallon barrel, up 44 cents from Friday's closing price on the
New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Among refined products, May contracts for wholesale unleaded
gasoline were up 1.04 cents at 53.65 cents per gallon, while
wholesale heating oil contracts were up 1.05 cents at 50.80 cents
per gallon.
   Mary T. Bergonia, an analyst at E.D.& F. Man International
Futures Inc., said ``war talk'' was mainly responsible, as traders
worried that escalating hostilities in the Persian Gulf region
might result in restrictions on supplies.
   In Washington today, the White House said President Reagan had
struck at Iranian oil platforms to punish Iran for the mine attack
that nearly sank a U.S. frigate and to warn the Iranians against
sowing new mines in the Persian Gulf.
   The Pentagon said an Iranian navy frigate responded by firing
missiles at U.S. aircraft, while an Iranian guided missile patrol
boat fired on the cruiser Wainwright. It added that the frigate was
attacked and set afire by U.S. planes and an American destroyer.
   Aside from the war action, Ms. Bergonia said traders were also
``nervous'' about a scheduled April 26 meeting between five members
of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and non-OPEC
producers.
   That meeting will be followed by a full conference by
representatives of all 13 nations in the cartel.
   Any agreement to limit output could also send prices higher.
   In addition, the analyst said, technical factors were also
supporting the market.
   Noting that the May crude contract will expire at the close of
trading Wednesday, she said traders believed that more industry
buying was likely before then.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
