<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Mixed In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mixed
today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Traders said prices were heavily influenced by the actions of
Chicago-based C&D Commodities, the largest speculative firm on the
floor of the exchange. C&D had sparked a sharp downturn in soybean
prices last Friday by selling large amounts of soybean futures and
options contracts.
   Grain futures started to rally this morning, but C&D became a
large seller once again, and prices fell.
   ``They (C&D) don't really control the market, but their
influence is real strong right now'' because of a lack of fresh
fundamental news, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   He said that in the absence of fresh news about basic supply and
demand factors, C&D's actions could have a fairly large impact on
futures prices.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 2{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.11} a bushel; corn was unchanged
to { cent higher with May at $2.03 a bushel; oats were unchanged to
1 cent higher with May at $1.61 a bushel; soybeans were { cent
lower to 1{ cents higher with May at $6.62 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .17 cent to .35 cent lower with April at 73.80
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .15 cent higher
with April at 79.52 cents a pound; hogs were .25 cent lower to .20
cent higher with April at 44.45 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .15 cent lower to .40 cent higher with May at 51.95 cents a
pound.
   Cattle futures closed mostly higher on Friday while pork futures
retreated.
</TEXT>
