<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Facet-Pennzoil     04-18 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Facet-Pennzoil,0478</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Facet, Pennzoil Announce Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Facet Enterprises, which has been fighting
off an unfriendly takeover attempt by the Prospect Group Inc.,
announced today that it has agreed to be acquired by Pennzoil Co.
in a deal worth $250.8 million.
   Pennzoil will pay $32 per share for all outstanding Facet
shares, topping Prospect's most recent offer of $27.50 apiece. The
New York-based Prospect announced it was extending its offer to 5
p.m. EDT.
   The Pennzoil offer came less than two weeks after Pennzoil
received a $3 billion cash settlement from Texaco Inc. to end their
four-year legal battle over Texaco's 1984 acquisition of Getty Oil
Co.
   But Bob Harper, spokesman for Pennzoil in Houston, said the
company had cash available for the acquisition before the
settlement with Texaco.
   ``We had been looking at this possibility for a number of weeks
prior to the settlement,'' Harper said. ``I really don't think that
you can put those two things together.''
   Harper said the board of directors and senior management of
Pennzoil will meet in June to discuss options for other
acquisitions. He said the Facet acquisition would be the largest
for Pennzoil in several years.
   Tulsa-based Facet manufactures and markets filters under the
Purolator brand name and for the private label market. It also
manufactures and markets transportation components, filters and
filtration systems and oil field production equipment.
   The agreement with Pennzoil was unanimously approved by the
Facet board of directors, Facet said in a statement.
   Under the plan, a cash tender offer by a subsidiary of Pennzoil
will commence as soon as practical for all shares of Facet common
stock at $32 per share net in cash. After completion of the tender
offer, Facet will be merged with Pennzoil's subsidiary.
   Pennzoil has informed Facet that it has sufficient cash to
complete the transaction and that there are no financing conditions
to the tender offer and merger.
   ``We are delighted that our efforts to maximize stockholders'
investment in Facet have resulted in an agreement which provides a
fair price for their shares,'' said James Malone, president and
chief executive officer of Facet.
   Randal McDonald, Pennzoil's president and chief operating
officer, said his company, as a substantial customer of Facet
``intends to operate the company as a separate entity headquartered
in Tulsa with its present employees.''
   Facet had rejected two tender offers from Prospect, including
the current bid.
   Prospect's $135.7 million cash offer was to have expired April
6, but the New York company announced a series of extensions.
   In doing so, Prospect revealed that it had been tendered since
late last year 247,170 shares of Facet common stock, an amount that
Facet said indicated shareholders were not taking advantage of the
Prospect offer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
