<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Panama-Banks 1stLd-Writethru f0024 04-18 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Banks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0024,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banks Reopen, Accepting Deposits Only</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout with banks reopening after six weeks; Also
moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banks reopened in Panama today for
the first time in six weeks but only to receive deposits. Business
was brisk but most customers appeared wary.
   Most people deposited checks, which they have been unable to
cash since the banks were closed on March 4.
   ``I'll keep my cash at home,'' said Frank Farrell, one of about
20 people lined up to make deposits at Chase Manhattan Bank when it
opened. ``Later on, maybe, I'll deposit cash.''
   A retiree, Farrell said he was depositing about a half dozen
dividend checks. Asked if he felt secure in depositing them, he
replied: ``I don't worry. Chase is solid.''
   A middle-aged Panamanian woman in the same line said she also
was depositing checks only.
   ``I need the cash to eat,'' she said.
   It was unclear when the banks would allow withdrawals.
   The banks reopened today after the National Banking Commission,
the government's bank regulator, said the banks could resume
accepting deposits and carrying out inter-bank operations.
   They were closed March 3 after a month-long run on deposits
turned into a stampede in late February when Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, the nation's strongman, dismissed then President Eric
Arturo Delvalle.
   The Reagan administration furthered the economic crisis by
imposing sanctions on Panama, including freezing Panamanian assets
in the United States, in an effort to force Noriega to leave his
post.
   Noriega, chief of Panama's 15,000-member Defense Forces, is
under federal indictment in the United States on charges of drug
trafficking and money laundering.
   The United States recognizes Delvalle as the nation's leader.
Delvalle was deposed after he ordered Noriega to step down.
   In other developments, a Roman Catholic priest on Sunday told
worshipers not to be intimidated by riot police who have crushed
demonstrations against Noriega.
   Hundreds of people stood and cheered repeatedly during the
homily by the Rev. Javier Villanueva at the Christ the King Church.
   ``There is no suffering, no blow from a truncheon or a stream of
poisonous water, nor an insult, nor criticism, nor pain that does
not form part of the suffering of Christ,'' he told about 500
people.
   On Saturday, police trucks equipped with water cannons fired a
mixture of tear gas and water at about 400 demonstrators, most of
whom were members of an opposition women's group, during a march on
the north side of Panama City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880418-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1219EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     04-18 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0451</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks weakened this morning in reaction to
falling bond prices, concern about inflation and U.S.-Iranian
fighting in the Persian Gulf.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, wobbly after a
big weekly loss, was down 11.28 points to 2,002.65 as of noon EDT.
   ``I think people are very jittery,'' said Philip C. Puccio,
senior vice president and manager of institutional trading at
Dillon Read & Co. in New York. ``There's going to be a lot of
volatility, a lot of skittishness.''
   Traders said investors still were reacting to the government's
reports last week of a higher-than-expected February trade deficit
and a jump in March wholesale prices. The reports suggested the
dollar will fall, inflation will rise substantially and the Federal
Reserve will tighten credit.
   Anxiety about inflation contributed to a selloff in bond prices
this morning that pushed yields on the 30-year issue past 9
percent, the highest level in three months. To many investors, this
made bonds more attractive and less risky than stocks.
   Rising oil prices linked to escalating violence in the Persian
Gulf also aggravated fears about inflation, traders said.
   Others said large institutional investors such as pension funds
were fearful of another large drop in the Dow average like the
101.46-point fall last Thursday, despite NYSE restraints on
computerized trading strategies that are designed to slow the speed
and magnitude of the index's movements.
   Declining issues led advances by more than 3-to-2 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 812 down, 527 up and 484 unchanged. Big
Board volume totaled 78.58 million shares in the morning vs. 132.88
million Friday morning.
   The NYSE's composite index of all listed common stocks fell 0.60
to 146.40. On the American Stock Exchange, the market value index
also fell 0.60 to 298.64.
   Oil stocks were mixed, despite a jump in petroleum prices caused
by the Persian Gulf hostilities. Amoco rose | to 78[, Chevron rose
\ to 48], Texaco fell | to 48 and Exxon fell [ to 43{.
   Pacificorp was the Big Board's most-active issue at 34, down {,
on volume exceeding 15 million shares. The heavy trading was linked
to the utility's quarterly dividend payment.
   American Telephone & Telegraph fell [ to 26{. The company said
its chairman James E. Olson died of cancer. Sears Roebuck fell ~ to
34. The retailer reported a decline in first-quarter earnings.
   On the Amex, Texas Air was among the most active issues, down ]
to 9}. The government has undertaken a broad inquiry in the airline
holding company's financial structure and the safety of its fleet.
</TEXT>
