<DOCNO> AP880418-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1245EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Goodrich     04-18 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Goodrich,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goodrich First-Quarter Earnings Up Nearly Tenfold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BFGoodrich Co. announced Monday that its
first-quarter net income increased nearly tenfold because of strong
demand for some of the company's specialty chemical products.
   In announcing the earnings ahead of the company's annual meeting
in New York, Goodrich Chairman John D. Ong noted that the massive
restructuring the former tiremaker undertook a few years ago is
``now producing the expected results.''
   Goodrich reported net income of $34.7 million, or $1.29 a share,
for the quarter, up from net income of $3.8 million, or 6 cents a
share, in the year-earlier period.
   Sales during the quarter ended March 31 totaled $588 million, up
17 percent from $485.6 million in the first quarter of 1987.
   Operating income from the company's largest business _ polyvinyl
chloride, or PVC _ jumped 126 percent, to $57.6 million from $25.5
million in the year-earlier quarter.
   PVC is used by pipe and plastics manufacturers and in siding for
homes. Though a cyclical business, PVC as well as the raw materials
used in making it currently are in short supply because of a robust
economy, the company said.
   Ong noted that Goodrich expects to complete the sale of the
company's interest in Uniroyal Goodrich within the next two months,
closing out the 118-year-old company's association with rubber
products.
   During the first quarter, Goodrich's stake in Uniroyal resulted
in a $3.3 million loss, mainly because of ``costs associated with a
reduction in salaried enrollment,'' Ong said.
   Goodrich announced in December that an investment group formed
by Clayton & Dubilier Inc. agreed to buy its interest in Uniroyal
for $225 million.
   Analysts who met with Goodrich executives before the annual
meeting noted that the additional cash, which will work to
substantially reduce the company's debt-to-capital ratio, could
make Goodrich vulnerable to a takeover.
   Ong and other executives stressed that they are actively working
to ``see where we can invest ... to enhance our core businesses.''
   One analyst who spoke on condition of anonymity said the
Goodrich management ``knows that that much cash in the bank is
dangerous.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
