<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Libya-Oil     04-18 0138</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Libya-Oil,0145</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Petroleum Investment Corporation Formed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya has formed a $500 million
investment corporation to acquire oil facilties abroad, a published
report said.
   The Middle East Economic Survey said in its Monday edition that
the company, to be known as the Foreign Petroleum Investment
Corporation, was formed by Libya's National Oil Company.
   The Nicosia, Cyprus,-based weekly newsletter, which specializes
in oil, added that the new company will act as a holding company
for two investments already made by Libya _ a 70 percent stake in
Tamoil's 100,000-barrel-per-day refinery in Cremona, Italy, and a
50 percent interest in the 80,000-barrel-per-day Coastal refinery
in Hamburg, West Germany.
   A barrel is the equivalent of 42 gallons.
   MEES said Muhammad Abd al-Jawad has been appointed head of the
new corporation. He is also chairman of Tamoil.
</TEXT>
