<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Earns-Sears 1stLd-Writethru f0112 04-18 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Earns-Sears, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0112,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sears Profit Down 37 Percent In First Quarter</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 8th graf to CORRECT that tax reform affected Allstate
sted Dean Witter; picks up 9th graf pvs bg'ng, The Coldwell ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co., the nation's largest
retailer, said today its profit for the first three months of 1988
fell more than 37 percent due to sharp earnings declines in its
retail and insurance divisions.
   Sears posted first-quarter net income of $179.5 million, or 47
cents a share, down from $287.9 million, or 75 cents a share, in
the same period a year earlier.
   Quarterly sales increased 16 percent, from $10.48 billion in
1987 to $12.16 billion, a record for first-quarter revenue, Sears
said in a statement.
   Despite a 4.6 percent increase in sales at Sears department and
specialty stores to $6.04 billion, income from the Sears
Merchandise Group fell to $18.7 million from $31.3 million a year
earlier.
   Edward A. Brennan, Sears chairman and chief executive officer,
said traditional business patterns produce the lowest sales of the
year in the first quarter while fixed costs remain constant.
   The Allstate Insurance Group reported first-quarter income of
$183.2 million, down from $246.9 million a year earlier. The
company said the results were adversely affected by the return of
normal winter weather patterns compared with mild conditions _ and
fewer claims _ a year earlier. Revenue for Allstate rose 35.5
percent, to $4.94 billion.
   The Dean Witter Financial Services Group was the company's best
performer, with first-quarter income of $15.5 million, up from $6.1
million a year earlier. The Discover Card, an all-purpose credit
card, recorded its first quarterly profit _ $6.4 million _ after
two years of heavy investment and start-up expenses.
   Tax reform accounted for $35.5 million of the decrease in income
from Allstate, Sears said.
   The Coldwell Banker Real Estate Group reported first-quarter
income of $7.5 million, down sharply from $39.3 million a year
earlier.
   Brennan said the decline in income was expected ``but this
should not be regarded as an indicator of results for the year.''
   ``We continue to be quite optimistic about the economy,''
Brennan said in a statement. ``Consumer confidence has rebounded to
a level higher than the pre-October peak. Recent employment growth
has been rapid and unemployment has fallen to its lowest level
since 1979. We expect disposable personal income to register a
healthy 7.5 percent increase in 1988 compared with 5.3 percent in
1987. This favorable atmosphere should benefit all our businesses.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880418-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1418EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     04-18 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0447</2ND_LINE>
