<HEAD>IBM Buys Stake In Metaphor Computer; Deal Includes Technology</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. has
acquired a $10 million stake in Metaphor Computer Systems and will
work with Metaphor on developing business software, the companies
announced Monday.
   Metaphor, a privately held company based in Mountain View,
Calif., will cooperate with IBM on rewriting its programs so they
will run on IBM's Personal System-2.
   Metaphor makes software that executives can use to analyze
masses of data in an easily understood graphic format. The software
runs on its own workstations, which use a microprocessor made by
Motorola Inc. The project with IBM will allow the software to run
on IBM's personal computers, which use Intel Corp. microprocessors.
   IBM's stake in Metaphor represents less than 10 percent of the
company.
