<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Steel,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Output Rose 2.2 Percent in Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel production rose to 1.987 million tons in
the week ended April 16, an increase of 2.2 percent from the
previous week's 1.945 million tons, the American Iron and Steel
Institute reported Monday.
   The industry's production amounted to 92.7 percent of capacity
during the week, compared with 90.8 percent in the previous week.
   Estimated figures for the year to date showed production at
29.629 million net tons, a rise of 29.5 percent from the 22.872
million net tons in the previous year. The steel operations of USX
Corp., the nation's largest steel producer, were shut down by a
strike during the first month of 1987.
   Production so far this year used 90.3 percent of capacity,
compared with 70.0 percent a year earlier.
   Net tonnage by district for the week ended April 16: Northeast
Coast, 295,000; Pittsburgh, 201,000; Youngstown, 126,000; Lake
Erie, 166,000; Detroit, 161,000; Chicago, 519,000; Midwest,
193,000; Southern, 224,000; and Western, 102,000.
