<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1539EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BricklinRanch Bjt   04-18 0759</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bricklin Ranch, Bjt,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auto Entrepreneur's Unpaid Bills Raise Anxiety in Little Town</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DX 3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEEKER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Malcolm Bricklin, the flamboyant
entrepreneur who brought the Yugo automobile to America, once
imported optimism to this depressed ranching town with
multimillion-dollar investments _ but worry has replaced hope as
his unpaid bills pile up.
   The town has been through this before, most recently with the
oil shale bust of 1982, when big promises and heavy spending on
expensive oil production techniques evaporated overnight.
   But Meeker's 1,800 residents don't want it to happen again, and
they hope Bricklin, who plans to sell his daring auto business,
soon will settle his debts and resume building on his lavish ranch
and youth camp 22 miles from town up the White River.
   Liens of more than $107,000 are on file against the 49-year-old
Bricklin in the Rio Blanco County Courthouse, and subcontractors
throughout Colorado's Western Slope are waiting for their money.
   ``A little guy can't carry this kind of money and I'm not sure
he understands this,'' said Neil Bratton, the owner of a Grand
Junction window company who claims Bricklin owes him a substantial
amount.
   Even Bricklin's chief aide, Pat Carfagno, admits the ranch,
where the importer hoped to establish a part-time personal
residence, owes $150,000 just in Meeker, which is in northwest
Colorado about 200 miles from Denver.
   But Carfagno said the scheduled sale of Bricklin's interests in
Global Motors for more than $20 million will free up enough cash to
satisfy western Colorado creditors and to continue Bricklin's plans
for an expensive youth camp on his property.
   Officials with Global Motors disclosed late last week that an
investor group planned to buy out Bricklin's stake in the firm,
which brought the Yugo to this country in 1985.
   ``We have been in a cash shortage and we've been honest with
people about that,'' said Carfagno, who has worked with Bricklin
for 21 years.
   ``We've run $7 million through this town in the last year,'' she
said, the bulk of it in land purchases.
   ``We're here and we're staying,'' she said.
   Townspeople hope Carfagno is right.
   Bricklin, who moved to Colorado from New York City, has suffered
some setbacks of his own. His Yugo business, although initially
successful, began to unravel as the Yugoslavian import gained a
reputation for consumer complaints. Earlier, in the 1970s, Bricklin
failed in his bid to popularize a gull-winged, plastic sports car
that bore his name.
   Lured by the idea of slow western living and spectacular
scenery, Bricklin came to Rio Blanco County in the winter of 1987.
He bought the financially troubled bowling alley in Meeker and
donated $10,000 a month to the Chamber of Commerce to promote town
events ranging from rodeos to sled dog races.
   Meeker folks say he provided jobs for many people who otherwise
would have had to leave the wide open country they love.
   But two months ago, he stopped paying his bills.
   ``I'm cautiously, skeptically optimistic,'' said Jan Hughley, a
motel owner and newly elected mayor of Meeker. ``He's done a lot
for Meeker and I hope he gets things squared away. But we have to
be careful because we've seen this before.''
   Carfagno, Bricklin and other members of the household spend
little time in Meeker. So to many, they remain outsiders, and
Eastern outsiders at that.
   Under construction at the ranch are a sprawling house, small
dams to provide ponds and waterfalls, corrals, outbuildings and a
road to the proposed youth camp.
   The house features a huge glass-enclosed swimming pool, a master
bathroom large enough to include a fireplace and a master bedroom
lined by windows that offer a panoramic view of the rushing river
and the mountains above.
   ``You gotta admit this is pretty nice,'' observed Bill Phillips,
the project engineer, who said he almost was forced out of Meeker
for lack of work until Bricklin came along.
   ``He's going to put $3 million into the camp's first-year
construction and the total probably will be $16 million to $20
million. I'm not worried,'' Phillips said.
   The camp already is being marketed in the East, at $2,900 per
child for an eight-week stint in the Rockies. A pool complex,
riding stables, tennis courts, cabins and support buildings are
planned, with the opening scheduled for June 29.
   Bricklin has offered a reduced camp rate for Rio Blanco County
children but Phillips expects few will show up.
   ``Why should they? Kids are in camp all the time just living
around here,'' he said.
</TEXT>
