<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ATVs 1stLd-Writethru a0718 04-18 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ATVs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0718,0754</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Concerned About Proposed Consent Decree</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS three new grafs for last graf pvs, Legislation to ... in
Congress., to ADD additional comments from the judge and D'Amato.
Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge expressed reservations Monday
both about signing and rejecting a consent decree to regulate
all-terrain vehicles that critics say won't reduce deaths and
injuries attributed to the machines.
   Rejecting the consent decree would force the government into
time-consuming litigation against manufacturers that would
inevitably delay imposition of any safety measures, U.S. District
Judge Gerhard A. Gesell said at a hearing on the case.
   But signing the decree would restrict the additional measures
the Consumer Product Safety Commission could take to improve the
safety of the vehicles known as ATVs, which have been blamed for
900 deaths and 300,000 injuries in the last five years, Gesell said.
   ``Is it best to move in the direction of doing what one can do
to reduce it as opposed to doing nothing about it?'' Gesell asked
during oral argument on the proposed settlement between the CPSC
and five manufacturers of the vehicles.
   The decree would ban the future sales of three-wheel ATVs unless
the manufacturers devised performance standards that would be
approved by the CPSC. It would also require warning labels on
four-wheel models and distributors would have to offer training
about the safe use of the machiens to owners of vehicles currently
in use.
   Consumer organizations and 32 states have asked Gesell to reject
the consent decree or make modifications on the grounds that it
would not protect consumers from the hazards of 1.5 million
three-wheel ATVs already in use.
   These critics say the decree is incomplete for not providing
refunds for people who already purchased the ATVs, which the
Justice Department called an ``imminent hazard'' late last year
when it announced a temporary consent decree.
   ``It is better than nothing, but it's seriously flawed,'' James
Shannon, attorney general of Massachusetts told Gesell.
   He called the machines ``some of the most dangerous consumer
products sold in this country.''
   Shannon and others criticized provisions of the proposed
settlement that would restrict the CPSC from taking further
enforcement action against ATVs during the 10 years the consent
decree is in effect.
   Gesell said ``the mechanism provided by Congress is stymied by
the consent decree.
   ``As I understand the decree, the agency represented here _ CPSC
_ is not able to issue a rule under the statute which would be in
many respects more severe'' than the sanctions imposed by the
consent decree, Gesell said.
   ``You take the agency out of the game, you can't tell me with
quite the same assurance the agency is going to continue to perform
its function,'' the judge told Howard P. Willens, an attorney
representing the manufacturers and distributors.
   Noting criticism of the CPSC as too slow to take action against
ATVs, the judge questioned the notion that the agency could be
relied upon to vigorously enforce the decree.
   ``The commission had to be led to drink, the commission wasn't
running in here with any eagerness,'' Gesell said.
   But Gesell said ``there is something to be said for a relative
degree of experimentation.''
   The consent decree, unprecedented in consumer product
regulation, could prove ``a technique that could be of great value
to consumers.''
   ``It would be ... in the public interest to have some idea if a
system like this would work,'' Gesell said.
   Gesell said he was not empowered to force the manufacturers to
give refunds to people who bought three-wheel ATVs and rejecting
the decree would result in litigation that could last several years.
   The judge, who indicated he would rule within a week, also
expressed concern that the consent decree lacked deadlines for
compliance with certain provisions and didn't provide a mechanism
for evaluating its enforcement.
   Legislation to force the manufacturers to buy back the machines
is pending in Congress. Among the sponsors is Sen. Alfonse M.
D-Amato, R-N.Y., who briefly spoke at the hearing against the
decree.
   ``I would suggest this is a wolf in sheep's clothing,'' D'Amato
said of the provisions barring further CPSC action against ATVs.
The senator suggested that Gesell modify the decree to give agency
an opportunity to take further action if deaths and injuries have
not been reduced after 12 to 18 months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
