<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-Sears Bjt   04-18 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Sears, Bjt,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sears' First-Quarter Profit Down 37 Percent</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co., beset by sluggish retail
sales and sharp declines in income from three of its four major
divisions, said Monday its first-quarter profit fell more that 37
percent from the same period a year ago.
   Sales were up 16 percent, however, and industry analysts agreed
with Sears Chairman Edward A. Brennan that the first-quarter income
should not be regarded as an indicator of results for the year.
   The nation's largest retailer reported net income of $179.5
million, or 47 cents a share, for the first three months of 1988,
down from $287.9 million, or 75 cents a share, for the year-earlier
period.
   Revenues increased 16 percent from $10.48 billion in 1987 to
$12.16 billion, a record for first-quarter revenues, Sears said in
a statement.
   Sales within the company's flagship division, the Sears
Merchandise Group, rose just 4.6 percent to $6.04 billion. Income
fell more than 40 percent to $18.7 million.
   The increase in retail sales was tiny compared to the record 47
percent advance a year earlier. Brennan said first-quarter retail
sales are traditionally the lowest of the year and blamed the
income decline on fixed operating costs.
   Income from the Allstate Insurance Group slipped nearly 26
percent to $183.2 million despite a 35.5 percent rise in revenues.
Sears said the results were adversely affected by the return of
normal winter weather patterns compared with mild conditions _ and
fewer claims _ a year ago.
   About $35.5 million of the decrease in Allstate's income was
attributed to tax-reform accounting changes, Sears said.
   The Dean Witter Financial Services Group was the company's best
performer, with first-quarter income of $15.5 million compared to
$6.1 million a year earlier. The Discover Card, an all-purpose
credit card, recorded its first quarterly profit _ $6.4 million _
after two years of heavy investment and start-up expenses.
   And the Coldwell Banker Real Estate Group reported first-quarter
income of $7.5 million, down from $39.3 million a year ago.
   Analysts said they were not surprised by Sears' drop in earnings.
   ``I don't take first-quarter earnings as indicative for the
year,'' said John Landschultz of Chicago-based Mesirow Financial
Corp.
   ``But the pressure continues to be on Sears to perform better,''
he said. ``You're getting modest sales gains and you need more.''
   In the wake of the earnings report Monday, Sears shares lost 50
cents to $34.37{ in New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Sears announced last month it was undertaking a massive
restructuring of its retail division that could trim as many as
4,000 jobs from the division's headquarters staff.
   The restructuring, which will take up to three years, was
expected to come under questioning by shareholders Tuesday at the
company's annual meeting in Chicago.
   Walter Loeb, senior retail analyst for Morgan Stanley Group Inc.
in New York, said the restructuring program was bound to help Sears
become more competitive in the retail arena.
   ``Three years is a little too long, in my opinion, but it will
be a more aggressive organization,'' he said.
   Brennan said in a statement that he was optimistic about Sears'
growth in light of recent economic indicators.
   ``Consumer confidence has rebounded to a level higher than the
pre-October peak,'' he said. ``Recent employment growth has been
rapid and unemployment has fallen to its lowest level since 1979.
We expect disposable personal income to register a healthy 7.5
percent increase in 1988 compared with 5.3 percent in 1987. This
favorable atmosphere should benefit all our businesses.''
</TEXT>
