<HEAD>Speakes Wants To Rebuild Credibility</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires as part of AM-People.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House spokesman Larry Speakes,
who resigned from his top post at Merrill Lynch & Co. in the wake
of the disclosure that he'd made up quotes for President Reagan,
now says his ``No. 1 goal in life'' is to restore his credibility.
   ``I had no idea that (the quote fabrication) was a problem ... a
major problem,'' Speakes said in an interview published Monday in
the Washington Post. ``It was something I wanted to tell about, but
I wasn't ... saying it was the thing to do. I thought people would
understand that in retrospect I didn't condone it.''
   Speakes stepped down Friday as senior vice president for
communications for Merrill Lynch in the wake of the uproar created
by the disclosure in his book ``Speaking Out.''
</TEXT>
