<DOCNO> AP880418-0295 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1726EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-18 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pound at Six-Year High Against Dollar; Gold Prices Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British pound advanced again Monday, hiting
a six-year high against the dollar as an outbreak of fighting in
the Persian Gulf heightened the importance of the North Sea oil
fields.
   Gold prices rose. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
bid of $458.75 for a troy ounce of gold as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from
$455.25 late Friday.
   The pound began gaining ground in London and continued its
advance in New York, moving firmly beyond the $1.90 level against
the dollar.
   While the pound had touched this level recently, it had not
finished that high 1982, said John McCarthy, vice president for
foreign exchange at Irving Trust Co.
   The sharp move in the pound prompted the Federal Reserve to
enter the market to sell pounds and buy dollars, said Ian Spence,
chief dealer at Manufactuers Hanover Trust Co.
   Traders said the pound was boosted by fresh tension in the
Persian Gulf, where U.S. forces destroyed two Iranian platforms in
retaliation for an Iranian mine attack that damaged a U.S. frigate
on patrol in international waters.
   ``People are focusing on the fact that there may be a boost in
oil prices, and that will benefit Great Britain because of its
North Sea oil fields,'' Spence said.
   The pound has come to be regarded recently as a
``petrocurrency,'' and any potential boost in oil prices would
support the currency.
   In London, the pound traded at $1.9015, more expensive than
Friday's $1.8890. In New York it cost $1.9050 to buy one pound,
more expensive than Friday's $1.9004. Traders said the pound was
slightly stronger against other major currencies.
   The dollar finished mixed against other currencies, but its
overall tone was relatively stable. Traders said the Persian Gulf
activity offered nominal support for the dollar.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.35 yen to close at 123.78. But later in
London, it rose to 124.42 yen from Friday's close of 124.13. In New
York, the dollar rose to 124.23 yen from 123.80 on Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York included: 1.65975 West
German marks, down from 1.66095; 1.3735 Swiss francs, up from
1.3725; 5.6370 French francs, up form 5.6345; 1,233.375 Italian
lire, up from 1,232.625, and 1.23205 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2333.
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday's rates,
included: 1.6615 West German marks, up from 1.6605; 1.3745 Swiss
francs, up from 1.3720; 5.6410 French francs, up from 5.6325;
1.8630 Dutch guilders, unchanged; 1,234.37 Italian lire, up from
1,232.50, and 1.2322 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2335.
   Gold prices jumped higher. On New York's Commodity Exchange,
gold closed at $459.40 a troy ounce, up from $455.90 on Friday.
   In London, gold traded at $459.25 a troy ounce late Monday,
higher than Friday's late bid of $456.25. In Zurich, the bid price
was $458.50, up from $455.50 late Friday, when the market closed at
midday for a holiday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.03 to close at a bid $457.98.
   Silver was quoted on New York's Comex at $6.422 a troy ounce,
down from $6.455 on Friday. In London, the metal traded at a bid
price of $6.49 a troy ounce, unchanged from Friday bid price.
