<HEAD>Manville Reports First-Quarter Earnings Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manville Corp. on Monday reported its first
quarter net income fell by 16.6 percent from the year-earlier
period, which had been boosted by one-time gains.
   The Denver-based building products company said its first
quarter profit was $35.7 million, or $1.23 per share, down from
$42.8 million, or $1.52 per share, in the first quarter of 1987.
   First quarter 1987 results included $9 million in gains from the
sale of two real estate ventures.
   Sales in the quarter ended March 31 rose to $502.1 million from
$475 million in the same period a year ago, the company said.
   ``Despite severe competition in most construction segments,
Manville's overall performance continues to be strong,'' said Tom
Stephens, Manville's president and chief executive officer.
   He attributed Manville's first quarter results to the
performance of the forest products division and the effects of
stronger international currencies.
   ``Excluding the non-recurring gain on the sale of our real
estate holdings, 1988's operating performance was higher than the
record first quarter of 1987,'' Stephens said.
   Manville filed for reorganization under Chapter 11 of the
federal bankruptcy act on Aug. 26, 1982, because it was faced with
billions of dollars worth of lawsuits claiming damage from exposure
to asbestos made by Manville.
   The federal bankruptcy court approved the company's
reorganization plan in December 1986, but the plan cannot be
implemented until all appeals by claimants are addressed.
</TEXT>
