<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-18 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0827</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gold Futures Surge on Persian Gulf Conflict</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold futures prices rose Monday on expectations that an outbreak
of fighting in the Persian Gulf could drive oil prices and
inflation higher, but analysts were skeptical about the chances for
a sustained rally.
   On other markets, energy futures advanced; most livestock and
meat futures declined; grains and soybeans were mixed; and
stock-index futures rose.
   Gold for June delivery settled above $460 a troy ounce on the
Commodity Exchange in New York for the first time this month. But
the settlement price of $461.70 was well below the day's high of
$464, an 11-week high.
   Silver and platinum also jumped in early trading, but an
afternoon selloff pushed their settlement prices below Friday's
final prices.
   The prospect that military action between the United States and
Iran in the Persian Gulf could disrupt crude-oil shipments and
drive oil prices higher was seen as a positive factor for the
inflation-sensitive metals, analysts said.
   But brief skirmishes such as Monday's U.S. Navy attacks on
Iranian oil platforms and military vessels often have an ultimately
negative impact on the precious metals, said Craig Sloane, metals
analyst in New York for Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   ``You get a knee-jerk response that's very quick in terms of
people rushing in and buying the metals,'' he said. ``But once you
reach the point where the buying can't sustain itself, the sellers
come in and it ends up being more damaging to the metals prices
than being positive.''
   Gold settled $3.20 to $3.80 higher, with the contract for
delivery in June at $461.70 a troy ounce; silver was 2.7 cents to
3.5 cents lower, with May at $6.44 a troy ounce.
   Crude-oil futures also fell back on the New York Mercantile
Exchange after a morning rally that pushed the contract for May
delivery to $18.92, just short of the important $19-a-barrel level.
   ``The market clearly reacted to the increased tension in the
Persian Gulf and the U.S.-Iran clash,'' said Andrew Lebow, an
analyst in New York with ED&F Man International Futures Inc.
   The setback apparently was motivated partly by technical factors
and partly by statements from Saudi Arabia and Kuwait that they
would not reduce their production of crude oil unless non-OPEC
producers also agreed to cut production, Lebow said.
   OPEC has invited some non-OPEC producers to meet next week to
discuss production levels.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 15 cents to 26 cents
higher, with contracts for May delivery at $18.52 a barrel. Heating
oil was .48 cent to .83 cent higher, with May at 50.50 cents a
gallon; unleaded gasoline was .64 cent to .73 cent higher with May
at 53.30 cents a gallon.
   Cattle and pork futures were pressured by profit-taking on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Cattle futures advanced above recent highs early in the session,
sold off on profit-taking, then recovered to finish only slightly
lower than Friday's final prices.
   Hog futures ran into some technical weakness late in the day,
analysts said. On the fundamental side, weights of slaughtered
animals have been relatively high and the market is still awaiting
a seasonal drop in supplies.
   ``I think there is this perception that near-term supplies won't
give you much to be optimistic about,'' said Philip Stanley, an
analyst in Chicago for Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc.
   Live cattle were .77 cent lower to .13 cent higher, with April
contracts at 74.10 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to
.60 cent lower, with April at 79.07 cents a pound; hogs were .50
cent lower to .10 cent higher, with April at 44.80 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .40 cent lower to .35 cent higher, with
May at 51.65 cents a pound.
   Soybean futures prices closed substantially higher on the
Chicago Board of Trade. Corn also advanced, while wheat futures
declined slightly.
   The soybean market showed its underlying strength by rallying
despite fairly heavy selling early in the session by speculative
funds, analysts said.
   ``We're in a bull market and the market just doesn't want to go
down,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc.
   Wheat was pressured by speculative selling and reports of
beneficial weekend rains in southern wheat-growing states, he said.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents lower to 1{ cents higher, with May
contracts at $3.11\ a bushel; corn was { cent to 1} cents higher,
with May at $2.03} a bushel; oats were 2\ cents to 4} cents higher,
with May at $1.64} a bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents to 7 cents
higher, with May at $6.66 a bushel.
   Stock-index futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
where the contract for June delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500
index settled .45 point higher at 259.25.
</TEXT>
