<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks weakened Monday on fears about inflation
and U.S.-Iranian shootouts in the Persian Gulf, although the market
recovered much of the loss in the late afternoon and ended the day
mixed.
   Volume remained light however, suggesting most of the trading
was done between professional brokerages. Many analysts said a
broad range of investors remained reluctant to get into stocks.
   ``I don't see any institutional rush to buy them,'' said Robert
O'Toole, manager of over-the-counter trading at Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. ``Nobody on the face of this earth can tell which way
this market's going for the rest of the week.''
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, still wobbly from a big
drop last week because of an unexpected jump in the trade deficit,
was down about 12 points through much of the session but held just
above the 2,000 level.
   The widely watched barometer closed at 2,008.12, down 5.81
points. Most broader indices of stock values fell slightly.
   ``Traders were trading with each other,'' said William King,
head trader at Nikko Securities Co. International in New York.
``Otherwise, it's really been a sleepy day.''
   Escalating violence between Iranian and American forces in the
Persian Gulf indirectly influenced Wall Street by pushing up oil
prices, which aggravated pre-existing fears of higher inflation and
rising interest rates.
   The impact was first felt in the bond market, where yields on
some 30-year issues surpassed the 9 percent barrier, the highest
levels in three months. This made bonds more attractive to many
investors and raised the prospect that stocks could suffer sharp
declines if bond yields continue to rise.
   Gaining and losing issues were about even on the New York Stock
Exchange, with 771 up, 765 down and 460 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 144.65 million shares, sharply lower than the 234.16
million shares traded in the previous session.
   Speculative takeover-related buying helped boost some stocks.
Rumors surfaced that the Haft family of Maryland was preparing an
offer for retailing giant F.W. Woolworth & Co., which rose 2 to 55.
   Armtek rose 2 to 30[ after Italy's Pirelli group agreed to buy
Armtek's Armstrong tire unit for $190 million in cash. Facet rose
3{ to 31] after Pennzoil agreed to buy the company for $32 a share,
topping a rival bid from Prospect Group.
   Oil stocks were mixed despite a runup in petroleum prices
incited by the Persian Gulf fighting. Amoco rose ~ to 78], Atlantic
Richfield fell ~ to 87{, Chevron fell { to 47| and Kerr McGee rose
{ to 37[.
   American Telephone & Telegraph fell \ to 26]. The company said
its chairman James E. Olson died after a monthlong battle with
cancer.
   Among other notable blue chips, Merck fell 2[ to 157}, Bethlehem
Steel rose 1 to 21, General Electric fell { to 39{ and DuPont rose
2\ to 84].
   Nationwide turnover in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 167.77 million shares.
   The Wilshire Associates 5,000 Equity Index, the market value of
5,000 NYSE, American and over-the-counter issues, totaled $2.587
trillion, off $3.49 billion from Friday.
   The NYSE index of all listed issues fell 0.23 to 146.77.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials fell 0.63 to 302.05,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index fell 0.56 to 259.21.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index rose 1.68
to 300.92. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market closed at 375.10, up 1.20.
