<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MotorolaChip     04-18 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Motorola Chip,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Motorola Announces 10 Supporters For New Chip</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorola Inc. unveiled a new line of
microprocessor chips on Monday that use a simplified set of
commands for extra speed and introduced 10 companies that will use
the line.
   The 88000 line of microprocessors is Motorola's entry into a
battle with Intel Corp., Advanced Micro Devices Inc., Sun
Microsystems Inc. and other companies that make or design the tiny
chips that serve as the ``brains'' of personal computers and work
stations.
   Among the companies that said they will use the 88000 in future
products were Data General Corp., Northern Telecom Inc., Convergent
Technologies and Tektronix Inc.
   Motorola, based in Schaumburg, Ill., said its chip was up to
five times as powerful as other chips based on the stripped-down
principles of Risc, an acronym for reduced instruction set computer.
   The company said it will work with Data General on developing a
version of the 88000 that uses a design called emitter-coupled
logic for extra speed. The version will allow performance of up to
100 million instructions per second by 1991, they said.
</TEXT>
