<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FoodPrices     04-18 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Food Prices,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers' Share Of Food Dollar Continues Decline In 1987</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers continued to get a declining share of
the consumer food dollar in 1987, an Agriculture Department report
said Monday.
   A selected market basket of grocery items used by economists to
track price changes for food commodities showed that farmers
received an equivalent of 29 cents for each dollar spent by
consumers on those items.
   The farm value share of the retail price of food in the market
basket has declined one percentage point _ a penny of each dollar
spent _ since it averaged 34 percent, or 34 cents, in the 1984
calendar year.
   According to USDA records going back to 1913, when farmers got
46 percent of the food dollar, the annual share has been at record
low levels the last three years _ 31 percent in 1985, 30 percent in
1986 and 29 percent in 1987.
   Previously, the low mark was a farm value share of 32 percent
during 1932 and 1933 in the depths of the Depression. It rose to
more than 50 percent during World War II and for a few years after.
   With 29 percent of the retail cost of market basket going to
farmers, that means the remaining 71 percent went to those who
handle raw food products after they leave the farm.
   The market basket contains average quantities of domestically
produced food bought in grocery stores, excluding non-alcoholic
beverages, and fish and seafood.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880418-0304 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 2035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Allegheny     04-18 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Allegheny,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allegheny International Slows Losses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. said Monday that
improved performance in its consumer products division helped stem
its losses in the second quarter to $4.5 million, compared with a
loss of $38.5 million in the same period a year ago.
   The Pittsburgh-based firm said record sales in its barbecue
grill and lawn and patio furniture lines coupled with strong
performance in its Latin American businesses contributed to the
improvements.
   Allegheny International reported quarterly sales of $254.7
million, up from $225.1 million in the year-ago period. Operating
earnings reached $19 million from $15 million.
   For the first six months, Allegheny International reported net
earnings of $2.7 million on sales of $511 million. That compares
with a net loss of $204.2 million on sales of $447.7 million for
the first six months of 1987.
   Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Oliver S. Travers said
customers and vendors have given ``excellent support'' during the
company's reorganization under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy
code, so ``we are focusing our primary attention on the financial
restructuring of the company.''
   Allegheny International manufactures and markets small household
appliances, electric blankets, lawn and patio furniture and
barbecue grills, many of which are sold under the Sunbeam and Oster
brand names.
