<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1818EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Pennzoil-Facet 2ndLd-Writethru f0269 04-18 0737</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pennzoil-Facet, 2nd Ld - Writethru, f0269,0760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pennzoil Acquiring Facet Enterprises</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs Tulsa, Okla.-based... to UPDATE with
Prospect extending its tender offer through Thursday. Picks up 4th
graf, Pennzoil informed...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennzoil Co. on Monday announced plans to pay
$250 million in cash for an oil field equipment company, but said
the purchase had nothing to do with the $3 billion it recently
received to settle its four-year legal battle with Texaco Inc.
   Under the agreement, which was unanimously approved by the board
of directors of Facet Enterprises Inc., a cash tender offer of $32
per share by a newly created Pennzoil subsidiary will commence as
soon as practicable, Pennzoil spokesman Robert Harper said.
   Tulsa, Okla.-based Facet had been fighting off an unfriendly
takeover attempt by the Prospect Group Inc., which extended its
latest offer of $27.50 per share through 5 p.m. EDT Thursday. Facet
had rejected two tender offers from the New York-based company.
   Pennzoil informed Facet that it has on hand sufficient cash to
complete the transaction and that there were no financing
conditions to the tender offer and merger.
   ``We believe Facet's management is a vital resource and a
crucial part of this transaction,'' said Randal B. McDonald,
Pennzoil's president and chief operating officer.
   ``We are hopeful the present management will continue in their
positions.''
   Facet manufactures and markets filters under the Purolator brand
name and for the private label market. It also manufactures and
markets transportation components, filters and filtration systems
and oil field production equipment.
   Pennzoil intends to operate Facet as a separate entity and keep
its headquarters in Tulsa, McDonald said.
   ``We are delighted that our efforts to maximize stockholders'
investment in Facet have resulted in an agreement which provides a
fair price for their shares,'' said James Malone, president and
chief executive officer of Facet.
   ``In addition, we are confident that a combination with a
company having the stature and financial resources of Pennzoil will
be beneficial to our employees, suppliers, customers and
community.''
   The acquisition of Facet is on the heels of a $3 billion payment
from Texaco that ended their courtroom battles over Getty Oil Co.
   But Harper said the company had cash available for the
acquisition before the settlement with Texaco.
   ``We had been looking at this possibility for a number of weeks,
prior to the settlement,'' Harper said. ``I really don't think that
you can put those two things together.''
   Earlier this month, Texaco agreed to pay Pennzoil $3 billion to
end the litigation and to allow the White Plains, N.Y.-based oil
giant to emerge from nearly a year under federal bankruptcy court
protection.
   After the money was transferred into Houston-based Pennzoil's
bank account, Pennzoil executives said they hadn't decided on
long-term plans for the sum.
   ``We're going to look and have been looking for some time'' at
ways to invest the money, Pennzoil Chairman J. Hugh Liedtke said.
   Warren Shimmerlik, an industry analyst at the New York office of
Merrill Lynch, said Facet appeared to be a logical fit for Pennzoil.
   ``It's a distribution and you can add something to it. You can
add some value and eliminate a lot of cost and apparently that is
what appeals to Pennzoil,'' he said.
   Shimmerlik and Charles Andrew of the New York investment firm of
John S. Herold & Co. each said they were not sure if there was any
link to the Texaco payment.
   ``This is so small, relative to the magnitude to the money they
got. I don't know if I'd call it the beginning of a spree,'' said
Andrew.
   ``Pennzoil states that by reinvesting the money they got from
Texaco into oil and gas properties, they can postpone any payment
in taxes. I don't think this (the Facet merger) would qualify, so
it may be this is not related to the money from Texaco,'' Andrew
said.
   In November 1985, a Houston jury shocked Texaco by agreeing that
Texaco had wrongfully interferred in a planned Pennzoil-Getty
merger and awarded Pennzoil $10.53 billion in damages _ the largest
civil award in U.S. history.
   Texaco appealed. A state appeals court upheld the verdict, but
reduced the $3 billion in punitive damages to $1 billion.
   On April 12, 1987, Texaco filed for bankruptcy protection,
saying it had to do so to avoid posting a potentially runious bond
to continue its appeal of the judgment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880418-0306 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1835EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Earns-Banks 2ndLd-Writethru   04-18 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Banks, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0582</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout to UPDATE with Continental Illinois earnings
and edit</NOTE>
<HEAD>Chase Manhattan Reports 164 Percent Increase in First-Quarter Net</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the nation's largest bank holding companies _ Chase
Manhattan Corp. and Continental Illinois Corp. _ on Monday reported
a sharp increase in their first-quater profits.
   Meanwhile, Great Western Financial Corp., based in Beverly
Hills, Calif., and the nation's second-largest savings and loan
association, said its first-quarter earnings fell 37 percent.
   Chase, the nation's second largest banking company, said net
income totaled $277 million, or $3.09 a share, up 166 percent from
$104 million, or $1.12 a share, in the year-earlier quarter.
   Continental Illinois, ranked 15th, said it netted $68.5 million,
or 28 cents a share, up 59 percent from earnings of $43.1 million,
or 16 cents a share, in 1987.
   Great Western reported first-quarter earnings of $56.1 million,
or 45 cents a share, down from restated 1987 first-quarter earnings
of $89.4 million, or 71 cents a share.
   Chase said its net income was boosted by the sale of its
securities information subisidiary Interactive Data Corp., the sale
of a branch office building in Paris and federal income-tax
benefits.
   Excluding these items, net income for the quarter would have
been $116 million.
   Total assets during the quarter averaged $95.7 billion, compared
with $97 billion in the year-earlier quarter. Chase's sale of its
subsidiary Nederlandse Credietbank N.V. on Dec. 31, 1987, reduced
1987 year-end total assets by about $4 billion.
   The provision for possible credit losses was $150 million during
the quarter, down from $160 million in the year-earlier quarter.
Chase said the continuing non-accrual status of loans to Brazil and
Ecuador reduced first-quarter net interest income by $53 million.
   Net interest income during the quarter amounted to $732 million,
up from $721 million in the year-earlier quarter. Total interest
expense was $1.46 billion, up from $1.26 billion.
   Other operating income for the quarter was $633 million, up from
$426 million in the year-earlier period. Operating expenses
amounted to $856 million, up from $840 million in the first quarter
of last year.
   Chase noted that a strong performance by its foreign-exchange
trading operation and increased fees and commissions were partially
offset by a decline in gains from the sales of investment
securities.
   Continental Illinois attributed its increase in earnings partly
to the settlement of a portion of Continental's pension-plan
obligation.
   By purchasing an annuity for a portion of that obligation,
Continental was able to realize gains on pension assets that had
appreciated, said company spokeswoman Holly Anderson.
   Continental said the remainder of first-quarter income resulted
from improved performance in the core businesses _ lending, fees
and trading _ of the holding company's Continental Illinois
National Bank & Trust Co.
   Continental said total revenue _ the sum of net interest revenue
plus fees, trading and other sources _ rose 13 percent to $275.7
million from $244.3 million a year ago.
   The comany said it lowered its provision for loan losses to
$10.4 million from $13.5 million last year.
   Great Western said its provision for loan losses was $19.5
million, down from $23 million. Total new loans increased to $2.3
billion from $2.2 billion in the year-earlier quarter, it said.
   Net interest income amounted to $201 million, down from $216
million in the year-earlier period. Interest expense amounted to
$485 million, up from $427 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
