<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Computer,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Apple Profit Up 135 Percent; NCR, Tandy Also Advance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Apple Computer Inc. said Monday its profit jumped 135 percent in
its latest fiscal quarter on a 51 percent rise in revenue, leading
a list of computer makers that announced improved results.
   Among other companies, profit was up 20 percent at NCR Corp. and
27 percent at Tandy Corp.
   Apple said it had an after-tax profit of $79.7 million, or 61
cents a share, in its second fiscal quarter ended April 1, up from
$33.9 million, or 26 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to
$867.2 million from $575.3 million.
   It was the third consecutive quarter that Apple, based in
Cupertino, Calif., had sales increases of more than 50 percent.
   ``Apple is succeeding in business markets,'' said Delbert W.
Yocam, Apple's chief operating officer. ``Acceptance for Macintosh
products continues to increase on a worldwide basis.''
   For the first six months of its fiscal year, Apple said its
profit rose 21.8 percent to $201 million, or $1.53 a share, from
$92.3 million, or 71 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose
15.4 percent to $1.91 billion from $1.24 billion.
   NCR, based in Dayton, Ohio, said its net profit rose to $74.1
million, or 88 cents a share, in the three months ended March 31,
compared with earnings of $61.5 million, or 65 cents a share, a
year earlier. Revenue rose 14 percent to $1.28 billion from $1.12
billion.
   Domestic orders declined, compared to the first quarter of 1987,
but foreign orders showed a strong gain, propelled partly by the
advantage of a cheaper dollar, NCR said.
   Tandy, based in Fort Worth, Texas, said its profit rose to $64.1
million, or 72 cents a share, in its third fiscal quarter ended
March 31, from $50.4 million, or 56 cents a share, a year earlier.
Revenue rose 8 percent to $839.1 million from $776.9 million.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Tandy's profit
rose 31 percent to $259.1 million, or $2.89 a share, from $197.9
million, or $2.20 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 10 percent
to $2.98 billion from $2.72 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
