<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AMR-Film     04-18 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AMR-Film,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airline Ordered to Pay $10.5 Million to Film Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines Inc. was ordered Monday to pay
$10.5 million in damages to a New York film company that won a
federal court breach of contract suit against the airline.
   Attorneys and a spokesman for American Airlines said the
Dallas-based airline would appeal the verdict.
   At issue was a contract between American and Robehr Films Inc.
calling for the airline to show short travelogue films along with
feature films on flights to New York, Honolulu, Los Angeles, San
Francisco, Dallas and Chicago. The travelogues contained segments
by advertisers based in the six cities.
   Robehr Films sued American in U.S. District Court for breach of
contract and fraud, claiming American did not show the films and
knowingly reported false viewrship figures.
   Joseph Gorayeb, the attorney representing Robehr Films, said his
client was insolvent as a result of the airline's breach of
contract.
   American Airlines, a unit of AMR Corp., countersued for $500,000
it claimed it was owed.
   A jury found in favor of Robehr on the breach of contract
complaint and ordered American to pay $10.5 million in damages, but
found for the airline in the fraud complaint. The jury voted in
favor of Robehr in American's countersuit.
   Kenneth Steinthal, the attorney representing American Airlines,
said the the damage award was ``ludicrous'' and would be fought.
Steinthal said there was nothing in the record to support such a
high damage award, and nothing to indicate the plaintiff lost any
money.
   The airline will ask Judge Richard J. Daronco on April 28 to set
aside the verdict as being unsupported by evidence, Steinthal said.
   Al Becker, a spokesman for American Airlines in Dallas, said of
the ruling: ``We obviously will be filing the appropriate motion to
have the decision overturned, and we are confident of a favorable
ruling, ultimately.'' He declined further comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
