<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Kraft     04-18 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Kraft,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kraft Net Income Earnings Down 22 Percent In First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kraft Inc. reported Monday that its first
quarter net income declined by 22 percent from a year earlier,
although profit in the year-earlier period was boosted sharply by a
one-time accounting change.
   The multinational food company posted first-quarter net income
of $118.3 million, or 90 cents a share, compared with $151.6
million, or $1.11 per share, a year ago.
   The year-earlier quarter included a $45.2 million gain resulting
from a change in accounting methods. Excluding the impact of the
change, Kraft's first quarter 1987 profit then would have been
$106.4 million, or 78 cents a share.
   Profit from continuing operations rose by 14 percent, the
company said.
   First quarter sales rose to nearly $2.9 billion from about $2.5
billion last year, the company stated.
   Sales within Kraft's largest division, the U.S. Consumer Food
group, increased 9 percent to $1.2 billion.
   Kraft also reported sales gains in its cheese, dairy, frozen
foods, commercial foods, food service, food ingredients and
international foods operations. Sales in the grocery products
divison were essentially unchanged.
   Kraft Chairman John M. Richman said Kraft's results benefited
from a lower tax rate, productivity improvements and a share
repurchase program that had reduced the company's common shares
outstanding by 4 percent as of March 26.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
